0	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	Red Cross repatriates Moroccan PoWs from Western Sahara
1	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	The international Red Cross on Wednesday repatriated 100 Moroccan prisoners of war who had been held by Polisario Front separatists who want independence for Western Sahara, the Sahrawi SPS news agency reported.
2	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	Polisario announced the release of the prisoners in a gesture of goodwill to mark a Muslim feast day on February 11.
3	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	The Moroccan government says more than 1,100 soldiers captured by the Polisario Front during clashes in the Western Sahara between 1975 -- when the disputed territory was annexed by Morocco on gaining independence from Spain -- and the early 1980s are still detained by the politico-guerrilla movement.
4	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	The men repatriated Wednesday by the International Committee of the Red Cross were freed by Polisario, which has proclaimed a Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic (SADR) in the disputed territory, after intervention by Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar.
5	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	A Moroccan newspaper close to the government, Le Matin, dismissed the Polisario announcement as "political marketing" and "cynical blackmail".
6	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	The PoWs still in Polisario hands are in sprawling prisoner of war camps in the Tindouf region of Algeria, across the border from the disputed territory, where the United Nations has for more than a decade run up against obstacles from either side to its efforts to organise a referendum on self-determination.
7	AFP_ENG_20030226.0513.LDC2007T07	In January 2002, the Polisario Front freed 115 Moroccan troops following intervention by Aznar, and five months later another 101 men were released after similar moves by German secretary of state for foreign affairs Juergen Chrobog.
