36	AFP_ENG_20070102.0312.LDC2009T13	The money was allegedly paid as a bribe to Saddam Hussein's regime to secure contracts as part of the UN-supervised food-for- oil programme which ran from late-1996 to 2003.
37	AFP_ENG_20070102.0312.LDC2009T13	The programme allowed the Iraqi government to sell limited amounts of oil to purchase essential goods to alleviate the effects of sanctions on the civilian population.
38	AFP_ENG_20070102.0312.LDC2009T13	In late December, state prosecutors in Munich said they had opened an investigation into German oil giant Linde, which faces similar accusations over the food-for-oil programme.
39	AFP_ENG_20070102.0312.LDC2009T13	An investigation ordered by UN Secretary General Kofi Annan found in 2005 that more than 2,000 companies from 60 countries bribed Saddam Hussein's government to be allowed to take part in the programme.
