318	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Britain takes centre stage at Beethovenfest in Bonn
319	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	The Beethovenfest, Bonn's annual tribute to its most famous son, will this year focus on the composer's links with Britain, the organisers announced on Tuesday.
320	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Under the motto "Joy -- Beethoven and the British cultural sphere", the annual month-long festival will showcase British artists, conductors and orchestras.
321	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	It will trace the links between Ludwig van Beethoven (1770-1827), one of world's most popular and best-known composers, and the musical, cultural and political life of Britain at the time.
322	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	It was the musical impresario and concert organiser Johann Peter Salomon (1745-1815) who first brought Beethoven's works to London in the early 1800s.
323	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	He had already been responsible for establishing the fame of Austrian composer Franz Joseph Haydn (1732-1809) in Britain.
324	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	One of Beethoven's friends and pupils, his former copyist and secretary Ferdinand Ries (1784-1838), commissioned a number of works from the composer when he became director of London's Philharmonic Society in 1813.
325	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	One of those commissions eventually became Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, nowadays known as the Choral Symphony (1824).
326	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	And it is the finale of that symphony, based on Schiller's "Ode an die Freude" (Ode to Joy), that provides the motto for this year's festival.
327	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Beethoven also wrote a patriotic symphonic work, "Wellingtons Sieg oder die Schlacht bei Vittoria", celebrating the Duke of Wellington's victory over the French at the Battle of Vitoria in Spain in 1821.
328	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	The work makes use of the anthems "Rule Britannia" and "God Save the King".
329	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Works by British composers will feature highly on the programme of this year's festival.
330	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	As well as musical giants such as Henry Purcell, Edward Elgar and Benjamin Britten, there will also be works by contemporary composers Thomas Ades, Harrison Birtwistle, Brian Ferneyhough and Jonathan Harvey.
331	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	The official opening gala concert will be a performance of Elgar's Serenade for Strings and his Enigma Variations, as well as Beethoven's violin concerto, by the Philharmonia Orchestra under British conductor, Sir Andrew Davis.
332	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Other British ensembles performing some of the 61 concerts between August 24 and September 23 include the BBC Symphony Orchestra, the Choir of King's College, Cambridge, the Academy of St. Martin's in the Field and the Hilliard Ensemble.
333	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	And perhaps one of the main highlights of the festival will be a performance of Britten's War Requiem in Bonn's "Beethovenhalle" concert hall on September 12.
334	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	The Beethovenfest dates back to 1845 when the Beethoven Monument on Bonn's Muensterplatz was unveiled and a three-day music festival was held in honour of the composer's 75th birthday.
335	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Among the guests were some of the leading composers of the age, including Hector Berlioz, Louis Spohr and Franz Liszt.
336	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	The modern version of the festival was initiated in 1931 and held every two to three years.
337	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	Since 1999, the festival has been an annual event.
338	AFP_ENG_20070306.0516.LDC2009T13	In previous years, the festival has focussed on Beethoven's influence on the music and culture of countries such as France and Russia.
339	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	British lawmakers back fully elected House of Lords
340	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	British lawmakers voted Wednesday to reform the upper chamber of parliament, the House of Lords, to make it fully elected for the first time in its 600-year existence.
341	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Members of the lower House of Commons voted by a margin of 113 votes for what would constitute a complete overhaul of the House of Lords and pave the way for one of Britain's most radical constitutional changes.
342	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The vote, which passed 337 to 224, will not pass into law, but the result is expected to inform government thinking when it draws up legislation for reform later this year.
343	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	MPs also voted by a majority of 280 to remove the remaining hereditary peers from the House of Lords.
344	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Hereditary peers survived Blair's first attempt to reform the chamber in 1999.
345	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Commons leader Jack Straw presented MPs with a total of nine options by the government, all of which they could back or reject.
346	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Among the options rejected were abolishing the second chamber altogether
347	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	a fully-appointed Lords
348	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	and partially-elected options at 20, 40, 50 and 60 percent.
349	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	They did back a proposal for an 80 percent elected House of Lords but by a margin of only 38 votes -- significantly smaller than the vote backing totally elected chamber.
350	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Prime Minister Tony Blair's government had favoured a 50 percent elected chamber.
351	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Blair himself voted in favour of a 50-50 split between elected and appointed peers (members of the House of Lords) but did not take part in the other votes, his office said.
352	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	A previous vote on reforming the House of Lords in 2003 ended in stalemate after lawmakers rejected all the options on offer.
353	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Blair backed keeping a wholly- appointed second chamber.
354	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	A police probe was launched last year into whether Blair's Labour and other parties illegally offered seats in the Lords in return for financial donations -- the "cash for honours" row which is plaguing his last weeks in power.
355	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Straw said Wednesday's vote was a "historic step forward on an issue which has been a matter of debate for decades" which could transform the Lords into a more dynamic and active law-making body.
356	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The Lords scrutinises and revises government legislation but is often seen by the public as an undemocratic "retirement home" for former MPs or a place for the privileged titled classes or political appointees.
357	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	"The House of Commons has broken the deadlock.
358	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	It is a dramatic result in the history of the British Parliament," Straw said.
359	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The Lords itself will vote on the issue next week, he added.
360	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The government will then consider its next move in discussion with all parties.
361	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	But already opponents assessed that very little will happen.
362	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The former leader of the main opposition Conservative Party, Iain Duncan Smith, said the vote for a fully-elected chamber was a "brilliant parliamentary tactic" designed to muddy the waters on reform.
363	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The vote came amid claims from a Labour peer in the House of Lords, Lord David Lipsey, that making it an elected body could cost more than one billion pounds (1.5 billion euros, 1.9 billion dollars) per term.
364	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The former economics editor of the weekly Sunday Times newspaper said this "plausible" estimate, based on official figures, was a conservative one and could rise with inflation.
365	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	The government, which refused to include costs in its initial white paper proposals, dismissed the figures as "preposterous... back-of-an-envelope calculations."
366	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Currently about 746 peers can sit, speak and vote in the House of Lords, which dates back to the 14th century.
367	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	Some 615 of them have been appointed for life and 92 inherited their seats.
368	AFP_ENG_20070307.0556.LDC2009T13	It also features 26 Church of England archbishops and bishops and 12 Law Lords -- members of Britain's highest appeal court.
