996	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	"For centuries they (the prime minister and executive) have exercised authority in the name of the monarchy without the people and their elected representatives being consulted," Brown told parliament.
997	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	Such authority had "no place in a modern democracy", he said, and by transferring the powers to parliament, it would make a "more open 21st century British democracy which better serves the British people".
998	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	"The government will now consult on a resolution to guarantee that on the the grave issue of peace and war it is ultimately this House of Commons which will make the decision," he said.
999	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	Brown also proposed greater transparency in the intelligence services, with the creation of a new National Security Council bringing together domestic and overseas security with development and community relations.
1000	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	To do so would send out a "clear message" that at all times Britain "will be vigilant and we will never yield to addressing the terrorist threat", he added.
1001	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	It would also help "co-ordinate military, policing, intelligence and diplomatic action and also to win hearts and minds in this country and round the world".
1002	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	But it was his proposal for a British bill of rights -- codifying people's existing entitlements -- and/or a written constitution for the first time in the country's history that is likely to generate the most debate.
1003	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	Unlike other countries, Britain's constitution as it stands is an uncodified body of law and largely consists of written legal precedents, international treaties, parliamentary conventions and royal prerogatives.
1004	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	Brown, who is keen to promote individual responsibility and a sense of British identity, said the starting point should be the country's shared values.
1005	AFP_ENG_20070703.0537.LDC2009T13	"There is a case that we should go further still than this statement of values to codify, either in concordat or in a single document, both the duties and rights of citizens and the balance of power between government, parliament and the people," he explained.
