1659	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Malaysia's "kopitiam" revival serves up competition for Starbucks
1660	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Move over Starbucks.
1661	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Traditional Malaysian "kopitiam" are making a comeback, serving cups of local-style brew and traditional fare as Malaysians discover a taste for nostalgia.
1662	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Kopitiam -- the word means "coffee shop" in the Hokkien dialect of ethnic Chinese in Malaysia -- were originally found in shophouses in villages and towns across the country, serving up coffee and breakfast.
1663	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Usually crowded, noisy and rather grimy, they were popular places to grab a quick drink and cheap street food.
1664	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Modern kopitiams have retained the old-fashioned marble-topped tables, wooden chairs and chunky crockery, but now they are to be found in the cavernous air- conditioned shopping malls of the capital Kuala Lumpur.
1665	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	And with their thick brewed "kopi," they are holding their own against the cappuccinos and macchiatos offered by foreign coffee chains that exploded onto the Malaysian scene in the late nineties.
1666	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	City-dwellers are rediscovering kopitiam fare such as soft-boiled eggs eaten with soya sauce and a dash of pepper, and bread toasted over a charcoal fire and slathered with salted butter and kaya, a rich coconut and egg jam.
1667	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"I grew up with this.
1668	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	This is very nostalgic for me," said Maran Subramaniam as he sipped a cup of aromatic kopi and munched on kaya toast at Old Town White Coffee outlet in downtown Kuala Lumpur.
1669	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"The coffee is cheaper than Starbucks but that's not the only reason.
1670	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	I just like it," said the 31-year-old executive, dressed in a crisp shirt and tie.
1671	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The new kopitiams also serve local favourites such as nasi lemak, a coconut flavoured rice with a fiery sambal or chilli paste, fried anchovies and egg on the side, and laksa -- noodles in a spicy broth.
1672	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	One popular kopitiam chain is Kluang Station which in the past two years has opened four outlets around suburban Kuala Lumpur, as well as one in southern Malacca.
1673	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The chain is based on the famous coffee shop at the railway station in Kluang town in southern Johor state, opened in 1938 by the great-grandfather of the chain's owner Phun Jun Jee.
1674	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Phun credits his grandfather with maintaining the heritage of the original shop, where the family patriarch worked from the age of eight, and which is now in the hands of the third generation, Phun's uncle.
1675	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The coffee served at Kluang Station is made with beans roasted and ground the same way it has always been prepared.
1676	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"We make coffee the traditional way.
1677	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The coffee beans are roasted with sugar and fat in the form of butter.
1678	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	It makes the drink smoother," Phun said.
1679	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The kaya at Kluang Station is also from a recipe handed down by his grandfather.
1680	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"My granddad used to make kaya in an old milk can and he would stir it over the fire and that's all the kaya he would use in one day," Phun said.
1681	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"Now, my kaya production has come up to four drums every three days.
1682	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Each drum uses about 1,500 eggs.
1683	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	It has gone from a small amount in a tin can to enough to fill your bathtub."
1684	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Phun has also tried to recreate the atmosphere of the original kopitiam at the train station.
1685	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"I took almost everything I could capture from the original colonial train stations -- the wire mesh windows, the station sign boards, the wood finish.
1686	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	I brought Kluang out of Kluang into Kuala Lumpur," he said.
1687	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	As nostalgia fans the growth of modern kopitiams, some of the old coffee shops remain but no longer play a significant role in society -- except in small towns far from Malaysia's glittering capital.
1688	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	This correspondent's father, who as a child had helped his own father run a kopitiam in the 1940s in Taiping in northern Perak state, has lived in Kuala Lumpur for almost 40 years.
1689	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	"The new kopitiams are for the young people.
1690	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	The atmosphere at these modern kopitiams is different.
1691	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	It doesn't give a sense of nostalgia for old timers like us," Loh Thiam Ghee said.
1692	AFP_ENG_20071130.0563.LDC2009T13	Phun has plans to expand but says he will stick to urban areas.
