2708	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Football: 'Old Lady' stadium with a Nazi past
2709	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Vienna, which chose to revamp a 77-year-old stadium rather than build a new one for the Euro, will host the June 29 final in a venue that was once the site of Nazi propaganda and racial experiments.
2710	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	The Ernst Happel stadium, originally named Prater stadium after the area of Vienna in which it is located, opened in 1931 for the second Workers' Olympiad after 23 months of construction.
2711	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	A "utopia made of steel, glass and concrete," the sleek structure by German architect Otto Ernst Schweizer was then considered the most modern stadium in Europe.
2712	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	The venue, which was home to the celebrated Austrian Wunderteam of the 1930s, originally held 60,000 at a time when men still wore hats to games.
2713	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	It was later increased to 90,000 in the 1950s, before standing places were abolished.
2714	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Renovated in 1986, the stadium was renamed after legendary Austrian coach Ernst Happel in 1993 and is now a protected landmark.
2715	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	But the affectionately nicknamed "Old Lady," which underwent further restoration in preparation for the Euro at a cost of 36.9 million euros (58.2 million dollars), also served a more sinister purpose during the 1930s.
2716	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	On May 1, 1934, marching schoolchildren paid tribute to Austro- fascist Chancellor Engelbert Dolfuss at the stadium, in a pompous Labour Day spectacle during which he proclaimed a new constitution, effectively turning Austria into an authoritarian state.
2717	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Four years later, on April 3, 1938, the stadium hosted the so- called Anschluss Spiel, or "annexation match," following Austria's occupation by Adolf Hitler's Germany on March 12.
2718	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Staged by Nazi propagandists as a reconciliation between two parts of the Reich that belonged together, the game - one week before an April 10 referendum, in which Austrians would overwhelmingly vote to join the Third Reich - nevertheless saw Austria defeat Germany 2-0, before an array of Nazi high officials.
2719	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	A year later on September 10-11, 1939, the stadium took on a new role as the German Gestapo locked up over 1,000 Jewish men there on the ground that the prisons were full.
2720	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	Josef Wastl, the then-director of the anthropology department at Vienna's Natural History Museum, examined some 440 detainees, taking measurements of their bodies and features for an "Anthropology of Jews" report, with photos, hair samples and plaster masks of their faces.
2721	AFP_ENG_20080529.5003.LDC2009T13	The prisoners were sent to Buchenwald concentration camp on September 30 and business resumed as usual on the following day, as the stadium once again played host to a football game.
