2799	AFP_ENG_20080705.0237.LDC2009T13	Beijing has accused the Dalai Lama of fomenting unrest in the Tibetan region that erupted on March 14 after four days of peaceful protests against Chinese rule.
2800	AFP_ENG_20080705.0237.LDC2009T13	China has ruled Tibet since 1951, a year after sending troops in to "liberate" the region.
2801	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Berlin mulling measures to attract skilled foreign workers
2802	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Germany plans soon to adopt measures aimed at relieving a shortage of qualified workers in certain sectors by attracting foreign candidates, an official spokesman said Monday.Although the ministry spokesman did not provide details, the confirmation came after a newspaper said Saturday that authorities were mulling an "index of worker needs."
2803	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	The report said officials could poll 7,000 companies each month to determine what kinds of skills were needed in the coming six months and adapt the granting of work vias accordingly.
2804	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	A spokesman for the Labour Ministry "neither denied, nor confirmed" the report but acknowledged that the search for a "control system to identify needs" was "the reflective framework within which we are proceeding."
2805	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Government spokesman Thomas Steg said the subject had been discussed intensively, in particular between the social democrat labour minister and his conservative counterpart at the interior ministry.
2806	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	A proposition was expected to be presented to the full cabinet on either July 16 or 23, Steg added.
2807	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Certain sectors of the biggest European economy, notably high- tech firms, are handicapped by a serious shortage of engineers, programmers and qualified technicians.
2808	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	The national engineering federation said last month that around 100,000 engineering posts were vacant throughout Germany.
2809	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Measures taken by the government to date have been judged too restrictive by the business sector and have not noticeably improved the situation.
2810	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	All the same, the government was expected to extend the period before which non- skilled workers from Eastern Europe could come freely to Germany, a measure that German businesses would like to see abandoned.
2811	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	When the European Union extended eastwards in 2004, Germany obtained permission to maintain its ban on foreign workers until 2009, and possibly two years longer.
2812	AFP_ENG_20080707.0320.LDC2009T13	Labour Minister Olaf Scholz has "a certain sympathy for an extension," owing to substantial unemployment levels, his spokesman said Monday, but "with an exception for skilled workers."
2813	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	'Bird's Nest' replaces Mao on Olympic note: central bank
2814	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	China's iconic "Bird's Nest" National Stadium will replace communist hero Mao Zedong on a special currency note to be issued on Tuesday for the Beijing Olympics, the country's central bank said.The People's Bank of China said in a weekend statement on its website that it would issue six million Olympic 10-yuan (1.5-dollar) notes.
2815	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	On one side of the note is an image of the National Stadium, known as the "Bird's Nest" because of its interlocking mesh of steel, according to images of the currency posted on the website.
2816	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	Above the stadium -- the main venue for next month's Games -- is the dancing-man emblem for the 2008 Olympics.
2817	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	Both the picture of the Bird's Nest and the emblem are set against the backdrop of the Temple of Heaven, one of the country's best-known landmarks.
2818	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	The images will replace a portrait of Mao, who founded communist China in 1949 and whose face adorns all modern Chinese bank notes.
2819	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	But older, smaller denomination notes are still in circulation without his image.
2820	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	The last time Mao's image was removed from a Chinese currency was for the 2000 millennium celebrations.
2821	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	At that time, the central bank replaced Mao's portrait on a 100-yuan note with a dragon.
2822	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	The other side of the Olympic note features the famous ancient Greek marble statue of a discus-thrower, Discobolus, portraits of athletes and the numerals "2008."
2823	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	On normal notes an image of the famous Three Gorges waterway in southern China features on that side.
2824	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	The waterway has recently been controversially dammed.
2825	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	Watermarks and other technologies are to be used in printing to prevent counterfeiting of the notes, the bank said.
2826	AFP_ENG_20080707.0579.LDC2009T13	The notes, predominantly a greenish-blue with a splash of red, are slightly larger than the ordinary 10-yuan notes, which are a more sombre grey and black.
