4998	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	Arrest in Saddam execution video brouhaha, U.S. says former leader dignified to the end.
4999	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	2007-01-03 19:53:46 UTC
5000	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	BAGHDAD, Iraq -- An Iraqi official announced on Wednesday the arrest of a witness to Saddam Hussein's hanging who allegedly recorded the event on a cell phone camera, while an adviser to the prime minister said two guards present were in custody.
5001	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	A U.S. military spokesman, meanwhile, said the tumultuous execution would have gone differently had the Americans been in charge.
5002	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	Maj. Gen. William B. Caldwell also said that Saddam had been dignified and courteous to his American jailers to the moment when he was handed over to the Iraqis outside the execution chamber.
5003	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	The spokesman said no Americans were present for the hanging.
5004	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	The leaked and unauthorized cell phone video, in which some of those present can be heard to taunt Saddam in the final moments of his life, set off an uproar both inside and outside Iraq.
5005	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	The storm of criticism prompted the U.S. to publicly distance itself and Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki to launch the investigation that led to Wednesday's detentions.
5006	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	"In the past few hours, the government has arrested the person who videotaped Saddam's execution.
5007	APW_ENG_20070103.1074.LDC2009T13	He was an official who supervised the execution and now he is under investigation," said a key al-Maliki adviser, who spoke on condition of anonymity because he was not authorized to release the information.
