5617	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Former New York Times reporter to take stand in CIA leak trial
5618	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	WASHINGTON 2007-01-30 10:36:26 UTC
5619	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Journalists will take center stage Tuesday at the CIA leak trial as Special Prosecutor Patrick Fitzgerald begins calling reporters as witnesses.
5620	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Fitzgerald said Judith Miller was to take the stand Tuesday, the first time the former New York Times reporter has testified publicly against the man she went to jail to protect as a source.
5621	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Vice President Dick Cheney's former chief of staff, I. Lewis "Scooter" Libby, is accused of perjury and obstruction for lying about conversations he had with journalists about outed CIA operative Valerie Plame.
5622	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Prosecutors want to show that Libby lied to investigators about his conversations with journalists regarding Plame, who believes she was outed as retribution for her husband's criticism of the Bush administration's prewar intelligence on Iraq.
5623	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	The original source of the leak, former Deputy Secretary of State Richard Armitage, has already confirmed his role and Libby is not charged with the leak.
5624	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Miller spent 85 days in jail for refusing to cooperate with Fitzgerald's investigation and reveal her conversations with Libby.
5625	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	She retired from the Times in November 2005, declaring that she had to leave because she had "become the news."
5626	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Prosecutors say Libby discussed Plame -- the wife of prominent Iraq war critic Joseph Wilson -- with Miller three times.
5627	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Two of those conversations occurred before Libby says he first remembered learning Plame's identity from another reporter, NBC newsman Tim Russert.
5628	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Libby now says his memory failed him when he spoke to Russert.
5629	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Russert said Monday that he did not tell Libby about Plame.
5630	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	"I was not and never have been the recipient of the leak," Russert told an audience in Oklahoma City.
5631	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Such discrepancies are at the heart of Libby's trial.
5632	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Previous witnesses, including former White House press secretary Ari Fleischer, have testified they had conversations with Libby about Plame before his conversation with Russert.
5633	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	After Miller ultimately decided to testify, saying Libby had given her permission to do so, the Times published an article describing Miller as a rogue reporter who battled with editors and colleagues.
5634	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Like so many other government witnesses in the case, Miller's credibility will be an issue under cross-examination.
5635	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	She made some inconsistent statements in her grand jury testimony, defense attorneys say.
5636	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Journalism groups have criticized Fitzgerald for calling reporters as witnesses and demanding they discuss conversations with sources.
5637	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Miller's notes likely will be used as evidence, and Fitzgerald is expected to call two other reporters -- Russert and Matthew Cooper of Time magazine -- during the trial.
5638	APW_ENG_20070130.0577.LDC2009T13	Miller shared in a Pulitzer Prize for reporting on terrorism, but her relationship with the Times was strained when it was discovered that her reporting on the existence of weapons of mass destruction in Iraq -- the Bush administration's primary reason to go to war -- was built on faulty intelligence.
