5641	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Dutch troops will not participate in destruction of poppy crops in Afghanistan
5642	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands 2007-01-30 12:33:20 UTC
5643	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Dutch soldiers serving in the NATO force in Afghanistan will not take part in the destruction of opium poppy crops because it is counterproductive to efforts to build public support for reconstruction, a government minister said.
5644	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	The minister of development, Agnes van Ardenne, said late Monday that the ultimate purpose of Dutch participation in the NATO stabilization force in Afghanistan is to promote reconstruction.
5645	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	"That's only possible if the population is working with us, but the population won't do that if people see that we, as it were, are playing along with the game of destroying the income stream, the only income stream of very many farmers," Van Ardenne said on the television program Nova.
5646	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	The cultivation of poppies -- used to produce opium, morphine and heroin -- reached record levels in Afghanistan in 2006, and U.S. officials have focused attention on plans to destroy the crop.
5647	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Opium sales are believed to help fund the Taliban, but also may make up more than a quarter of the country's economy, according to a World Bank study published in November.
5648	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Opium production from poppies in Afghanistan last year rose 49 percent to 6,700 tons, enough to supply 90 percent of the world's heroin, according to the U.N.
5649	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	NATO's International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan, which recently increased in size to 32,000 troops, works together with the Afghan government to carry out reconstruction projects in the country's provinces.
5650	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Until now, ISAF's focus has often been on peacekeeping, but it plans major pushes on both quelling the Taliban insurgency and reconstruction efforts this spring.
5651	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Washington hopes ISAF will actively participate in poppy eradication projects, which have so far been ineffectual.
5652	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	In a blow to the U.S. anti-drug plan, Afghan President Hamid Karzai said earlier this month he would not approve a Colombian- style spraying program to eradicate the poppies, ordering them plowed under instead.
5653	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	U.S. company DynCorp International Inc. had hoped to win a contract to carry out the spraying.
5654	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Afghan officials said the Cabinet was concerned about the impact of herbicides on humans, legitimate crops and animals.
5655	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	The ministers also likely feared a violent backlash from rural Afghans protecting their livelihood.
5656	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	In a second blow to the U.S. plan, Ardenne said she would advise the governor of Uruzgan province to ignore Karzai's directive to destroy crops in the absence of a viable alternative.
5657	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	The Netherlands currently has around 1,900 soldiers in Afghanistan, most in the southern province of Uruzgan.
5658	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Ardenne has just returned from a three-day visit to Dutch troops.
5659	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Earlier this month, U.S. Ambassador to Afghanistan Ronald Neumann said the country has eradicated 1,483 acres (593 hectares) of poppies so far this year -- compared to none by the same time last year.
5660	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Still, that's only a fraction of the 407,000 acres (162,800 hectares) of poppies that were cultivated in 2006, including 173,000 acres (69,200 hectares) in Helmand province alone, according to U.N. figures.
5661	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Asadullah Wafa, the governor of Helmand, said he approved of Karzai's decision.
5662	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	"There is another way to eradicate, like launching operations through all the districts, and I hope the international community will give us tractors and provide more troops to destroy poppies," he said.
5663	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	Uruzgan, adjacent to Helmand in the South, produces less than 10 percent of the country's poppy crop, according to the World Bank study.
5664	APW_ENG_20070130.0743.LDC2009T13	In a December visit to Kabul, John Walters, the top U.S. anti- drug official, warned that Afghanistan could turn into a "narco- state" unless "giant steps" were made toward eliminating poppies.
