6500	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	MORGANTOWN, West Virginia 2007-03-16 21:05:06 UTC
6501	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Long-struggling steelmaker Wheeling-Pittsburgh Corp. posted an expected fourth-quarter loss Friday, announcing a hit of $18.1 million (euro13.58 million).
6502	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	That translates to a loss of $1.20 (euro.90) per share for the period ending Dec. 31, 2006, compared with a net loss of $23.4 million (euro17.56 million), or $1.61 (euro1.21), in the same period the previous year.
6503	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Net sales totaled $332.3 million (euro249.38 million) on 431,325 tons of steel products shipped for the quarter, compared with $356 million (euro267.17 million) on 527,336 tons of steel shipped in the same period the previous year.
6504	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	The average selling price per ton was $770 (euro577.86), compared with $675 (euro506.57) per ton the year before.
6505	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	For the year, Wheeling-Pitt reported a profit of $6.5 million (euro4.88 million), or 44 cents per share, compared with a year- end loss of $33.8 million (euro25.37 million), or $2.37 (euro1.78) per share, in 2005.
6506	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Investors began bracing for the losses last fall, when privately held Illinois steel distributor Esmark Inc. seized control of the company in a proxy fight.
6507	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Almost immediately, Esmark executives warned it would take until spring -- at least through the first quarter -- to turn around deep financial problems for the company that had twice survived bankruptcy but struggled to turn a profit.
6508	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	"We are in the infancy stage of the first chapter of our turnaround," said James Bouchard, chairman of Wheeling-Pitt's board and chief executive of Esmark.
6509	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Wheeling-Pitt shares fell 45 cents, or 1.84 percent, to close at $24.06 (euro18.06) on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
6510	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	To try to soften the bad news, Wheeling-Pitt announced it will end its reliance on a $250 million (euro187.62 million) federally guaranteed loan on April 1, 2008, nine years earlier than expected, by refinancing the balance.
6511	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	An initial payment of $37.5 million (euro28.14 million) will be made Monday on the balance of $187.4 million (euro140.64 million), said Craig Bouchard, president of both Esmark and the Wheeling-Pitt board of directors.
6512	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	The rest would be refinanced after Esmark and Wheeling-Pitt formally complete their previously announced merger.
6513	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	Both boards have already approved plans for the new publicly traded company, which will be called Esmark Inc., but shareholders also must vote.
6514	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	The Bouchards said Friday they hope to complete the merger by June.
6515	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	The company also announced Friday it has offered voluntary early retirement packages to management employees, with severance packages depending on experience.
6516	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	It described the buyout plan as "fair and equitable" and said it helps the company balance the size of the management ranks with the union-covered work force.
6517	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	"We need to reduce management and overhead to run leaner and meaner," Craig Bouchard said.
6518	APW_ENG_20070316.1536.LDC2009T13	The company currently employs about 3,100 people in West Virginia, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
