6574	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Egyptian parliament approves controversial amendments to constitution
6575	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	CAIRO, Egypt 2007-03-20 03:41:03 UTC
6576	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Egypt's parliament approved a controversial set of amendments to the constitution that the opposition has denounced as a blow to democracy in this top U.S. ally in the Mideast.
6577	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	President Hosni Mubarak has billed the changes Monday as part of a reform package aimed at increasing democracy in the country he has ruled unchallenged for a quarter century.
6578	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	But the opposition has said the changes will restrict judicial supervision of elections they call vital to preventing vote fraud.
6579	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The amendments also write permanently into the constitution strong security powers for the president they fear will be abused.
6580	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The changes come at a time that the U.S. has reduced public pressure on Egypt to bring greater democracy.
6581	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Two years ago, the Bush administration made reform in Egypt a top priority, but more recently it has spoken out less often, more concerned with winning Cairo's support in the Mideast's numerous crises, including Iraq, Lebanon and the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
6582	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Many critics see the changes as aimed at preserving the 78-year- old Mubarak's control and smoothing the way for his son Gamal to succeed him in a future election.
6583	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Opponents also believe the amendments aim to ward off any election challenge from the Muslim Brotherhood, an Islamic fundamentalist group and the biggest opposition bloc in the legislature.
6584	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The 454-seat parliament voted on the measures in a late evening session, a day earlier than expected, after hours of discussion.
6585	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	"With our blood and souls we sacrifice ourselves for you, Mubarak," the ruling party lawmakers chanted before the results of the vote were announced.
6586	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	A spokesman for the Muslim Brotherhood accused the government of passing the measures "in the night, like thieves."
6587	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	"There is a strange and worrisome insistence on passing the amendments as quickly as possible, which reveals the extent of the conspiracy against the people," Hamdi Hassan told The Associated Press."
6588	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The 34 amendments passed with a vote of 315 in favor, parliament speaker Fathi Sorour said on Egyptian television.
6589	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The amendments will now be put before a popular referendum, expected in late March or early April.
6590	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Sorour did not announce the "no" votes in the session.
6591	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The Brotherhood's Hassan said 113 lawmakers voted against the amendments, including two members of the ruling National Democratic Party.
6592	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Abdel-Halim Qandil, a leader of the pro-reform Kifaya movement, said the government was "rushing to commit a political crime.
6593	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	... They are using the constitution like a tissue paper."
6594	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	"They are moving on to a greater crime, the son inheriting power from the father," he said.
6595	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	One amendment bans the formation of any political party based on religion, ensuring the Brotherhood -- which is banned -- cannot become a party.
6596	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Another amendment would require any candidate for president to come from a recognized political party holding at least 3 percent of the seats in parliament.
6597	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Brotherhood candidates run as independents in elections.
6598	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The group scored a surprise victory in parliamentary elections in 2005, winning about a fifth of the seats.
6599	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The opposition was also angered by a change that would create an independent commission to monitor elections, a step they say will reduce the role of judges in overseeing the vote.
6600	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	During the 2005 elections, pro-reform judges blew the whistle on vote fraud that plagued the balloting.
6601	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Another amendment would replace emergency laws in place since the 1981 assassination of President Anwar Sadat, which give police wide powers to detain people and curb political activity.
6602	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Under the new proposed amendment, the constitution would empower the president to refer "any terrorist crime to any of the judiciary authorities stated in the constitution or the law."
6603	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Opponents say that means the president can refer suspects to military courts, which have been widely used in the past but are sharply criticized by rights groups since their rulings cannot be appealed.
6604	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	The London-based rights group Amnesty International said the proposed reforms, particularly the anti-terrorism statute, will lead to the "greatest erosion of rights in 26 years."
6605	APW_ENG_20070320.0207.LDC2009T13	Foreign Minister Ahmed Aboul Gheit bluntly rejected the criticism, saying outsiders don't have the right to "even express their opinion" on Egypt's constitution.
