6677	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	All political killings are bad, whether perpetrated by government troops or communist rebels, an influential Roman Catholic cardinal in the Philippines said in reports published Tuesday.
6678	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	The comments by the archbishop of Manila, Cardinal Gaudencio Rosales, come in the wake of accusations by left-wing and human rights groups blaming the Philippine military for the killing, abduction and torture of hundreds of political activists since President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo came to power in 2001.
6679	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	"We should tell the government as well as the rebels that it is wrong to kill," Rosales said in comments published in major newspapers Tuesday.
6680	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	"It is not one-sided.
6681	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	It is both sides."
6682	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	Presidential spokesman Ignacio Bunye said the cardinal's words were "fair."
6683	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	Arroyo's government denies supporting abuses against political activists, and insists it is taking action to stop them.
6684	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	It has appealed for help from the European Union with forensic investigations.
6685	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	Bunye said the government would also welcome the participation of the U.N. human rights commission and the U.S. government "in the fight versus wrong and the quest for impartial justice."
6686	APW_ENG_20070327.0685.LDC2009T13	Military officials say they are investigating the alleged involvement of some soldiers in the killings, but blame most on communist guerrillas who they say are conducting an internal purge.
