6701	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Indonesia will resume sending bird flu virus specimens to the World Health Organization immediately, the health minister said Tuesday, ending a four-month standoff health officials feared could potentially put the entire world at risk.
6702	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Health Minister Siti Fadiliah Supari had earlier refused to share samples with the global body, saying she was afraid they would be used to develop vaccines that would be ultimately unaffordable for poor nations in the event of a pandemic.
6703	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	International scientists argued that, without specimens, they could not monitor the virus that has killed 66 people in Indonesia -- a third of the world's total -- to see if it was mutating into a more dangerous form.
6704	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"We will start sending bird flu samples to the World Health Organization immediately," Supari told reporters after receiving assurances from the global body that viruses would only be given to pharmaceutical companies with Indonesia's consent.
6705	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"Now we have the right to directly face the companies to negotiate to get what we want," the health minister said.
6706	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"We trust WHO will not violate our trust, because this is related to the WHO's credibility."
6707	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	The unexpected announcement came on the second day of talks in the capital Jakarta between Supari, top WHO officials, regional health chiefs and international avian influenza experts.
6708	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	The meeting wraps up Wednesday.
6709	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"We will keep those viruses and not share them with any industry," David Heymann, the WHO's top flu official, said at a joint press conference.
6710	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"There will be a mechanism to determine how that is done in a transparent way."
6711	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	For weeks, Supari has been demanding that the global body change its 50-year-old virus sharing system, in which it collects regular flu samples from all over the world and makes them available to vaccine makers and others.
6712	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"These practices keep developing countries poor and sick," Supari said Tuesday night.
6713	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"The system is more dangerous than bird flu itself."
6714	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Indonesia's decision to withhold the virus had received support from some other developing nations.
6715	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Heymann earlier said Supari's demands would hinder research into the virus and jeopardize public safety.
6716	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"If we don't know what's going on, it's dangerous, and here is where the virus is most affecting humans," he told reporters late Monday, adding that vaccine makers are already looking elsewhere for virus samples.
6717	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"They will use other viruses, and it will leave Indonesia in great risk," he said.
6718	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	"And it will leave other countries in great risk."
6719	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Heymann suggested several ways to ensure a fairer distribution of vaccines, among them, creating stockpiles of vaccines for use in poor countries and transferring technology so they can produce their own.
6720	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	To ensure it has access to a bird flu vaccine, Indonesia has reached a tentative agreement with U.S. drug manufacturer Baxter Healthcare Corp.
6721	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Under the deal, Indonesia would provide samples of the virus in exchange for Baxter's expertise in vaccine production.
6722	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Indonesia would stockpile the vaccine for use in case there is a major human outbreak.
6723	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Bird flu has killed at least 169 people since it began ravaging Asian poultry stocks in 2003, according to WHO.
6724	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	It remains hard for people to catch, and most human cases have been linked to contact with sick birds.
6725	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	But experts fear it could mutate into a form that spreads easily among people, potentially sparking a pandemic that could kill millions.
6726	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Indonesia, the world's fourth-most-populous country, is seen as a potential hotspot because of its high density of people and chickens.
6727	APW_ENG_20070327.0939.LDC2009T13	Currently, only up to about 500 million doses of flu vaccine can be produced annually -- far short of what would be needed in a pandemic.
