7263	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Estonia-Russia tensions escalate in row over Soviet monument
7264	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	TALLINN, Estonia 2007-05-02 00:10:25 UTC
7265	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Tensions between Estonia and Russia grew as the Baltic country's foreign minister canceled a meeting with lawmakers from Moscow, saying they were spreading lies about a disputed Soviet monument.
7266	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The two-day visit by a delegation from Russia's State Duma was meant to defuse a diplomatic row between the two countries over Estonia's removal of the Bronze Soldier statue from downtown Tallinn.
7267	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	But it only appeared to have escalated the feud.
7268	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	"I will not meet with a delegation that spreads only lies regarding events in Estonia and whose objective is not the accurate portrayal of the situation, but rather election campaigning," Foreign Minister Urmas Paet said in a statement issued Tuesday.
7269	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The Estonian capital was rocked by violent clashes last week between riot police and ethnic Russian protesters, angered by the government's decision to move the Bronze Soldier, a statue honoring Soviet troops killed during World War II.
7270	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Many ethnic Estonians consider the monument a bitter reminder of five decades of Soviet occupation.
7271	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	One man was stabbed to death, more than 150 people were hurt and 1,100 detained in the worst riots since Estonia regained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.
7272	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Estonian police banned public gatherings in the capital region starting Tuesday and extended a ban on alcohol retail sales through May 9, fearing unrest on the date when ethnic Russians traditionally celebrate the Red Army's 1945 defeat of Nazi Germany.
7273	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The delegation from Moscow, headed by Leonid Slutsky, vice chairman of the Duma's foreign affairs committee, placed a wreath of flowers at the statue Tuesday, a day after it was re-erected at a military cemetery outside the city center.
7274	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	At the start of the visit, the Russians called on the Estonian government to resign.
7275	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	On Tuesday, one of them suggested the statue had been damaged in the move.
7276	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	"We see marks -- they are masked, of course, the statue has been restored -- but one can see that it has been subjected to sawing," Nikolai Kovalyov, chairman of the Duma veteran's affairs committee, said in comments shown on Russia's NTV television.
7277	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Estonia forcefully denied any damage to the statue, saying that bronze statues are made in pieces that are joined together.
7278	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Paet said the visitors were "out of line" and accused them of spreading lies about the monument.
7279	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Russia is considering sanctions against Estonia, but Kovalyov said at a news conference they were "not an efficient instrument" because they would also hit ethnic Russians in the Baltic country.
7280	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	In Moscow, however, Mayor Yuri Luzhkov called for a boycott on Estonia and its products.
7281	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Russian media reported that Russian police detained a few demonstrators at the Estonian Embassy, after an Estonian flag was ripped off its pole outside the building.
7282	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The flag was later restored.
7283	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The dispute has strained already tense relations between the Kremlin and Estonia, and highlighted long-standing Russian complaints about the treatment of Russian-speaking minorities in Estonia and neighboring Latvia.
7284	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	While Russian speakers in the Baltic states enjoyed advantages under Soviet rule, many now struggle to get education, deal with government offices and get jobs amid a resurgence in native languages and inroads by English.
7285	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Late Tuesday, Paet urged the European Union, of which Estonia has been a member since 2004, to express support for his country.
7286	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	He also said that hacker attacks blocking several Estonian government Web sites had been traced to IP addresses linked to "the office of the Russian president and individuals at Russian government organizations."
7287	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	The Estonian government was to officially inaugurate the statue at its new location on May 8, a day before Russians celebrate the Allied victory over Nazi Germany.
7288	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	In the next step of its contentious plan, the government wants to move the remains of Soviet soldiers believed to be buried next to the statue's original site.
7289	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	Archeologists excavating the grave said they had found 12 coffins by Monday, and opened six of them to examine the remains.
7290	APW_ENG_20070502.0032.LDC2009T13	---
