7370	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	GRAND RAPIDS, Michigan 2007-05-14 16:51:59 UTC
7371	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	Dow Chemical Co. said Monday it plans to build multibillion- dollar production complexes in Saudi Arabia and China by entering into pacts with large energy companies in those nations.
7372	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	Dow Chemical has signed an agreement with Saudi Aramco, the world's largest supplier of energy, to enter into the final negotiation phase for the formation of a joint venture to build, own and operate a "world-scale" chemicals and plastics production complex near Ras Tanura in Saudi Arabia's Eastern Province.
7373	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The Ras Tanura petrochemical joint venture would take years to complete and be operationally integrated with Saudi Aramco's Ras Tanura refinery complex and its Ju'aymah gas-processing plant, which would supply raw materials to be used in production at the new facility, Midland-based Dow said in a statement.
7374	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The new business would produce a broad range of products, including ethylene and propylene, the building blocks used in the production of various plastics and chemical products.
7375	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	"These are basic chemicals that you use to make either commodity products or specialty products," Andrew N. Liveris, Dow's president and chief executive, said in a telephone interview from London.
7376	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	"That's the unusual part of the Aramco-Dow joint venture -- that we're going to actually put in place an ability to make our specialty products as well."
7377	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The massive project would help expand Saudi Arabia's economic base, create jobs and promote economic diversification in the country, said Abdallah S. Jum'ah, president and CEO of Saudi Aramco.
7378	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	Dow and the Shenhua Group of China were to sign a cooperation agreement for conducting a detailed, two-year feasibility study for building a coal-to-chemicals complex in China's Shaanxi Province.
7379	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The project would use "clean coal" technologies that convert coal to methanol to produce basic products such as ethylene and propylene, as well as other derivative products.
7380	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	Liveris said the project is in line with Dow's strategy to improve its competitive position in Asia "with locally produced products and solutions."
7381	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	"The building of the world-scale coal chemical plant jointly with Dow will make full use of the respective advantages of the two companies," said Chen Biting, chairman of Shenhua Group.
7382	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	"It is of great significance for the world to produce the oil substitute converted from coal and it is the case for China in particular."
7383	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The feasibility study is expected to take about two years.
7384	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	The two companies then would put together a project-application report for submission to the Chinese government for approval.
7385	APW_ENG_20070514.1001.LDC2009T13	Liveris declined to say how much money Dow planned to spend on the two projects other than to describe the Saudi Aramco project as the larger of the two and that each would cost "multiple billions of dollars."
