7601	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK 2007-06-10 05:58:07 UTC
7602	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	A medical examiner blamed a 17-year-old track star's death on the use of too much anti-inflammatory muscle cream, the kind used to soothe aching legs after exercise.
7603	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Arielle Newman, a cross-country runner at Notre Dame Academy on New York's Staten Island, died after her body absorbed high levels of methyl salicylate, an anti-inflammatory found in sports creams such as Bengay and Icy Hot, the New York City medical examiner said Friday.
7604	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	The medical examiner's spokeswoman, Ellen Borakove, said the teen used "topical medication to excess."
7605	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	She said it was the first time that her office had reported a death from using a sports cream.
7606	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	In addition to spreading the muscle cream on her legs between track meets, Newman was using adhesive pads containing the anti- inflammatory, plus an unspecified third product containing the chemical, Borakove said.
7607	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	The products were used and the chemical absorbed over time, she said.
7608	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Newman, who garnered numerous track awards, died April 3.
7609	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	She had gone to a party the night before, then returned home and spent hours talking with her mother.
7610	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Methyl salicylate poisoning is unusual, and deaths from high levels of the chemical are rare.
7611	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	"Chronic use is more dangerous than one-time use," Edward Arsura, chairman of medicine at Richmond University Medical Center, told the Staten Island Advance on Friday.
7612	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	"Exercise and heat can accentuate absorption."
7613	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Dr. Ronald Grelsamer, of Mount Sinai Medical Center, said Newman had a very abnormal amount of methyl salicylate in her body.
7614	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	"She either lathered herself with it, or used way too much, or she used a normal amount and an abnormal percentage was absorbed into her body," he said.
7615	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Her mother, Alice Newman, said she still could not believe her daughter's death was caused by a sports cream.
7616	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	"I am scrupulous about my children's health," she told the Advance newspaper.
7617	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	"I did not think an over-the-counter product could be unsafe."
7618	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Johnson &amp
7619	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	Johnson, the makers of Bengay, expressed sympathy for the family and reminded consumers about "the importance of reading the label on this and all over-the-counter medicines to ensure safe and proper use," in a statement released Saturday.
7620	APW_ENG_20070610.0182.LDC2009T13	The label on Ultra Strength Bengay says the product should be applied no more than three or four times daily and consumers should stop and see a doctor if the condition worsens or symptoms persist for more than a week, spokeswoman Meghan Marschall said.
