7723	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	He would not name the hospitals outside France involved, but said they and government health authorities in the U.S. and Spain had been contacted, and that Brainlab was leaving it up to them to inform their patients of the malfunction.
7724	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Another Brainlab official said the U.S. hospitals were in Washington state and Ohio.
7725	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Dr. Georges Noel, a radiotherapy expert at the Paul Strauss cancer center in Strasbourg, France, says this treatment is reserved for patients who cannot undergo an operation.
7726	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	If the tumor cannot be removed by surgery, radiotherapy can provide comparable results, Noel said.
7727	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	For these patients, radiology "is the most effective alternative," he said.
7728	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	While other treatments for these patients are available, none provides results as effective as radiotherapy, Noel explained in an e-mail message.
7729	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Noel said that the machine malfunctions were potentially harmful for patients.
7730	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	"A mistargeted machine could irradiate healthy brain tissue.
7731	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	... It could kill healthy tissue," Noel said.
7732	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Whether this would have a large or small effect on the patient depends on the part of the brain affected, he said.
7733	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	The Brainlab case has raised concern because it is the latest of several cases involving brain cancer radiation treatment in hospitals around France dating back to 2004.
7734	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	In the latest incident, Brainlab alerted the four French hospitals directly June 7, after it identified a calibration error in a machine in Spain, Vilsmeier said.
7735	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	That machine has not yet been used on patients.
7736	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	The problem was identified after 145 patients received an improper dose of radiation from Brainlab equipment in Toulouse in southern France in April.
7737	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	It has not yet been determined whether it was an underdose or an overdose, the French Nuclear Safety Authority said.
7738	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Following that incident, Brainlab, in conjunction with two French regulatory bodies, began a nationwide assessment of all Brainlab machines in use, and detected the targeting problem.
7739	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	The two incidents, however, were not connected, the Health Ministry said in a statement Monday.
7740	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	The ministry responded with an order on Sunday for all four hospitals using the identified Brainlab equipment to suspend their activities.
7741	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Four other brain tumor radiotherapy machines, not made by Brainlab, in operation elsewhere in France were not affected.
7742	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Radiotherapy treatment involves a one-time blast by a high-energy X-Ray that is aimed from several sources and focused on one point to kill the tumor.
7743	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	It typically has a margin of error of 0.8 millimeters when used on brain tumors, but when an older software used to map the brain is combined with a newer aiming apparatus, that margin can increase, Vilsmeier said in a telephone interview.
7744	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	In the malfunctioning French machines, the margin was found to have increased to 1.25 millimeters, Brainlab said in a statement.
7745	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	"We don't expect any problems with the patients," said Vilsmeier, because a doctor will typically use a safety margin of 1 to 3 millimeters (0.04 inches to 0.12 inches).
7746	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	"This security margin is always used to avoid critical organs: very important parts of the brain such as those that control sight," said Dr. Christian Carrie, coordinator of radiotherapy at the Leon Berard Cancer Centre in Lyon.
7747	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Carrie said that with a security margin, "we cannot be sure, but we can hope" to avoid killing healthy brain tissue "even if there is a problem with the targeting of 1 millimeter."
7748	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Four hospitals, in Nancy, Tours, Montpellier and Paris, shut down their radiotherapy machines Monday and an analysis of the machines has begun.
7749	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	The hospitals have also begun the process of tracking down all patients who may have received treatment from the malfunctioning machines, a number that may top 620, reported Le Parisien newspaper.
7750	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Brainlab is offering a software update that should take care of the problem, Vilsmeier said.
7751	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	In 2004 and 2005, 24 patients in Epinal received as much as a 30 percent overdose of radiation while undergoing prostate cancer treatment.
7752	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	Four of these patients died, and their families are suing the hospitals, claiming that the deaths were a result of the overdoses.
7753	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	A 32-year-old woman died of complications after receiving a radiation treatment to an area 10 times the size she should have, in Lyon in 2004.
7754	APW_ENG_20070614.1533.LDC2009T13	In both the Epinal and Lyon incidents, hospitals blamed the problems on human error.
