7774	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Famed American World War II cemetery in France gets visitor center
7775	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	COLLEVILLE-SUR-MER, France 2007-06-21 00:28:03 UTC
7776	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Photos of fresh-faced privates, wizened U.S. generals and the largest amphibious military operation in history.
7777	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Dented army canteens that once dotted killing fields in France.
7778	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The booming sounds of gunships echoing over the waves in Normandy -- this time, on video.
7779	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The Normandy American Cemetery in Colleville-sur-Mer, best known for its sober rows of white grave markers honoring fallen U.S. troops in World War II, has at last gotten a visitor's center.
7780	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Nearly a million visitors trek every year to the cemetery overlooking Omaha Beach, one of the two landing points where U.S. troops stormed ashore on D-Day -- June 6, 1944 -- and helped the Allies rid the menace of Nazi Germany over Europe.
7781	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Six years in the making, the new center was inaugurated recently by U.S. Defense Secretary Robert Gates for the 63rd anniversary of the start of "Operation Overlord" that helped end the war.
7782	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	"We build memorials like this to remind us of the past.
7783	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	So that successive generations will know the enormous cost of freedom," Gates said at the ceremony.
7784	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Designers faced a delicate task balancing the desire to educate while not overshadowing sacrifices of nearly 10,000 Americans buried nearby.
7785	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The US$30 million (euro22.4 million) visitor center is purposely understated, with most of the 10,000-square-feet (929-square- meters) of display space underground, though it is now the entryway for tourists onto the cemetery's manicured lawn.
7786	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	"The cemetery has always had this extremely powerful emotional component," said Macarena Aristegui of the American Battle Monuments Commission, which runs the cemetery and memorial.
7787	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	"What was lacking was a story to go with the names written on the headstones."
7788	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The site is one of the most visited U.S. military cemeteries in the world.
7789	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	It draws veterans' relatives, many of them Americans who feel proud of their country's contribution to the liberation of France and Europe, as well as veterans themselves whose numbers are dwindling -- but who still have many thoughts for their fallen comrades-in-arms.
7790	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The center displays scratched and dented weapons, photos of soldiers who carried them, and excerpts from letters they sent home.
7791	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	It also shows documentary films and news reports about the war's progress.
7792	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	U.S. Congressmen David Obey, D-Wis., and John Murtha, D-Pa., proposed building the center in 2001, and it was designed by French-American architect Nicolas Kelemen.
7793	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The first stone was laid two years ago.
7794	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Some 200 American World War II veterans were on hand for the center's June 6, 2007, inauguration, along with 15 who had fought on the beaches, some of whom hadn't been back since the war, Aristegui said.
7795	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Admission to the visitor center is free.
7796	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	A small private room is available for veterans and their families to give them privacy before or after a visit to the cemetery.
7797	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	---
7798	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	If You Go:
7799	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	NORMANDY AMERICAN VISITOR CENTER: U_R_L Four trains run daily between Paris' St. Lazare station and Bayeux, Normandy, the nearest train station to the visitor center.
7800	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The trip is about 2- 1/2 hours.
7801	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	From Bayeux, taxis are available to reach the memorial.
7802	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	The cemetery is open daily from 9 a.m.- 5 p.m., except for Dec. 25 and Jan. 1.
7803	APW_ENG_20070621.0078.LDC2009T13	Admission is free.
