8225	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Two other people, Marjorie Diehl-Armstrong and her friend, Kenneth E. Barnes, are charged with bank robbery and conspiracy.
8226	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Authorities said the plot was concocted so Diehl-Armstrong, 58, could pay someone to kill her father.
8227	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Diehl-Armstrong and Barnes are accused of contriving a series of notes to make Wells appear to be "merely a hostage," according to the indictments.
8228	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Their plan was to get the money from Wells in a way that if he was caught, he could claim he was an unwilling participant, authorities said in court papers.
8229	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	According to the indictments, they locked a live bomb onto Well's neck to ensure he followed their instructions and turned over the money.
8230	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"If he died, he could not be a witness," authorities said in the indictment.
8231	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	U.S. Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan described Wells as having a limited role in the plot and couldn't comment on what his motive might have been for being involved.
8232	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	The bomb that killed Wells was on a timer but it was unclear if his co-conspirators planned on his death, she said.
8233	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"Sadly, the plans of these other individuals were much more sinister ... and he died as a result," Buchanan said.
8234	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"It may be that his role transitioned from that of the planing stages to being an unwilling participant in the scheme."
8235	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Diehl-Armstrong is currently serving a state prison sentence for killing her boyfriend, James Roden.
8236	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	In the indictment, authorities say she killed Roden to keep him from disclosing details of the robbery plot.
8237	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Barnes, 53, is jailed in Erie County on unrelated drug charges.
8238	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Authorities have described him as Diehl-Armstrong's fishing companion.
8239	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Diehl-Armstrong was notified Tuesday that she may face charges of bank robbery, conspiracy and a firearms count, lawyer Lawrence D'Ambrosio said.
8240	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	He says she is innocent.
8241	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Wells set out to deliver an order for two pizzas to a mysterious address that turned out to be the location of a TV tower on Aug. 28, 2003.
8242	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	He turned up about an hour later and roughly 2 miles (3 kilometers) away at a PNC Bank branch, with a note demanding money and saying he had a bomb.
8243	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Wells took the money from a teller, got into his car and was soon captured by police.
8244	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Hanging from his neck under his T-shirt was a triple-banded metal collar and a device with a locking mechanism that kept it in place.
8245	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Attached to the collar was a bomb.
8246	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"It's going to go off," Wells said.
8247	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"I'm not lying."
8248	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	He said someone had started a timer on the bomb and forced him to rob the bank.
8249	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	While police waited for a bomb squad, the bomb exploded, killing Wells.
8250	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Police found a gun resembling a cane in the car and a nine-page handwritten letter that included detailed instructions on what Wells was to do with the bank money and how he could unlock the collar by going through a kind of scavenger hunt, looking for clues and landmarks.
8251	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	The note also included a list of rules and a threat that Wells would be "destroyed" if he failed to complete his mission.
8252	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Buchanan said Wednesday that while Wells was in the bank, Diehl- Armstrong and Barnes had watched from across the street, and Diehl-Armstrong was later seen twice along the route described in the notes.
8253	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Jim Sadowski, a former co-worker of Wells, said he does not believe his friend could have been involved.
8254	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	"I worked with him and I knew him.
8255	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	I just don't see him doing anything like that.
8256	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	He was a nice person," Sadowski said.
8257	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Diehl-Armstrong has been linked to the Wells investigation because her boyfriend's body was found in the freezer of a home near the TV tower where Wells made his final delivery.
8258	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	She pleaded guilty but mentally ill to killing her boyfriend and is serving a sentence of seven to 20 years in state prison.
8259	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	The man who owned the home, William Rothstein, was questioned in Wells' death but has since died of cancer.
8260	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	D'Ambrosio, Diehl-Armstrong's attorney, has said he believes she had nothing to do with Wells' death but may have known the people behind the robbery.
8261	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	---
8262	APW_ENG_20070711.1480.LDC2009T13	Associated Press writer Joe Mandak in Pittsburgh and Lara Jakes Jordan in Washington contributed to this report.
