8896	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Three months after elections, Belgium still lacks a government.
8897	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Is Belgium ' s end ear?
8898	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	BRUSSELS, Belgium 2007-09-04 12:27:56 UTC
8899	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	In a hoax that sent panic through the nation, a Belgian TV station reported last year that the Dutch-speaking half of the country had declared independence and the king and queen had fled.
8900	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Now, a notion that was once a fantasy of fringe politicians is suddenly on everybody's lips: Is Belgium about to come an end?
8901	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Almost three months after elections, Belgium has no government, efforts to form one are on hold, and unity appeals by King Albert II have been ignored -- eroding the prestige of a monarchy often hailed as the glue holding this bilingual nation of 10.5 million together.
8902	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Such is the deadlock between Dutch and French-speaking parties over how to form the next government that mainstream politicians and media are now openly airing the view that Belgium's linguistic camps may be better off divorcing.
8903	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	"I don't want the end of Belgium, but I fear it will happen," says Gerard Deprez, a former Christian Democratic leader from French-speaking Wallonia.
8904	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Elio di Rupo, the Francophone Socialist leader, says the danger of Belgium's disintegration "is greater now than it was on June 10" -- when elections triggered the protracted haggling over forming the government.
8905	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	In the June 10 ballot, Christian Democrats and Liberals won 81 of the 150 parliamentary seats and agreed to form a coalition.
8906	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	But the composition of the government has been stalled due to bickering over Flemish demands for more autonomy and the redrawing a bilingual Brussels-area voting district.
8907	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Belgium's 6.5 million Dutch-speakers and 4 million Francophones south have enjoyed broad self-rule since the 1980s
8908	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	only Brussels is officially a bilingual region.
8909	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Many Flemish grouse their wealthier, service-based economy subsidizes Wallonia.
8910	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Dutch-speakers view the Francophones' dilapidated cities and 14 percent unemployment -- double their rate -- as the legacy of hardline Socialist rule
8911	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Dutch-speakers are demanding autonomy in health care, justice and transport -- some of the last bastions of central control from Brussels.
8912	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Many feel the next logical step would be full independence.
8913	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	"Living together in one country is impossible if year after year the minority prevents the majority to realize its most important desires," Het Laatste Nieuws, Belgium's largest daily, argued recently.
8914	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Seeing politicians "at each other's throats" in linguistic spats makes Belgians believe divorce is possible, says Jos Geysels, a commentator said in the daily De Morgen.
8915	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Chris Peeters, an Antwerp resident, sees widespread support for Flemish independence "because all the difficulties we have had over the last 10 years in Belgium ... are coming from the French part.
8916	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	So it would be a solution for Belgium to split apart."
8917	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	A recent VTM television network poll found 46 percent of Flemings favoring independence -- the highest level in years due to the linguistic political sniping.
8918	APW_ENG_20070904.0665.LDC2009T13	Among parties, independence is an official goal only of the far- right Flemish Interest party but its growing popularity -- it won 17 seats in the June voting -- has radicalized even mainstream Flemish parties.
