9159	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"We believe that an independent South, or Hawaii, Alaska, or Vermont, would be better able to serve the interest of everybody, regardless of race or ethnicity," said Michael Hill of Killen, Alabama, president of the League of the South.
9160	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Separated by hundreds of miles (kilometers) and divergent political philosophies, the Middlebury Institute and the League of the South are hosting a two-day Secessionist Convention starting Wednesday in Chattanooga.
9161	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	They expect to attract supporters from California, Alaska and Hawaii, inviting anyone who wants to dissolve the union so states can save themselves from an overbearing federal government.
9162	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	If allowed to go their own way, New Englanders "probably would allow abortion and have gun control," Hill said, while Southerners "would probably crack down on illegal immigration harder than it is being now."
9163	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	The U.S. Constitution does not explicitly prohibit secession, but few people think it is politically viable.
9164	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Vermont, one of the nation's most liberal states, has become a hotbed for liberal secessionists, a fringe movement that gained new traction because of the Iraq war, rising oil prices and the formation of several pro-secession groups.
9165	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Thomas Naylor, the founder of one of those groups, the Second Vermont Republic, said the friendly relationship with the League of the South did not mean everyone shares all the same beliefs.
9166	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	But Naylor, a retired Duke University professor, said the League of the South shares his group's opposition to the federal government and the need to pursue secession.
9167	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"It doesn't matter if our next president is Condoleezza (Rice) or Hillary (Clinton), it is going to be grim," said Naylor, adding that there are secessionist movements in more than 25 states, including Hawaii, Alaska, New Hampshire, South Carolina and Texas.
9168	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	The Middlebury Institute, based in Cold Spring, New York, was started in 2005.
9169	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Its followers, disillusioned by the Iraq war and federal imperialism, share the idea of states becoming independent republics.
9170	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	They contend their movement is growing.
9171	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	The first North American Separatist Convention was held last fall in Vermont, which, unlike most Southern states, supports civil unions.
9172	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Voters there elected a socialist to the U.S. Senate.
9173	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Middlebury director Kirpatrick Sale said Hill offered to sponsor the second secessionist convention, but the co-sponsor arrangement was intended to show that "the folks up north regard you as legitimate colleagues."
9174	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"It bothers me that people have wrongly declared them to be racists," Sale said.
9175	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	The League of the South says it is not racist, but proudly displays a Confederate Battle Flag on its banner.
9176	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Mark Potok, director of the Southern Poverty Law Center's Intelligence Project, which monitors hate groups, said the League of the South "has been on our list close to a decade."
9177	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"What is remarkable and really astounding about this situation is we see people and institutions who are supposedly on the progressive left rubbing shoulders with bona fide white supremacists," Potok said.
9178	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Sale said the League of the South "has not done or said anything racist in its 14 years of existence," and that the Southern Poverty Law Center is not credible.
9179	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"They call everybody racists," Sale said.
9180	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	"There are, no doubt, racists in the League of the South, and there are, no doubt, racists everywhere."
9181	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	Harry Watson, director of the Center For the Study of the American South and a history professor at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said it was a surprise to see The Middlebury Institute conferring with the League of the South, "an organization that's associated with a cause that many of us associate with the preservation of slavery."
9182	APW_ENG_20071003.0324.LDC2009T13	He said the unlikely partnering "represents the far left and far right of American politics coming together."
