9434	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	That was the third straight quarter of declines, after a revised 4.1 percent fall in the April-June period.
9435	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Although housing investment accounts for only 3 percent of the GDP, its decline is a cause for worry because it could hurt factory output and business investment by cooling demand for construction materials and durable goods such as refrigerators and TVs.
9436	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Such a slowdown in internal demand would mean that the Bank of Japan will likely have to wait until next year to lift short-term interest rates from the current 0.5 percent level.
9437	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	The data came before the central bank finishes its two-day monetary policy meeting later Tuesday.
9438	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Most analysts expect the bank to leave short-term rates unchanged at 0.50 percent.
9439	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	In the July-September period, consumer spending, which accounts for more than half of Japan's GDP, rose 0.3 percent on quarter, better than a revised 0.2 percent rise in the April-June period.
9440	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Solid sales in the travel industry attributed to the rise.
9441	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Business investment rose 1.7 percent, rebounding from a revised 2.1 percent decline in the April-June period.
9442	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Companies bought more general industrial machinery, according to the Cabinet Office.
9443	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	The data, meanwhile, indicate that Japan has so far withstood the impact of the slumping U.S. housing sector, which since August has roiled global stock markets, sank some hedge funds and caused the leaders of major U.S. banks to be sacked.
9444	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Exports rose 2.9 percent, up for the 10th straight quarter and much faster than a revised 0.9 percent gain in the April-June quarter as Asian nations bought more Japanese goods, such as cars and motorcycles.
9445	APW_ENG_20071113.0103.LDC2009T13	Imports were up 0.5 percent, after gaining 0.8 percent in the second quarter, due in part to higher oil and natural resource prices.
