9475	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	Ryanair Holdings PLC said Wednesday it is suing the European Commission over its refusal to investigate whether German government funding for a Munich airport terminal amounts to illegal state aid for Lufthansa AG.
9476	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	The suit filed in the European Court of First Instance, the second-highest EU court, is the latest salvo in an apparent tit- for-tat battle between Ryanair and EU competition authorities.
9477	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	For the past two years Ryanair has accused European leaders of demonstrating bias in favor of the continent's national flag carriers, citing a range of government financial supports benefiting Lufthansa, Air France, Alitalia and Olympic Airways of Greece.
9478	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	Ryanair has been subjected to a series of EU investigations into its deals with far-flung, small airports, most recently in July when investigators began probing whether Ryanair's exceptionally cheap contracts with three airports in Germany and Finland violated competition laws.
9479	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	The EU also is looking into Ryanair's contracts with airports in the Mediterranean islands of Sardinia and Malta.
9480	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	The Ryanair announcement came on the same day that European Consumer Affairs Commissioner Maglena Kuneva published a report alleging widespread deceptive practices in the on-line sales of airline tickets.
9481	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	The report did not single out Ryanair, which pioneered the rise of Web-based sales in Europe and is frequently criticized by consumer groups for its plethora of add-on charges, including for conventional check-ins and use of credit cards.
9482	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	But Kuneva warned that offending airlines would be identified in four months if they didn't reform how their Web sites tacked on costs to ticket prices.
9483	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	Chief Executive Michael O'Leary said Ryanair had waited two years for EU authorities to act on the airline's original complaint against German state aid to build and operate Terminal 2 in Munich.
9484	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	O'Leary said Lufthansa and its partner airlines enjoyed "exclusive use" of the terminal, which was built chiefly with more than euro1 billion (US$1.4 billion) in state aid.
9485	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	He said the terminal had run up losses exceeding euro100 million (US$140 million) annually.
9486	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	"No private investor would have invested in the loss-making facility and then granted exclusive access to just one airline.
9487	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	Lufthansa is therefore receiving substantial state aid at Munich Airport, which distorts competition in the European air transport market," O'Leary said.
9488	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	"Munich Airport's refusal to allow Ryanair to use this facility has subjected passengers in Bavaria to the stranglehold of Lufthansa's high fares and fuel surcharges," he said.
9489	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	Ryanair mounted a similarly themed lawsuit last week against the European Commission alleging it has ignored a previous Ryanair complaint against French government policies that allegedly favor Air France.
9490	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	That lawsuit was also filed in the European Court of First Instance.
9491	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	"The French government's operation of massively discounted domestic airport fees in France -- almost all of which supports Air France -- amounts to approximately euro1 billion (US$1.4 billion) of illegal state aid to the benefit of Air France, yet the commission has refused to do anything about this for the last 18 months," O'Leary said.
9492	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	EU antitrust authorities further annoyed Ryanair in June by rejecting its takeover terms for rival Irish carrier Aer Lingus, ruling that a combined operation would create a Ryanair monopoly in Ireland.
9493	APW_ENG_20071114.0707.LDC2009T13	The EU in this decade has approved a string of other European mergers involving Air France, Dutch carrier KLM, Lufthansa and the defunct Swissair.
