9801	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	A group representing German restaurant and bar owners said Friday it has filed a challenge to the country's supreme court against new laws that restrict smoking.
9802	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	Several German states recently have introduced, or plan to introduce, partial bans on smoking in restaurants and bars, although the restrictions generally have fallen short of near- total bans on smoking in enclosed spaces elsewhere in Europe.
9803	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	The industry group, DEHOGA, said it joined in a suit filed to the Federal Constitutional Court by an inn owner in the southwestern state of Baden-Wuerttemberg, which on Aug. 1 became one of the first to introduce curbs on smoking.
9804	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	The state's ban, like most others in Germany, allowed for special rooms to be set aside for smokers, but DEHOGA argued that that puts owners of one-room bars, such as the plaintiff, at a disadvantage.
9805	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	It said the man, whose customers were 70 percent smokers, had seen his turnover decline by more than 30 percent in the August- November period from a year earlier.
9806	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	"In most hotels and many restaurants, the implementation of the smoking ban has gone without problems so far," DEHOGA head Ingrid Hartges said in a statement.
9807	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	However, "there are significant problems in one-room operations ... in which the majority of regular customers often are smokers," she added.
9808	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	"Many of these caterers are angry ... and fear for their existence."
9809	APW_ENG_20071221.0636.LDC2009T13	It was not immediately clear when the court might consider the complaint.
9810	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Oil prices rise as consumer spending report suggests US economy is weathering the credit storm
9811	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK 2007-12-21 15:13:25 UTC
9812	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Oil prices rose Friday after the government reported that consumer spending surged last month, raising hopes that the U.S. economy will weather the crisis roiling credit markets and that demand for oil and gasoline will strengthen.
9813	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	The Commerce Department said consumer spending jumped 1.1 percent in November, the biggest one-month gain since 2004 and well above analyst expectations for an 0.7 percent increase.
9814	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	That news countered Thursday's report from the Conference Board that its index of leading indicators dropped 0.4 percent in November to the lowest level in more than two years, suggesting the economy was headed for a slowdown.
9815	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Light, sweet crude for February delivery rose 67 cents to $91.73 on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
9816	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	A slightly weaker dollar also supported oil prices Friday.
9817	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Oil futures offer a hedge against a weak dollar, and oil futures bought and sold in dollars are more attractive to foreign investors when the greenback is falling.
9818	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Many observers blame oil's rise last month to near $100 on speculators driven to oil futures by the weaker dollar.
9819	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	While oil prices were higher Friday, trading volumes ahead of the holidays were low.
9820	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	A similar pattern of light trading led to a choppy day Thursday.
9821	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	"Many traders seem to have quit trading for the year and others are less active," said Peter Beutel, president of the energy risk management firm Cameron Hanover, in a research note.
9822	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Crude futures have since retreated as OPEC boosted supplies and several forecasters cut demand predictions.
9823	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	But in recent weeks, prices have held generally to a range between $88 and $92, leading some analysts to conclude investors are seeking direction and may be poised to make another push for $100 a barrel in the new year.
9824	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	"The markets are looking for something that will provide that sense of trend that is currently missing," Beutel said.
9825	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Because of the holidays, it may be a while before a trend emerges, analysts say.
9826	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	"We most likely will have to wait until mid-January for volume to pick up in most complexes, as (investors) decide which of the countervailing factors at work are likely to dominate the early innings of the New Year," said Edward Meir, an analyst at MF Global UK Ltd., in a research note.
9827	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	Other energy futures were mixed Friday.
9828	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	January heating oil futures gained 0.71 cent to $2.5966 a gallon on the Nymex, while January gasoline futures added 2.63 cents to $2.3539 a gallon.
9829	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	January natural gas futures dropped 2.9 cents to $7.108 per 1,000 cubic feet on the Nymex.
9830	APW_ENG_20071221.0793.LDC2009T13	In London, Brent crude rose 58 cents to $91.46 a barrel on the ICE Futures exchange.
