9843	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	New Jersey bans Iran investments, becomes one of few US states to do so
9844	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	TRENTON, New Jersey 2008-01-04 20:44:50 UTC
9845	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	New Jersey on Friday became one of at least three U.S. states to prohibit state pension money from being invested in companies doing business in Iran.
9846	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	Most American companies are already barred from doing business in the country, but Democratic Gov. Jon S. Corzine signed a measure restricting the state from buying stock in international companies that do business with Iran.
9847	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	The move is designed to protest the country's links to terrorism and its nuclear ambitions.
9848	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	"I continue to support using economic means, not military means, to bring about policy changes in Iran," Corzine said recently when discussing the bill signed privately on Friday.
9849	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	Florida and California have similar laws.
9850	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	Florida's law also banned investments in Sudan, and the board governing Florida's public employee retirement fund authorized it to divest nearly $1.3 billion (euro880,000 million) invested with 21 companies doing business in the two nations.
9851	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	California Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger in October signed legislation to end state investment in companies that do business with Iran.
9852	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	New Jersey Assemblyman Neil Cohen, a Democrat who helped sponsor the bill, cited Iranian threats against Israel.
9853	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	"Divesting our finances from entities associated with Iran will send a clear message in the universal language of money that New Jersey will have no part in Iran's pursuit of actions that would lead to Holocaust-like genocide and the complete destruction of a sovereign nation," Cohen said.
9854	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	The New Jersey proposal mirrors a 2005 bill that prohibited investing state pension funds in companies doing business in Sudan to protest what the United States has deemed a genocide in the African nation.
9855	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	New Jersey also passed a similar law in the 1980s barring investments in South Africa.
9856	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	The state's pension fund is worth about $80 billion (euro54 billion), though it was unclear how much is invested in companies doing business in Iran.
9857	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	The law requires the state to hire an independent research firm specializing in global securities to identify such investments.
9858	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	New Jersey's pension fund is the nation's ninth largest.
9859	APW_ENG_20080104.1098.LDC2009T13	It recently divested $2.16 billion (euro1.47 billion) from 17 companies doing business in Sudan.
9860	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Exit poll indicates Saakashvili will win Georgian election
9861	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	opposition says vote rigged
9862	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	TBILISI, Georgia 2008-01-06 10:36:00 UTC
9863	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	President Mikhail Saakashvili headed for victory in Georgia's election, according to an exit poll and early results released Sunday, but the opposition claimed the vote was rigged and called for protests.
9864	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili's supporters waved flags and tooted car horns in the capital after the exit poll showed him winning 53.8 percent of the vote Saturday.
9865	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	But the poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points -- casting doubt on whether the president would hang onto the absolute majority needed to avoid a runoff.
9866	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Early results released by the Central Election Commission Sunday also indicated Saakashvili was poised for victory.
9867	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	With some 3 percent of precincts counted, Saakashvili had 61.5 percent, while his main challenger Levan Gachechiladze received 21.3 percent.
9868	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Gachechiladze, received 28.3 percent of the vote, according to the exit poll, which the opposition said was falsified.
9869	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	About two hours before the polls closed Saturday night, the head of an international election-monitoring mission said the election appeared fair.
9870	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	"From what we're seeing now ... there does not appear to be anything to suggest there is an election being stolen," said U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings, heading a mission sent by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
9871	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	But opposition leaders said the campaign was held under unfair conditions and claimed there were widespread violations during the vote.
9872	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Gachechiladze, speaking on television early Sunday, claimed he had won in most precincts and the vote count was being held under conditions of "terror."
9873	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	He called for protests Sunday afternoon, urging "all of Georgia to come to make sure we don't lose our country."
9874	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili, while still waiting for official results, said the exit poll showed him winning and called for reconciliation in a speech to supporters at a celebratory concert.
9875	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	"If the final results confirm that I have won in the first round, then I will assume the honor and responsibility to serve all of Georgia for the next five years," he said.
9876	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	"I'm extending my hand to those who voted for me and to those who took part in the elections," he said.
9877	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The U.S.-educated Saakashvili led mass street protests that ousted a Communist-era veteran from power following fraudulent elections in late 2003.
9878	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	He won a January 2004 election with more than 96 percent of the vote and set out to transform the bankrupt country into a modern European state.
9879	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Now the Rose Revolution hero, who was much lauded in the West, is accused by his opponents at home of sidelining his critics and displaying an authoritarian bent.
9880	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	After casting his ballot in Tbilisi, Saakashvili said he was dedicated to having a free and fair election.
9881	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	"We are committed to having Georgia as a beacon of democracy in our part of the world," he said.
9882	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili's opponents took to the streets in November, holding peaceful demonstrations for five days before police violently dispersed them.
9883	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili imposed a state of emergency that included banning independent TV news broadcasts.
9884	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The violent crackdown angered many Georgians and called into question Saakashvili's commitment to democracy.
9885	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili defused the crisis by calling an early election, cutting short his own five-year term.
9886	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	A runoff vote could allow the opposition, now split among six candidates, to unite behind Gachechiladze, a businessman and lawmaker.
9887	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Gachechiladze, 43, represents an opposition coalition that wants to do away with the presidency.
9888	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	If a parliamentary system is established, as the coalition wants, he would step down.
9889	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The opposition has been undermined by a scandal that has discredited one of the leading candidates, billionaire Badri Patarkatsishvili.
9890	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	He has been accused of plotting to overthrow the government and has acknowledged offering large sums of money to police if they side with protesters.
9891	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Georgian authorities say he offered US$100 million (euro68 million).
9892	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The exit poll showed Patarkatsishvili finishing third with 6.2 percent of the vote.
9893	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Saakashvili says the election has put at stake his plan to transform Georgia into a country worthy of membership in NATO and the European Union.
9894	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	Sixty-one percent of voters approved of joining the Western military alliance in a referendum that was held alongside the Saturday election, according to the exit poll.
9895	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	During his four years in office, he has cracked down on organized crime and corruption, modernized the police force and the army, restored steady supplies of electricity and gas, and improved roads.
9896	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The result has been annual economic growth of about 10 percent and a steady rise in foreign investment.
9897	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	The economic success has not yet defeated poverty, and after the November protests, Saakashvili made social welfare one of his top priorities.
9898	APW_ENG_20080106.0292.LDC2009T13	---
