9936	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	In recent months, several al-Qaida-inspired groups have emerged in Gaza, though their actual links to the terror network, if any exist, are murky.
9937	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	An almost complete closure of Gaza since the Hamas takeover in June has driven Gazans deeper into poverty, creating fertile ground for militant groups.
9938	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	There has been intense speculation about a possible al-Qaida presence in the Palestinian territories since the 2001 terror attacks on New York and Washington.
9939	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	Palestinian intelligence officials believe the terror network has formed some sleeper cells in Gaza, and suspect possible al-Qaida involvement in several spectacular attempts to assassinate Palestinian security commanders since 2004.
9940	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	Israel also insists al Qaida has put down roots in Gaza, a claim denied by Hamas.
9941	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	Some Gazans the visit of Bush's predecessor, Bill Clinton, to Gaza in 1998.
9942	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	At the time, peace hopes ran high, and Clinton was given a hero's welcome in the coastal territory.
9943	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	"We were full of joy and hope on that day (of Clinton's visit)," said Shawki Abdel Rahman, 59, a retired teacher, who watched Bush's arrival on a large-screen TV in a Gaza electronics store.
9944	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	"Today, it's the opposite," he said.
9945	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	"There is no peace and no joy over this visit."
9946	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	---
9947	APW_ENG_20080109.0836.LDC2009T13	AP reporter Sarah El Deeb contributed to this report from Khan Younis.
