10594	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai claims he won an outright victory, but independent observers say it is more likely that he would face a runoff election against 84 -year-old Mugabe.
10595	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	MDC Secretary-General Tendai Biti said Sunday that there were clear signs of irregularities in the recount.
10596	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	The opposition also claimed mounting violence and intimidation against people who voted for their candidates, especially in rural areas that once were Mugabe strongholds.
10597	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Violence had displaced 3,000 people, injured 500 and left 10 dead, Biti said at a news conference in South Africa.
10598	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	It was impossible to verify the claims because of reporting restrictions in Zimbabwe.
10599	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Biti said key members of the opposition's administration had been arrested, along with more than 400 supporters.
10600	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Biti and Tsvangirai -- who has been accused of treason -- say they cannot return to Zimbabwe because they would face immediate arrest.
10601	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Elections officials said the recount was going smoothly.
10602	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	But "there are signs that the counting might take longer than the three days we had projected," the Herald quoted Utloile Silaigwana, a deputy chief elections officer, as saying.
10603	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	He said the delay was mainly due to party agents "raising issues which they would want attended to and clarified."
10604	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	The Herald said in some constituencies, counting was proceeding at a "snail's pace" and was likely to take about one week to complete.
10605	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Kohler-Barnard said the process was marred by delays and administrative problems.
10606	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	"The repeated miscommunication of venue addresses meant that party agents and electoral observers were frequently posted to the incorrect venue, thus undermining the observation process and contributing to further delays in the recount," she said.
10607	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	She went on to list specific instances of ballot box irregularities.
10608	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	International pressure on Mugabe to release the election results continued to mount.
10609	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	The government of neighboring Malawi called for Zimbabwe's government to resume talks with former colonizer Britain, white farmers and the opposition party -- all of whom Mugabe considers his enemies.
10610	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	The statement, dated Sunday, indicated growing differences among southern African leaders on how to help resolve Zimbabwe's crisis.
10611	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	"The Government of Malawi believes that the people of Zimbabwe should not live in the past.
10612	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	They must move on.
10613	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Therefore, we believe that a new set of negotiations could be initiated at different levels ... so that Zimbabwe can begin to develop and transform its economy," the statement said.
10614	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Zimbabwe's economy, with inflation raging beyond 100,500 percent, began unraveling when Mugabe ordered takeovers in the late 1990s of large, fertile farms owned by a few thousand minority whites.
10615	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	Britain initially had paid to buy some of the farms but stopped, saying Mugabe was giving the land to cronies and relatives instead of landless blacks Zimbabweans.
10616	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	New negotiations for British support for land reform ended in 1997 when Britain's Labour Party won power from the Conservatives and said it had no responsibility for whites who own farms in Zimbabwe.
10617	APW_ENG_20080421.0526.LDC2009T13	U.N. Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon said he was discussing the crisis with African leaders on the sidelines of a five-day U.N. trade meeting that opened Sunday in Ghana.
