10697	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Japan says no need to impose broad ban on US beef
10698	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	TOKYO 2008-04-24 04:16:27 UTC
10699	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Japan will not impose a blanket ban on U.S. beef imports, despite the discovery of a spinal column in a meat shipment from an American processing plant, a government spokesman said Thursday.
10700	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Japan this week temporarily halted beef shipments from a U.S. plant after finding the spinal column, which violated a trade accord prohibiting parts believed to pose a risk of mad cow disease.
10701	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	But Chief Cabinet Secretary Nobutaka Machimura said the violation was apparently an isolated case, and Tokyo would not retaliate by blocking all beef shipments from the United States.
10702	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	"We understand this is not a systematic problem concerning U.S. exports to Japan and there is no need to impose an import ban," he told reporters.
10703	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	"But this is clearly unwelcome, and we asked the U.S. government to fully abide by conditions concerning Japan-bound shipments," Machimura added.
10704	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	The spinal column was discovered Monday at a Japanese meat- processing factory during an inspection, said a statement from the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries and the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare.
10705	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	It was found in one of 700 boxes shipped from National Beef California LP and imported by trading house Itochu Corp., the statement said.
10706	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Shipments from the U.S.-based company have been halted.
10707	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Japan imposed a ban on U.S. beef imports in December 2003 after the first case of mad cow disease was found in the United States.
10708	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	The ban was lifted in 2005, but imposed again in January 2006 after an import violation.
10709	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	U.S. beef imports resumed in July 2006, but sales are a fraction of what they used to be.
10710	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Japan's finicky consumers are sensitive to suggestions American meat is unsafe, and some officials urged U.S. producers to be more careful.
10711	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	"This should not happen again," said Health Minister Yoichi Masuzoe.
10712	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	"We will continue to make maximum measures to ensure food safety."
10713	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	The U.S. Embassy said Wednesday an investigation would be conducted to find out what happened, but added that the meat shipment itself was completely safe.
10714	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Under the agreement, Japan accepts only meat from cattle 20 months of age and younger, which are thought to pose less of a risk of the disease.
10715	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	U.S. exporters must also remove spinal columns, brain tissue and other materials from shipments bound for Japan.
10716	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	Mad cow disease, formally known as bovine spongiform encephalopathy, is a degenerative nerve disease in cattle.
10717	APW_ENG_20080424.0202.LDC2009T13	In humans, eating meat products contaminated with the illness is linked to variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, a rare and fatal malady.
