11082	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	The news magazine also said Loeffler listed meeting McCain along with the Saudi ambassador to "discuss US-Kingdom of Saudi Arabia relations," even though Loeffler told a reporter last month that he had not discussed his clients with McCain.
11083	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	McCain's new policy prohibits any staffer on the campaign from being a registered lobbyist or foreign agent.
11084	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	Part-time volunteers for the campaigns, such as Loeffler, have to disclose whether they are registered lobbyists or lobbying on behalf of foreign entities.
11085	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	Under the policy, dated May 15, such volunteer advisers cannot lobby McCain or his legislative staffs during the period they serve on the campaign.
11086	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	The work of lobbyists close to McCain had become fodder for critics, undermining McCain's image as a reformer who has tried to restrict the influence special interests in government.
11087	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	McCain advisers Doug Goodyear, who was to run the Republican convention in St. Paul, Minnesota, and Doug Davenport, a regional campaign director for the Mid-Atlantic states, also resigned this month.
11088	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	Both worked for DCI Group, a consulting firm hired to improve the image of Myanmar's military junta.
11089	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	When the policy was announced last week, McCain fired energy policy adviser Eric Burgeson, who represents energy companies as a lobbyist.
11090	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	The campaign also asked Craig Shirley to resign from McCain's Virginia leadership team because he was behind an independent group that has been criticizing Democrats Hillary Rodham Clinton and Barack Obama on the Internet.
11091	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	McCain's new policy also states that no one with a campaign title or position may participate in so-called 527 groups, which can raise unlimited amounts of money for television ads not controlled by campaigns.
11092	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	But the policy also underscored the fine line McCain has drawn.
11093	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	Several top strategists working on his campaign are lobbyists who have taken leaves of absence from their jobs to work for McCain.
11094	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	Among them are campaign manager Rick Davis, whose past clients have included a Russian industrialist, and Charlie Black, a high profile Washington lobbyist with domestic and foreign clients
11095	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	In adopting the policy and making it public, the McCain campaign sought to stabilize the bad press he was getting and turn the tables on his most likely Democratic opponent.
11096	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	"Sen. McCain has put forward the most strident policy to date," said McCain spokeswoman Jill Hazelbaker.
11097	APW_ENG_20080518.0886.LDC2009T13	"It now falls on Barack Obama to meet this level of transparency and disclose which lobbyists are serving as advisers to his campaign."
