11382	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	The siege of the mosque came amid an increasingly violent anti- vice campaign led by the mosque's administrators in which roaming bands of students harassed music and video shops, sometimes kidnapping women accused of being prostitutes.
11383	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	Tensions boiled over into gunbattles with security forces trying to enforce government authority.
11384	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	The government said 102 people, including 11 security personnel, were killed in the standoff that began July 3 last year.
11385	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	The siege seriously undermined the government's reputation among ordinary Pakistanis, many of whom believe far more people died, including women and children.
11386	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	A year later, the mosque siege still resonates among militant groups, which have referred to it in videos as a rallying cry.
11387	APW_ENG_20080706.0397.LDC2009T13	Mohammed Amir Siddiq, a spokesman for the Red Mosque, denounced Sunday's suicide attack and said he was not aware if any of those at the anniversary gathering were wounded.
