11621	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	At least 9 climbers feared dead in K-2 avalanche
11622	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan 2008-08-04 00:46:15 UTC
11623	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	At least nine climbers were feared dead on K-2, the world's second-highest mountain, after an avalanche cut ropes used to cross a treacherous wall of ice, officials and other climbers said Sunday.
11624	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Several other mountaineers were missing, prompting a desperate rescue effort on the peak in northern Pakistan, which is regarded as more dangerous to climb than Mount Everest.
11625	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	A total of 22 people, mostly foreigners, in eight different groups scaled K-2's summit on Friday, said Nazir Sabir of the Alpine Club of Pakistan.
11626	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	As they made their way down, an avalanche carried away ropes fixed 1,148 feet (350 meters) below the peak, sweeping some climbers to their deaths and stranding others at a height where they would likely succumb to exposure, Sabir said.
11627	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Accounts varied on the number of dead and how they died.
11628	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Sabir said nine people died in the avalanche.
11629	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Included in that number, were two rescuers -- a Nepalese sherpa and a Pakistani porter -- who survivors said fell to their death.
11630	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Mohammed Akram, vice president of the Adventure Foundation of Pakistan, a nonprofit organization, said one rescue team dispatched Sunday had reached a Dutchman and an Italian suffering from frostbite and were helping them down toward a camp at an altitude of 21,325 feet (6,500 meters).
11631	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	He said helicopter crews spotted survivors, but could not pluck them to safety because the air is too thin for them to operate so high.
11632	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	The fixed rope lines were strung across a point on the mountain known as "The Bottleneck."
11633	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Chris Warner, an American who climbed K-2 last year, said it was the deadliest place on the mountain, the fall from there down the south face is some 9,000 feet (2,740 meters).
11634	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	"You can see how for people who were exhausted, it would have been nearly impossible for them to descend without the ropes," said Warner.
11635	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	He said hope was fading for anyone still alive and separated from their group.
11636	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	"Once their hands and feet are frozen, they really are unable to move on their own power, and it takes other people to carry them down," he said.
11637	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	At 28,250 feet (8,610 meters), K-2 stands about 785 feet (240 meters) below Mount Everest, but is a "phenomenally dangerous mountain," said Alan Arnett, who climbed a nearby peak with at least one of the missing climbers.
11638	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Compared with Everest, "it's more technical, it's steeper, the weather is more intense," he said.
11639	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	The toll from the avalanche was the highest from a single incident on K-2 since at least 1995, when seven climbers died after being caught in a fierce storm.
11640	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	About 280 people have summited K-2 since 1954, when it was first conquered by Italians Achille Compagnoni and Lino Lacedell.
11641	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Dozens of deaths have been recorded since 1939, most of them occurring during the descent.
11642	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	---
11643	APW_ENG_20080804.0029.LDC2009T13	Associated Press writers Zarar Khan in Islamabad and Lily Hindy in Washington contributed to this report.
