11896	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Deutsche Bank paying $575,000 fine
11897	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	WASHINGTON 2008-09-10 22:55:50 UTC
11898	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Deutsche Bank Securities Inc. has agreed to pay a $575,000 fine in a settlement over alleged violations of short-selling rules in 2005 and 2006, New York Stock Exchange regulators said Wednesday.
11899	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	It was the largest fine ever levied by NYSE Regulation for alleged trading violations on NYSE Arca, the sibling electronic exchange.
11900	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Deutsche Bank also was censured in the disciplinary action.
11901	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	The investment firm neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing.
11902	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	The regulators said that between January 2005 and October 2006, Deutsche Bank executed a number of short sales on ineligible stocks without having borrowed the shares, made arrangements for borrowing them, or having "reasonable grounds" to believe they could be borrowed when necessary.
11903	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	The stocks in question weren't on the firm's list of securities that are allowed to be sold short in that fashion, the regulators said.
11904	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	That was in violation of securities regulations related to short- selling, they said.
11905	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Deutsche Bank also failed to adequately supervise some traders who engaged in the short sales, according to the regulators.
11906	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Short sellers bet that a stock's price will fall so that they can profit from it.
11907	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	They borrow shares of the stock and sell them.
11908	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	If the price drops, they buy cheaper actual shares to cover the borrowed ones, pocketing the difference.
11909	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	So-called "naked" short selling occurs when sellers don't even borrow the shares before selling them, and then look to cover positions immediately after the sale.
11910	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	"We're pleased to resolve this matter," Deutsche Bank spokesman Ted Meyer said.
11911	APW_ENG_20080910.1471.LDC2009T13	Deutsche Bank AG, the German bank that is the investment firm's parent, rose 89 cents, or 1 percent, to end at $85.61 in trading Wednesday.
