12109	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"Every one of us is actually positive about the agreement, or the need to cement the agreement and make it work," Mugabe said.
12110	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"I don't see any reason why we can't work together as Zimbabweans," he said.
12111	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"We are all sons of the soil, as we say, and the differences arise purely from own conceptions of what Zimbabwe should be and what the government of Zimbabwe should be."
12112	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Tsvangirai won the most votes in March presidential polling, but not enough to avoid a runoff against Mugabe.
12113	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	An onslaught of violence against Tsvangirai's supporters led him to drop out of the presidential runoff and Mugabe was declared the overwhelming winner of the second vote, which was widely denounced as a sham.
12114	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	More than 100 opposition supporters were killed in the violence, thousands of people were beaten up and suffered broken limbs, and tens of thousands were forced from their homes.
12115	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe, who has been in power since independence from Britain in 1980, and Tsvangirai have been enemies for a decade.
12116	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Tsvangirai has been jailed, beaten, tortured and tried for treason -- charges that were dismissed in court.
12117	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	But Mugabe made clear Wednesday that he was willing to share power with Tsvangirai, who would become prime minister under the agreement, leading a council of ministers responsible for government policies and reporting to a Cabinet headed by Mugabe.
12118	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Still, Mugabe did not spell out who would have the final say if there was a major disagreement.
12119	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	And while he repeated several times that all parties want the agreement to work, Mugabe dismissed Tsvangirai's Movement for Democratic Change as a creation of Britain's three major parties and beholden to its government.
12120	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe described Zimbabwe's government as a pyramid with the president at the top, but he said "the president never settles on the matter alone," and always works with the vice presidents.
12121	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"And now that we have a prime minister we rope him in and we discuss in the presidency, or whatever we call it, together, and we look at the issues and see what solutions can be applied to any problem that confronts us," Mugabe said.
12122	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	The power-sharing deal was mediated during months of negotiations by Thabo Mbeki, who has been forced to step down from the South African presidency by the country's ruling party.
12123	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe said it was up to the Southern African Development Community to decide whether Mbeki continued as mediator.
12124	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	But the Zimbabwean president offered praise, saying Mbeki has been "quite excellent."
12125	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"There is a man who has been in the seat for so many years as the father of the African National Congress and democracy in one stroke pulls him down," Mugabe said of Mbeki.
12126	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"Democracy without morality is no democracy for all."
12127	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Tsvangirai has repeatedly said he does not want a legal witch hunt in Zimbabwe, but that he believes some kind of truth and reconciliation process is necessary to allow healing after years of violence and repression.
12128	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe disagreed.
12129	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"At the moment, the fight between us has been one between Britain and ourselves -- Britain, of course, using as their front the opposition," Mugabe said.
12130	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"So the British and the Americans, they've got to be reconciled to us."
12131	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Western nations, who have shunned Mugabe's government and whose aid and investment are sorely needed, have reacted cautiously to the coalition agreement.
12132	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Millions of dollars in aid are expected to flow in if Mugabe actually shares power.
12133	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe said Wednesday the West should now begin removing "demonic" sanctions, which have targeted individuals and companies seen to be supporting his regime.
12134	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	They were tightened after elections this spring and the European Union recently added an arms ban.
12135	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"We don't expect investment from countries that are hostile," Mugabe said.
12136	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"They can keep their investment, but we would hope in the first place that sanctions would be lifted.
12137	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	There is no reason for imposing sanctions on Zimbabwe at all.
12138	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	There has never been any reason for it, you see, except hostility."
12139	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	European Union foreign ministers have welcomed the power-sharing deal but have said that Mugabe must prove he is willing to restore democratic rule before EU sanctions can be lifted.
12140	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Zimbabwe has the world's highest inflation rate even by the official figure of at 11 million percent, and independent economists put it much higher.
12141	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Critics have linked Zimbabwe's economic slide to Mugabe's 2000 order that commercial farms be seized from whites.
12142	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe says the land reform program was meant to help poor blacks and blames the country's economic collapse on Western sanctions.
12143	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Food, fuel, hospital supplies and other necessities are scarce as prices skyrocket in the region's former breadbasket.
12144	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	And millions of Zimbabweans, including doctors, teachers, business owners and others with important skills, have fled the country.
12145	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	Mugabe said Wednesday that Zimbabwe can return to its former economic status, saying "if only the West can leave us alone, you will certainly see us come up."
12146	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	"It will take us time because we have lost some time because of sanctions," he said.
12147	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	While critics have complained about Zimbabwe's human rights record, Mugabe said the African Union and southern African leaders have not.
12148	APW_ENG_20080925.0081.LDC2009T13	When asked whether he would allow Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International to come in, he replied: "Ha!
