12168	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	US ' casino ' mentality blamed for planet ' s meltdown
12169	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	SAO PAULO, Brazil 2008-10-01 14:50:36 UTC
12170	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	Astounded by the U.S. government's failure to resolve the financial crisis threatening the foundations of the global free market, fingers of blame are pointing at America from around the planet.
12171	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	National leaders and ordinary people say the U.S. must quickly fix the financial crisis it created before the rest of the world's hard-won economic gains are lost.
12172	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	"The managers of big business took huge risks out of greed," said President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, whose economy is highly dependent on U.S. trade.
12173	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	"What happens in the United States will affect the entire world and, above all, small countries like ours."
12174	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	In Europe, where some blame a phenomenon of "casino capitalism" that has become deeply engrained from New York to London to Moscow, there is more of a sense of shared responsibility.
12175	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	But Europeans also blame the U.S. government for letting things get out of hand.
12176	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	"I have to do with this situation all the time," said Norbert Weigel, a merchant banker smoking a cigarette near Frankfurt's main station Wednesday morning.
12177	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	"Surely the Americans are to blame.
12178	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	Investment bankers made investments on products where they didn't understand the risk and were trying to make fast profits."
12179	APW_ENG_20081001.0688.LDC2009T13	Mezat Oyena, a native of southwestern Turkey who owns a barbershop in Berlin's central Mitte neighborhood, blames the crisis for a dropoff in his business.
