12351	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	US authorities shutter worldwide spam operation
12352	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	CHICAGO 2008-10-14 21:50:13 UTC
12353	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	One of the largest spam operations in the world, a vast network involving countries from New Zealand to China and the United States, has been shut down, the Federal Trade Commission announced Tuesday.
12354	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The spammers sent out billions of e-mails in recent years encouraging people to click through to Web sites that allegedly used false claims to peddle prescription drugs, as well as "male enhancement" and weight-loss pills.
12355	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The FTC has received more than 3 million complaints about the spam and related Web sites, illustrating the scale of the operation, officials said.
12356	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The sites, including one called "Canadian Healthcare," were difficult to distinguish from legitimate online pharmacies -- making the pitches more persuasive, said Steve Baker, the FTC's Midwest Region director.
12357	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	"These sites are really professionally constructed," he said.
12358	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	"Some years ago you used to be able to tell the bogus things because they looked cheesy and had misspellings.
12359	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Anymore, I don't think that's true."
12360	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The operation violated the federal CAN-SPAM Act of 2003, meant to restrict commercial spam, by using false header information to hide the origin of messages, not offering an opt-out link and failing to list a postal address, the FTC said.
12361	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The FTC hasn't determined a total sales figure, but it likely to ran into the millions of dollars, Baker said.
12362	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The case should remind consumers to beware of spam, he said.
12363	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	"If you find your way to these Web sites through spam, you should really be asking yourself if you can trust them at all," Baker said.
12364	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	A federal judge in Chicago issued a temporary injunction to halt the operation and also froze its assets.
12365	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	The Federal Bureau of Investigation is investigating and those involved could also face criminal charges, Baker said.
12366	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Those spearheading the enterprise, known as "Affking" on the Internet, included a U.S. and a New Zealand citizen, according to court documents.
12367	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Servers in China hosted the Web sites and the drugs were shipped from India, while operatives in Cyprus and the former Soviet republic of Georgia processed credit card information, Baker said.
12368	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	As part of their inquiry, FTC staff made undercover purchases from the sites.
12369	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	No one asked the clandestine buyers to provide verification of a prescription and the shipped drugs did not include doctors' instructions or dosage information, officials said.
12370	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Meanwhile, federal prosecutors in Detroit have won their first conviction in a case involving spam e-mail and efforts to manipulate the price of Chinese stocks.
12371	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	A 56-year-old East Lansing woman pleaded guilty Tuesday to conspiracy and aiding fraud.
12372	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Judy Devenow is one of 11 people charged with illegally sending spam to generate excitement about Chinese stocks.
12373	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Devenow worked for Alan Ralsky of suburban Detroit, who is accused of running the spam scam.
12374	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Authorities say he made $3 million just in summer 2005 by trading in and out of Chinese stocks on U.S. exchanges.
12375	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	Devenow says she was paid $150,000 to send several million e-mails a day from January 2004 through September 2005.
12376	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	She has agreed to cooperate with prosecutors against her co-defendants.
12377	APW_ENG_20081014.1380.LDC2009T13	---
