12770	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	European stocks drop as Dow erases early gains
12771	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	LONDON 2008-11-21 17:06:10 UTC
12772	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	European markets fell further Friday as early gains on Wall Street were wiped out amid mounting fears about the U.S. economy and the future of banking giant Citigroup Inc. in particular.
12773	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Asian stocks closed mostly higher earlier in the day.
12774	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Despite opening some 150 points higher following Thursday's 445 point slide, the Dow Jones industrial average was up only 16.09 points, or 0.2 percent at 7,568.38.
12775	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Meanwhile, the broader Standard &amp
12776	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Poor's 500 index was 10.06 points, or 1.3 percent, higher at 762.50, having ended Thursday at 752, its lowest close since April 1997.
12777	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	European stocks, which had not suffered as much as their U.S. counterparts on Thursday, tumbled on the renewed selling on Wall Street, with the FTSE 100 index of leading British shares closing down 94.03 points, or 2.4 percent, at 3,780.96.
12778	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Germany's DAX was down 92.79 points, or 2.2 percent, at 4,127.41 while the CAC-40 in France was down 99.16 points, or 3.3 percent, at 2,881.26.
12779	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Earlier, Asian markets recouped early losses in the wake of Thursday's sell-off on Wall Street to end up in positive territory.
12780	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Japan's Nikkei 225 stock average rose 207.75, or 2.7 percent, to 7,910.79, and Hong Kong's Hang Seng index jumped 2.9 percent to 12,659.20.
12781	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Despite the earlier Asian gains, stock markets are generally on a renewed downtrend, ending the week sharply lower than where they started.
12782	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	"Concerns of a more severe recession than expected, the return of deflation fears and the lack of new effective initiatives taken by policymakers are pushing investors to sell higher-risk assets," said Calyon analyst Herve Goulletquer.
12783	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	This week's jitters were stoked primarily by concerns about the futures of Citigroup Inc. and the U.S. car industry.
12784	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Citigroup's future remains up in the air despite a report that said the banking giant was considering a sale to rebuild investor confidence.
12785	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	The New York-based bank is scheduled to hold a board meeting Friday to discuss whether to sell all or part of itself, The Wall Street Journal reported.
12786	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	But as no hard news emerged from the company about that possibility, Citigroup's shares tumbled below $4 a share to their lowest level in more than 15 years.
12787	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	That extended a sharp, weeklong plunge that could not be stemmed by Saudi investor Prince Alwaleed bin Talal's decision Thursday to raise his stake in the company to 5 percent from less than 4 percent.
12788	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Investors have been worried that losses from souring debt will swamp banks, even those given financial support from the government's $700 billion rescue plan.
12789	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Citigroup, in particular, is a source of big concern for the markets as the company hasn't turned a profit in the past four quarters, unlike rivals such as JPMorgan Chase &amp
12790	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Co. and Bank of America Corp.
12791	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	European investors were also spooked by a survey showing that the recession in the euro-zone may be deeper than many feared.
12792	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	The monthly preliminary estimate of the purchasing managers index for the manufacturing sector slumped to a record low of 36.2 in November from 41.1 the previous month, while the equivalent estimate for the services sector also dropped to a record low, at 43.3 in November from October's 45.8.
12793	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Earlier in Asia, South Korea's Kospi surged 5.8 percent and Australia's market closed up 1.9 percent after initially falling more than 3 percent.
12794	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	But mainland China's Shanghai Composite index slipped 0.7 percent and markets in the Philippines and Indonesia also sank.
12795	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Financial, real estate and technology stocks led the recovery in Asia, particularly in Hong Kong, where HSBC Holdings PCL jumped 4.5 percent, China Construction Bank Corp. rose 6.7 percent and Standard Chartered Bank increased 4.5 percent.
12796	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Oil prices, which have fallen to a third of their July peak, edged up in London trading.
12797	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	Light, sweet oil for January delivery rose 30 cents to $49.72 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange after earlier falling as low as $48.25, the lowest since May 2005.
12798	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	In currencies, the dollar rose 1.3 percent to 94.81 yen while the euro was up 1.1 percent at $1.2579.
12799	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	---
12800	APW_ENG_20081121.0850.LDC2009T13	AP Business Writers Tim Paradis in New York and Stephen Wright in Bangkok contributed to this report.
12801	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Dow up 494 as Obama prepares to name treasury boss
12802	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK 2008-11-21 23:40:14 UTC
12803	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Wall Street put a stop to a terrifying decline and stormed higher Friday as President-elect Barack Obama appeared ready to tap the chief of the New York Federal Reserve as the next treasury secretary and hand him the herculean task of righting the U.S. financial system.
12804	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The Dow Jones industrial average, which had broken even for the day until news of the nomination leaked about an hour before the close, raced upward and finished 494 points higher, a rally of more than 6 1/2 percent.
12805	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The outbreak of buying pushed the Dow above 8,000 -- a figure that would have seemed like a nightmare three months ago but on Friday was a relief for Americans who have watched their investments and retirement savings drain away with alarming speed.
12806	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	In the two previous days, the Dow had lost a staggering 873 points, more than 10 percent of its value, and the broader Standard &amp
12807	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Poor's 500 index had sunk to its lowest level since 1997.
12808	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The turnaround came when word reached Wall Street that Obama was likely to nominate New York Fed president Timothy Geithner, 47, for treasury secretary.
12809	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Geithner would assume top responsibility for tackling what threatens to be the deepest recession in a generation.
12810	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Financial markets despise uncertainty, and investors were looking for a clear message from Obama on who will make up his economic brain trust.
12811	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Wall Street had been voicing increasing frustration with Henry Paulson, the current treasury secretary, over his erratic handling of the federal financial rescue system.
12812	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	"Something needed to be done on the economy," said Ben Halliburton, chief investment officer at Tradition Capital Management.
12813	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	"The fact that they've got the team together, maybe that is going to shorten the period of indecision."
12814	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Elsewhere, the government continued its efforts to shore up the financial system.
12815	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. also said it would guarantee up to $1.4 trillion in U.S. bank debt for more than three years as part of the government's financial rescue plan.
12816	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The decision is aimed at breaking the logjam of bank-to-bank lending.
12817	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The health of the economy depends on the free flow of credit, and credit markets cinched up again as the market plunged earlier this week.
12818	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The Friday afternoon rally managed to prevent the week from being one of the few most dismal in Wall Street history.
12819	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	Corporate mainstays running the gamut from Gap Inc. to Alcoa Inc. and Walt Disney Co. to Microsoft Corp. surged by double-digit amounts.
12820	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	But it did not erase heavy losses for the week.
12821	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The Dow finished down about 5 percent for the five days, and other major averages suffered, too -- 8 percent for the S&amp
12822	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	P 500, nearly 9 percent for the Nasdaq.
12823	APW_ENG_20081121.1345.LDC2009T13	The Dow finished at 8,046, and the S&amp
