13162	APW_ENG_20081218.1231.LDC2009T13	The New York-based Conference Board, a private research group, said its index of leading economic indicators fell for the second straight month, dropping 0.4 percent in November.
13163	APW_ENG_20081218.1231.LDC2009T13	That was slightly better than expected.
13164	APW_ENG_20081218.1231.LDC2009T13	And the Philadelphia Federal Reserve said regional manufacturing is contracting in December, but not by as much as in November.
13165	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Ripples of Madoff scandal spread everywhere
13166	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK 2008-12-20 23:36:14 UTC
13167	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In the nonprofit legal center Steven Schwartz runs from a converted furniture store in Massachussets, the e-mail was very good news: By week's end, a check for $243,000 would be on its way.
13168	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The money couldn't come soon enough.
13169	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The sharp downturn in the economy had put Schwartz's group -- working to improve treatment of teen offenders with mental illnesses -- under very tight budget pressure.
13170	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	At least the check was a promise he could count on.
13171	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	By that Thursday, though, events were unfolding 160 miles (258 kilometers) away that would upend those assumptions and assurances.
13172	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In a federal courtroom in lower Manhattan, a Wall Street wizard stood before a judge, charged with running a $50 billion fraud that targeted scores of wealthy and powerful investors.
13173	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The name of the accused, Bernard L. Madoff, meant nothing to Schwartz and why should it?
13174	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	He'd never heard of the money manager with the beachfront mansion and the 55-foot (17-meter) yacht.
13175	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	They'd certainly never met.
13176	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	There was no reason to think they had anything in common.
13177	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Except, it turned out, the money.
13178	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In the days since Madoff's Dec. 11 arrest, the tale has repeatedly been told of wealthy victims who, perhaps naively, invested their trust in a man who promised financial miracles.
13179	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	But the scale of the Madoff scandal can just as well be measured in its still-widening ripples, reaching far-flung people and causes -- from a group helping just-released inmates find jobs in Rhode Island to another working to provide fresh food in poor neighborhoods in Detroit and Oakland, California.
13180	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Their future is now in jeopardy -- a painful reminder of the financial web linking very different worlds.
13181	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	---
13182	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Signing up companies for office space in Manhattan skyscrapers made Norman F. Levy a very rich man.
13183	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In the hotly competitive but tight-knit world of New York commercial real estate, Levy worked across more than seven decades brokering leases in midtown's towers.
13184	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	When he died in 2005 at 93, he was hailed as an elder statesman of the trade whose zest for the deal was matched by his generosity with both friendship and money.
13185	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"Your spirit and love of life have touched and changed all who knew you," one friend of 40 years wrote in a paid death notice for Levy that ran in The New York Times.
13186	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"You taught me so much.
13187	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	I'll cherish our relationship forever."
13188	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The friend was Bernard Madoff.
13189	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The real estate broker and the money manager were separated by 26 years, but they and their families had formed a friendship reinforced by shared interests, social circles -- and trust.
13190	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Levy and Madoff were active in some of the same organizations, like New York's Yeshiva University.
13191	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	They donated their money to many of the same causes -- groups including the Lincoln Center Theater and Gift of Life, a South Florida charity that tries to save Jewish leukemia victims by matching them with bone marrow donors.
13192	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In the summer, both families headed to the Hamptons.
13193	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	When Norman F. Levy died, he was staying at his daughter's house fronting the Atlantic, just a few sprawling lots away from the mansion owned by the Madoffs.
13194	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	For more than 30 years, the Levys also entrusted their personal investments to Madoff.
13195	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	When they chartered the Betty and Norman F. Levy Foundation -- which reported assets last year of $244.4 million -- as the vehicle for their charitable giving, they again put their trust in their longtime friend.
13196	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"My father believed in Bernie Madoff," Norman Levy's son, Francis -- who declined to comment for this article -- said in a recent interview with FOX Business News.
13197	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"The one thing he said about Bernie (was), "If there's one honorable person, it's Bernie."
13198	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	---
13199	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Francis Levy, a novelist, and his sister, Jeanne Levy Church, had no reason to think otherwise.
13200	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	When Norman Levy died, they took the helm of the family philanthropy, leaving the funds invested with Madoff, whose offices were housed in the same Third Avenue tower as the foundation.
13201	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The Levy Foundation continued donations to longtime favorite charities.
13202	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	But its biggest checks went to a new set of organizations created by Norman Levy's children to champion causes they embraced.
13203	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In 2000, Jeanne set up the JEHT Foundation, whose name is an acronym for Justice, Equality, Human dignity and Tolerance -- originally to work on criminal justice reform, an area where funds are scarce.
13204	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Last year, the Levy family financed JEHT to the tune of $29.9 million.
13205	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Levy Church, and her husband, Kenneth, "felt that they were fortunate in their life to have this remarkable amount of money and they felt they wanted to use it for less fortunate people," said Robert Crane, president of the JEHT Foundation.
13206	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Francis Levy co-founded the Philoctetes Center, a group dedicated to fostering discussions of everything from literature to economics.
13207	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In 2007, the Levy Foundation financed Philoctetes with $950,000.
13208	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Last year, Francis Levy invited his family's longtime friend, Madoff, to appear on a panel at the center to talk about the workings of Wall Street.
13209	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	More recently, the Levy Churches formed another group, the Fair Food Foundation, based in Ann Arbor, Mich., which set out to find ways to get fresher, healthy food to residents of poor city neighborhoods starting with Detroit and Oakland, California.
13210	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	None of the Levys' foundations are well-known to the general public.
13211	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	But they got an enthusiastic reception from groups across the country that were hungry for funding.
13212	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	At the walk-in counseling office run by Rhode Island Family Life Center in a poor neighborhood in South Providence, a JEHT grant of $500,000 over two years paid staffers who help inmates just released from prison find housing and jobs.
13213	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	In 2007, the group provided services to 1,000 people.
13214	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	A New Orleans group, Advocates for Environmental Human Rights, used a grant from JEHT to pursue a lawsuit charging "environmental racism" in the predominantly black Louisiana town of Mossville, where the soil and water are polluted by 14 surrounding factories.
13215	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	And in Schwartz's program in Massachusetts, JEHT offered a three- year grant for work in Connecticut, Texas, Alabama and elsewhere to get states to reconsider treatment of teen offenders with mental health problems, encouraging them to send some home with therapy or provide it in detention centers.
13216	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The JEHT grant accounted for 26 percent of the Center for Public Representation's annual budget.
13217	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Its importance became even more clear this fall when a state tax on real estate transactions that provides nearly as much of the group's funding dropped sharply with the collapse of the housing market, Schwartz said.
13218	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Still, Schwartz's staff of 11 was so certain of JEHT's backing that they moved ahead with new projects, spending about $25,000 in advance.
13219	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"We just trusted that we would get the money, and so rather than suspend the work until the check was in hand ... we do the work and expected the check will follow," Schwartz said.
13220	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	---
13221	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Crane, the director of the JEHT Foundation, was working late that Thursday evening when his cell phone rang.
13222	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	His benefactors, Jeanne and Kenneth Levy Church, were on the line.
13223	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"Are you sitting down?"
13224	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	they asked.
13225	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The couple told him they'd just come across a story online about the arrest of a New York money manager whose name soundly vaguely familiar to Crane.
13226	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	All the Levy Church's money was invested with Bernie Madoff.
13227	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	If it was gone, so was the foundation.
13228	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	On Monday morning Crane sent an e-mail to people at nearly 150 groups around the country that count on his foundation for $25 to $30 million in funding each year.
13229	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The checks they had been expecting would not be coming, he told them, and JEHT would close by the end of January.
13230	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Francis Levy's group, the Philoctetes Center, also announced it could not continue without a cash infusion.
13231	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The Fair Food Foundation, announced it would close, delivering what its president, Oran Hesterman called "a stinging blow" to activists working to improve nutrition in poor neighborhoods.
13232	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Leaders of some of the groups funded by the foundations said they had not even been aware that their money came from the Levy family.
13233	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Nor had they ever heard of Madoff.
13234	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Some groups, like the Rhode Island center that finds jobs and housing for former inmates, were relatively lucky.
13235	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	JEHT provides a third of its annual budget, but the check for 2009 had already been cashed.
13236	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	The impact will become clear next year when the group tries to replace that money in an economy that has made fundraising increasingly difficult, Executive Director Sol Rodriguez said.
13237	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	For others, the impact was immediate.
13238	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	Between the JEHT closure and the drop in tax revenues, Schwartz's group has seen 48 percent of its budget vanish.
13239	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	On Wednesday, he called an emergency meeting with his staff.
13240	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	They've put juvenile justice projects in Texas and Alabama on hold.
13241	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	But those are emergency measures, not a solution.
13242	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"We don't have any money," he said.
13243	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"I'm not sure what we're going to do."
13244	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	It's a strange paradox, Schwartz and others in his situation say.
13245	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	All the attention swirling around Madoff has been about his wealthy lifestyle and the ultra-rich investors in places like Palm Beach and Hollywood and New York who lost their shirts.
13246	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	But few seem to understand the repercussions.
13247	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"It's very ironic that the very wealthiest in the country can have such a severe impact on kids on the low end of the totem pole," said Mark Steward, whose Missouri Youth Services Institute has relied on funding from the Levy family to help improve juvenile detention centers in Santa Clara County, California, Washington, D.C. and elsewhere.
13248	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	If only Madoff knew, Steward mused -- "Or maybe he does know."
13249	APW_ENG_20081220.0593.LDC2009T13	"Sometimes, they just don't care."
