13253	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Finance Minister Brian Lenihan said Sunday night that the boards of the three banks -- Allied Irish, Bank of Ireland and Anglo- Irish -- would issue preference shares paying fixed dividends to the government in exchange for the aid.
13254	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The plan still requires shareholder approval at emergency meetings expected next month.
13255	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The plan is designed to boost each bank's cash reserves and restore international confidence in Ireland's banking sector, which faces rising loan defaults and the prospect of worse to come from a deepening recession.
13256	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Allied Irish Banks PLC, Ireland's biggest bank, and No. 2 Bank of Ireland both are in line to receive euro2 billion.
13257	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	In return the government will receive preference shares paying a fixed 8 percent dividend -- or euro160 million a year from each bank -- as well as 25 percent of voting rights in the bank's board of directors.
13258	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Anglo-Irish Bank Corp., a specialist lender heavily exposed to the collapse of Ireland's property and construction markets, would fall under government control.
13259	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The government has agreed to pay euro1.5 billion for preference shares in Anglo-Irish that will pay a 10 percent fixed dividend, or euro150 million annually.
13260	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The government would receive 75 percent of voting rights if shareholders approve the plan.
13261	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Lenihan said all three banks could pay back the aid at face value within the next five years, or 125 percent of its value after five years.
13262	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	He also said the government was ready to provide more aid if the banks' share values and ability to lend didn't markedly improve.
13263	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The finance chief said the government was willing to underwrite the issuing of euro1 billion each in new Allied Irish and Bank of Ireland shares -- which means the government would purchase any new shares that existing shareholders decline to buy.
13264	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Bank of Ireland said it was interested in the government's underwriting offer.
13265	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Allied Irish said it remained hopeful of raising sufficient funds from selling its own assets, particularly its minority stake in M&amp
13266	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	T Bank Corp. of New York.
13267	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Lenihan said the government's representatives on the boards of all three banks would ensure that the banks increase mortgage lending by 30 percent and loans to small business by 10 percent.
13268	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	The banks also would be expected to back off defaulting mortgage- holders, giving them a six-month grace period.
13269	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Ireland's long-booming economy has gone swiftly into reverse over the past year.
13270	APW_ENG_20081222.0177.LDC2009T13	Its recession is forecast to deepen in 2009 and unemployment rise to 10 percent or more.
