13309	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	POLL FINDS GAP BETWEEN GROWTH FIGURES, POPULAR PERCEPTION
13310	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Taipei, June 5 (CNA) 06/05/07 20:36:01 (By Sofia Wu)
13311	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	A majority of respondents to a public opinion poll complained about lingering economic doldrums, declining income, inflating consumer prices and the widening wealth gap, pollsters said Tuesday.
13312	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	According to the results of the survey conducted by the China Times, a Taipei- based Chinese-language daily, 69 percent of the respondents said they feel the domestic economy is in bad shape, while 21 percent said the economy is "so-so," and only 4 percent gave the economy a positive review, with 6 percent refusing to answer the question.
13313	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	The telephone poll was conducted from May 30-June 1 among randomly chosen adults, with 829 valid samples collected and a margin of error of 3.5 percent recorded.
13314	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Compared with the findings of a similar survey conducted by the newspaper in mid-February, the ratio of those who perceived the economy as "sluggish" rose 21 percent while the percentage of those who felt the economy was "in good shape or robust" decreased 13 percent.
13315	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	The survey findings marked a sharp contrast to official growth figures.
13316	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	According to statistics released by the government, the country's gross domestic product (GDP) posted a 4.15 percent gain year-on-year in the first quarter of this year.
13317	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Superficially, Taiwan's economy has continued to grow, but the poll found that few respondents are upbeat about their economic well-being.
13318	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	According to the poll results, 47 percent said they are worried about a possible decrease in their real household income
13319	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	36 percent said they expect their family income to remain almost the same as last year
13320	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	while only 9 percent said they think their income is likely to increase.
13321	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	While the government has often touted a steady decline in the unemployment rate, but fear of job losses has continued to haunt many wage earners.
13322	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	The survey results show that 54 percent of the respondents said they are afraid of losing their jobs, compared to 43 percent who said they have no such worries.
13323	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Asked about their views on the current consumer price levels, 56 percent said they can hardly endure the present upward spiral
13324	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	32 percent said they perceive the price hikes to be moderate
13325	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	7 percent said they feel the price levels have remained almost unchanged
13326	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	and only a tiny number of respondents said they feel consumer prices are falling.
13327	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	The increasing wealth gap between rich and poor is now widely perceived, according to the poll.
13328	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Up to 88 percent of those surveyed said they think the rich-poor gap has been widening seriously while only 5 percent said the problem is not very serious.
13329	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Asked about Taiwan's current socio-economic structure, 56 percent perceived themselves as middle class in the social hierarchy, compared to 1 percent who perceive themselves as upper class and 35 percent who said they are at the bottom of society.
13330	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Meanwhile, 81 percent said they agree with the comment that Taiwan's middle class has disappeared, with wealth getting more concentrated among fewer people, while the poor are getting poorer.
13331	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	However, 11 percent said they disagree with the observation.
13332	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Generally speaking, 46 percent said their current livelihoods are roughly same as the previous year
13333	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	40 percent said their living standards have declined and only 13 percent said their living quality has improved.
13334	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	As for major obstacles to Taiwan's economic development, 42 percent said "government inaction due to partisan strife" is the most serious problem hindering economic development
13335	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	32 percent said official corruption and incompetence is to blame
13336	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	7 percent attributed the current woes to international competition
13337	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	and 6 percent said cross-Taiwan Strait issues are the main hindrance.
13338	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	Economists also attributed the gap between bright economic growth figures and bleak popular perception to a combination of factors, including the country's excessive reliance on exports for economic growth, relocation of a number of manufacturing industries to China and other areas to lower production costs, flagging private consumption and investment, zero growth in salaries for a large number of wage earners
13339	CNA_ENG_20070605.0036.LDC2009T13	and most of the economic growth benefits enjoyed by capitalists and corporate owners.
