13425	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	President Chen Shui-bian touted Friday his insistence on Taiwan's separate identity, the consolidation and deepening of Taiwan's young democracy, and the upholding of freedom of the press as his political legacies.
13426	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"I feel I have done right in standing firm on carving out a distinct Taiwanese identity separate from China and working hard to consolidate and deepen our young democracy," said a confident Chen in an interview with cable television station TVBS.
13427	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Reviewing his eight years in office, Chen said he also feels he has not let the country down in maintaining peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait and in promoting closer cross-strait exchanges.
13428	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"Despite occasional tension in cross-strait relations over the past years, none of them have ever deteriorated into a conflict or crisis.
13429	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	The situation has consistently been brought under control and cross-strait relations have generally remained stable and peaceful, as well as growing ever-closer economically," he said.
13430	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Asked about how a national leader should react to a national crisis, Chen said that although things may differ in nature and require different response strategies, fundamental beliefs and core values should be upheld without change.
13431	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"Without fundamental convictions, a national leader will be prone to wavering," he said.
13432	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Moreover, Chen went on, resilience is very important.
13433	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"A national leader must have the capacity to cope with stress, pressure and adversity and should not flip-flop on key policy issues under pressure from interest groups or the media," he added.
13434	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Noting that a national leader must take a stance conducive to national interests and the well-being of the people, Chen said Taiwan's president must insist on taking the correct path in the face of pressure from China and the international community, referring to his adamant attitude toward the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) -initiated referendum on seeking U.N. membership under the name of Taiwan, despite opposition from the United States, Europe and China.
13435	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	The referendum is set to take place alongside the March 22 presidential election.
13436	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	As to whether he felt despondent about the extremely low voter turnout for the two referendums held alongside the Jan. 12 legislative elections, Chen replied: "Not at all."
13437	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"Even though the referendums failed to pass the legal thresholds required for them to take effect, I don't think they were flops," Chen argued.
13438	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	One of the referendums was initiated by the DPP and asked voters whether the main opposition Kuomintang (KMT) should be required to return to the national coffers its ill-gotten party assets.
13439	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"The number of `yes' ballots cast for the `KMT assets' referendum was even higher than the total ballots the DPP garnered in the legislative elections," Chen said.
13440	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	As a matter of fact, he went on, the gap between voter turnout for the legislative elections and the "KMT assets" referendum -- 58.5 percent to 26 percent -- was slightly lower than the difference between the 2004 presidential election and the two defensive referendums held alongside -- 80 percent to 45 percent.
13441	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	In the 2004 presidential poll, Chen took 6.47 million ballots, while the number of ballots cast in each of the two defensive referendums held exceeded 7 million.
13442	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"None of the four national referendums held in the past was successful, mainly because of the unreasonably high legal threshold set forth by our existing Referendum Act, " Chen said, adding that he looks forward to seeing the law amended to lower the threshold.
13443	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Referring to his other legacies, Chen said he is gratified with the implementation of an alternative minimum tax system and a portable pension system, as well as the legislation of a national pension act that will take effect in October.
13444	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"All these moves are no easy task and we have made them at a price far lower than that endured by many other countries, " Chen said, adding that the enactment of these new systems have delivered on his campaign promises.
13445	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Chen refrained from commenting in detail on a recent incident involving four KMT lawmakers who gatecrashed DPP presidential candidate Frank Hsieh's campaign headquarters in an attempt to investigate whether Hsieh was unlawfully using the building, which belongs to the state-controlled First Financial Holding Co., as his campaign office.
13446	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"We should look at the incident from a macro-perspective, rather than just taking it as an isolated case.
13447	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	We should pay more heed to the impact of the expanding legislative power, which has led to many unprecedented developments and phenomena over the past years, including a six-month delay in legislative passage of the government budgets and unconstitutional provisions included in statutes regarding the National Communications Commission and the 319 Truth Commission," Chen said.
13448	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	On a KMT legislative caucus plan to enact a statute governing presidential power transition that will freeze the outgoing president's personnel and policy-making rights following every presidential election, Chen said such stipulations will violate constitutional provisions, as the president's powers and duties are prescribed in the Constitution, which cannot be overridden by an act passed by the lawmaking body.
13449	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Meanwhile, Chen revealed that he plans to come up with a new nomination list for Control Yuan seats for confirmation by the legislature, in which the KMT controls a more-than two-thirds majority.
13450	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	The country's top government watchdog body has remained empty since the term of previous Control Yuan members expired in January 2005 as the opposition-controlled legislature refused to review the Chen-proposed list.
13451	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"The roster will comprise elite members from relevant professional fields, " Chen said, adding that he hopes the legislature will not boycott his nomination this time around.
13452	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	With just slightly more than two months to go before his eight- year tenure expires, Chen said he keenly hopes that political bickering and antagonism between the KMT-led "pan-blue alliance" and the DPP-led "pan-green camp" can come to an end along with his retirement May 20.
13453	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	In another interview with the London-based Financial Times earlier in the week, Chen also touted his administration's achievements in overseeing a shift in sentiment for "Taiwanese identity" that appears irreversible.
13454	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"According to opinion polls, more than 70 percent of Taiwan's citizens now see themselves as Taiwanese rather than Chinese, up from about 30 percent before the DPP took power, " Chen told the Financial Times.
13455	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"If there hadn't been the past eight years of DPP rule and myself as president, Taiwan would have been taken by China after six years, " he said.
13456	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	"That is because of our insistence that Taiwan is a sovereign country, that Taiwan and the PRC are two sovereign countries that do not belong to each other."
13457	CNA_ENG_20080315.0014.LDC2009T13	Calling the rise of a distinct Taiwanese identity "a road of no return, " Chen argued in the interview that while Taiwan and China have moved closer to each other economically, they are moving even further apart politically, thanks to the DPP administration's efforts.
