13477	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Ruling Kuomintang (KMT) Chairman Wu Poh-hsiung and his KMT delegation departed for Japan Sunday for a week-long visit aimed at cementing bilateral relations with Tokyo.
13478	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	It marked the first time the KMT chairman has headed to Japan to promote party- to-party exchanges since the KMT came to power in May.
13479	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	During the visit, Wu and his team are expected to meet with leaders of major political parties in Japan and several senior politicians who have assumed important government positions.
13480	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Noting that President Ma Ying-jeou is attaching great importance to the trip, Wu told the media prior to his departure that the president asked him to pass on some messages to the Japanese side.
13481	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	One of them, Wu said, was that in view of the "special partnership" Taiwan and Japan have maintained, the two sides should spare no effort to further bolster bilateral ties.
13482	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Taiwan and Japan are very close to each other geographically, share many common interests and have deep historical links, with bilateral trade amounting to US$60 billion and more than 2.5 million visitors traveling between the countries per year, Wu quoted Ma as saying the day before.
13483	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Wu said that although Taiwan cannot relinquish its sovereignty claim over the disputed Tiaoyutais, a group of islets in the East China Sea claimed by both sides along with China, the president believes that Taiwan and Japan "can put aside the dispute and move toward pursuing their common interests, like fishery cooperation."
13484	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Wu said Japan may suffer some losses as a transportation hub after direct air and shipping links between Taiwan and China are developed, but that overall Japan will continue to benefit from closer Taiwan-China exchanges.
13485	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	For example, he said, a great number of Taiwanese enterprises have purchased machinery and production equipment from Japan and then exported their products to China, allowing both Taiwan and Japan to prosper from the triangular relationship.
13486	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	"Taiwan and Japan can work together to crack China's vast market," he said.
13487	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	One of the key members of Wu's delegation is former Taiwan representative in Japan Hsu Shui-teh.
13488	CNA_ENG_20081207.0013.LDC2009T13	Wu said Hsu will contribute a lot to the visit because he has maintained close connections with Japanese politicians and has clout in bilateral Taiwan- Japan relations.
