13500	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Texas Mandates Papilloma Virus Vaccinations
13501	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	HOUSTON
13502	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Texas on Friday became the first state to require school-age girls be vaccinated against a virus -- typically transmitted through sex -- that has been shown to cause cervical cancer.
13503	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Gov. Rick Perry signed an executive order mandating that most girls, starting in September 2008, must receive the vaccination against the human papilloma virus, or HPV, prior to entering sixth grade.
13504	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	More than a dozen states have been considering such a move.
13505	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	HPV, which causes genital warts, is the most common sexually transmitted disease in the United States.
13506	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Several strains of the virus have been linked to cervical cancer, which kills about 3,700 Americans a year, according to the Food and Drug Administration.
13507	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	The federal government approved an HPV vaccine last year, and a government advisory panel has recommended that all girls get shots at age 11 or 12 -- before they begin having sex.
13508	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	But the American College of Pediatricians, a socially conservative group, has opposed any vaccination requirement, calling that a ``precedent-setting action that trespasses on the right of parents to make medical decisions for their children, as well as on the rights of the children to attend school.''
13509	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	By sidestepping the Texas Legislature, Perry -- a conservative Republican -- avoided a showdown with GOP lawmakers and Christian organizations that oppose mandatory HPV vaccinations on the grounds that teaching young people to avoid pre-marital sex is a better solution.
13510	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Perry defended his decision Friday, arguing that the vaccinations are needed to save lives.
13511	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	He promised that parents who did not want their children vaccinated ``for reasons of conscience'' would be allowed to seek exemptions.
13512	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	The mandate would affect roughly 365,000 girls a year.
13513	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	``The HPV vaccine provides us with an incredible opportunity to effectively target and prevent cervical cancer,'' Perry said in a statement.
13514	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	``Requiring young girls to get vaccinated before they come into contact with HPV is responsible health and fiscal policy.''
13515	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Public health advocates and liberal activists praised Perry's action, calling it a triumph of common sense over political ideology.
13516	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	``I'm surprised he took this step
13517	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	it breaks with his [political] base,'' said Kathy Miller, president of the Texas Freedom Network, which opposes efforts to mix religion and government policy.
13518	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	But the move drew immediate criticism from conservative groups, which noted that the governor had accepted campaign contributions from Merck &amp
13519	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Co., the drug company that manufactures the vaccine.
13520	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	``All Merck wanted was a mandate so the insurance companies would have to pay for this.
13521	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Follow the money,'' said Cathie Adams, president of the Texas Eagle Forum, an organization that promotes socially conservative government policies.
13522	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	``This is telling girls that they can be promiscuous and still be safe,'' she added.
13523	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Merck has been pushing for laws mandating its Gardasil vaccine in numerous states.
13524	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	It has also launched a television advertising campaign featuring young girls and the slogan ``One less,'' to signify one fewer cancer patient for everyone who takes the vaccine.
13525	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	The New Jersey-based drug company donated $6,000 to Perry's reelection campaign last year, Texas campaign finance records show.
13526	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	One of its top Texas lobbyists, Mike Toomey, is Perry's former chief of staff.
13527	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Merck was paying Toomey between $25,000 and $50,000 to influence politicians, according to disclosure reports.
13528	LTW_ENG_20070203.0123.LDC2009T13	Perry spokeswoman Krista Moody said the state would boost existing health care programs by $29.4 million a year to help poorer Texans pay for the vaccines, which currently cost more than $300 for a three-shot series.
