13539	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Security Comes at a Price for Poles
13540	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	PROCHNIK, Poland
13541	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	One grave stands out in the tiny, unfenced village cemetery.
13542	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Andrzej Zielke's plot is the only one enclosed by an ironwork fence and the only one with a small bench that sits in front of flickering candles and the black, broken heart of a headstone.
13543	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``He died tragically executing a fighting order in the second change of the Polish military contingent in Iraq,'' reads the inscription, in Polish, on the broken heart, which is etched with the young soldier's face.
13544	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Zielke's black army beret, soaked recently by a winter rain, sits next to the headstone.
13545	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	About 400 yards down the only road in the village of Prochnik is a farmhouse -- home to a gentle-voiced Polish woman who lost her beloved son in a desert far away and who can't figure out why he was in Iraq, fighting an American war.
13546	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``I have no idea,'' said Stanislawa Zielke, 49, when asked why she thought Poland had sent its troops -- the third largest Iraq coalition force after the United States and Britain.
13547	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Many Poles wonder why their government seems so keen to help out the United States in its wars at a time when many other countries are distancing themselves from Iraq and, to a lesser extent, Afghanistan.
13548	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Al-Qaida did not attack Poland, people say -- though perhaps now it will, they quip.
13549	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Saddam Hussein, even if he had possessed weapons of mass destruction, was not likely to have put Warsaw near the top of his target list.
13550	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Polls regularly show at least 70 percent of Poles disapprove of their roughly 1,000-strong contingent being in Iraq.
13551	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	But successive Polish governments have continued a policy of cooperation with the United States on military and intelligence matters that is perhaps unmatched by any country other than Britain.
13552	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Poland announced late last year that its troops will stay in Iraq through this year and, privately, politicians expect levels to be maintained for years.
13553	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Poland also is upping its troop levels in Afghanistan from about 100 to more than 1,000 at a time when it is increasingly hard to find NATO volunteers for the ever-more dangerous war there.
13554	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	And, soon there will be up to 500 troops helping keep peace between Israel and Hezbollah in southern Lebanon, a region the U.S. cares very much about since Israel is the United States' most important Middle East ally.
13555	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Add to the list of Polish favors to the United States the forthcoming negotiations between the two governments over the proposed location of an American missile defense system in Poland that would help protect the United States but not Poland itself and the CIA's widely reported use -- which Poland has officially denied -- of a Polish air base for transporting terrorist suspects to secret interrogation sites.
13556	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	There is a simple calculation that explains this unfashionable support of the U.S. and its military ventures, Polish politicians, Western diplomats and analysts say: Surrounded by historically hostile countries such as Russia and Germany and abandoned in the face of Nazi invasion in 1939 by European allies such as Britain, Poland looks across the Atlantic for bankable friendship.
13557	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	A Russian invasion may seem unlikely now, experts say, but Poles have learned -- through centuries of occupation and vast suffering -- to be extremely wary of their neighbors.
13558	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``Insurance,'' said Konstanty Gebert, a leading Polish columnist and author, using a single word to explain his country's strong pro-U.S. foreign policy.
13559	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``This is not a country that feels it's future is assured.
13560	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Most of that is paranoia -- but not all.''
13561	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Other than its membership in NATO and the agreement of all member states to help defend any state that is attacked, Poland has no guarantees that its gentleman's agreement with the United States will pay off.
13562	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``What they get for it is the security umbrella,'' said a Western diplomat in Warsaw who requested anonymity.
13563	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``It keeps that favorable impression of Poland in Washington high.''
13564	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	There are signs of cooling toward the United States, however, among Polish politicians.
13565	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	Marian Pilka, a leading member of parliament in the ruling Law and Justice Party, told Newsday that when the government sits down to negotiate the missile system with the United States, it will expect something in return.
13566	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``If this system is to be in Poland, it will make some danger to our country and should be balanced by our own missile defense system,'' he said, referring to U.S.-made Patriot missile defense systems, which could help protect Poland from attacks on its territory.
13567	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	But for those who have suffered from Poland's decision in 2003 to join the war in Iraq, the idea of a theoretical American insurance policy for their country seems irrelevant given the cost.
13568	LTW_ENG_20070301.0063.LDC2009T13	``I'm mad at everybody who had anything to do with the war,'' Stanislawa Zielke said when asked if her son's death was a sacrifice worth making for the sake of Poland's security.
