13664	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	LCD Flat-Screen TVs on Downward Pricing Trend
13665	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	If you've been waiting for fast-falling prices of LCD flat-screen TVs to flatten out, you can stop.
13666	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Now's the time to buy.
13667	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Or maybe not.
13668	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Prices have been basically stalled since the retail wars of the 2006 holidays, when LCD TVs, once luxury items, went almost mainstream.
13669	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	But prices will probably plunge again by the end of the year.
13670	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	A 42-inch set currently selling for an average $1,877 could be going for $1,175 -- a drop of more than 35 percent -- just in time for the winter holidays, the iSuppli research group said Tuesday.
13671	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Already, at some discount and membership stores, you can find an off-brand 42-inch LCD set for under $1,000.
13672	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``I have a 20-inch LCD set across from me that was $1,500 just four years ago.
13673	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Now I could get it for $149,'' said Richard Doherty of the Envisioneering Group.
13674	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``The prices have fallen faster than any consumer electronics item in years, with the exception of DVD players.''
13675	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	If the price falls as much as expected this year, the average 42-inch LCD set will cost only about $80 less than a plasma flat- screen of the same size.
13676	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	For years, plasma was the undisputed flat-screen king, largely because the technology was far cheaper.
13677	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	But now LCDs could rule -- especially among the environmentally- and weight-conscious.
13678	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``LCD TVs use a lot less electricity,'' Doherty said.
13679	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``People who consider themselves green tend to buy LCD.
13680	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	And the weight of two 37-inch LCD TVs are about equal to that of one plasma set the same size.''
13681	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Right now, LCD sets have 22 percent of the market.
13682	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	The iSuppli group predicts that will rise to 51 percent in 2009.
13683	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	This year, the number of raw LCD screens -- each of which contains a liquid crystal gel divided into hundreds of thousands of individual pixels -- shipping from factories will reach 75.2 million, up from 52.7 in 2006, iSuppli said.
13684	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	And the price of the screens to TV manufacturers is forecast to fall 17 percent in just the first half of this year.
13685	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	That will likely to be passed onto shoppers.
13686	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	At the stores, competition is fierce.
13687	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``At the beginning of 2006, we were seeing 42-inch LCDs at about $3,500 or $4,000,'' said Ross Rubin, an analyst with the NPD Group.
13688	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``But they were from just a handful of manufacturers.
13689	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	By the end of the year, many more manufacturers were offering LCDs and there was very aggressive retail discounting during the holidays.''
13690	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	What's good for shoppers, though, doesn't necessarily make manufacturers and retailers happy.
13691	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	In December, ``some of the 32-inch brands were as low as $500,'' said Riddhi Patel, an analyst with iSuppli.
13692	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	``That's an awesome price for the consumer but it was hard on everyone in the TV supply chain because it was such a low profit margin.''
13693	LTW_ENG_20070314.0171.LDC2009T13	Since then, LCD prices have stayed nearly the same, or gone slightly up in some cases.
