13739	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	``There might be some friction caused by the way this service operates -- it doesn't operate on a sectarian basis,'' the U.S. official said on condition of anonymity.
13740	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	``There appear to be people in Iraq, and perhaps in one of its neighboring countries, who do not like that fact.''
13741	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	A Shiite official who deals with insurgency issues said that Waeli was trying to steer the service away from a sectarian bias, but the problem was with those surrounding him.
13742	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	``He is trying very hard to move away from sectarianism and say this is a government to protect the people, but some of his officers have sectarian views.''
13743	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	Waeli said his main goals were to crack down on al-Qaida, Baathists, militias and criminals.
13744	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	But his service has no legal charter to be engaged in domestic spying or arresting people and is lobbying to pass a law through Parliament that would formalize its surveillance activities, make it a full ministry and put it in charge of the CIA-funded INIS.
13745	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	That legislation would cap the agency's transformation from a minor state ministry into a pillar of Iraq's security apparatus.
13746	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	But the Shiite coalition itself has not made its mind up about whether to formalize Waeli's powers.
13747	LTW_ENG_20070415.0059.LDC2009T13	Sunnis speak with severe distrust of Waeli's ministry, describing it as sectarian in nature.
