13831	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Closed Rulings Questioned in Contract Case
13832	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	LOS ANGELES
13833	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	As Clive Cussler stumbled through seven days of trial testimony during his legal showdown with billionaire Philip Anschutz, Judge John P. Shook expressed skepticism about the 75-year-old novelist's performance on the witness stand.
13834	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	``Mr. Cussler is smart like a fox,'' Shook said.
13835	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	``He has got an iron-trap mind.
13836	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	He knows what is going on here.''
13837	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	The judge made the statement April 20 when he huddled with lawyers to discuss Cussler's responses before the jury.
13838	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Like nearly all of the sidebar conferences held in the high-stakes trial, the meeting took place behind closed doors.
13839	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Transcripts of the sessions obtained by the Los Angeles Times provide rare insights into legal maneuvering, finger-pointing and posturing in the breach-of-contract case.
13840	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	They reveal how entertainment lawyer Bertram Fields prevailed in persuading Shook to ban testimony about Cussler's alleged use of racial and anti- Semitic epithets.
13841	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	And they show Anschutz's attorneys repeatedly challenging the way Fields sought to try the case.
13842	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	The documents also raise questions about the court rulings and oral arguments that took place inside Shook's chambers.
13843	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Legal experts say that routinely closing parts of a civil trial to the public and the media violates the U.S. Constitution and California's long-standing ``open court'' statute.
13844	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	``This judge needs a little reminder of the First Amendment,'' said Laurie Levenson, a professor at Loyola Law School.
13845	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	``In no circumstances should every hearing be held in secret.''
13846	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Cussler is seeking about $38 million in damages based on claims that Anschutz and his movie production company reneged on contractual rights that gave the author ``sole and absolute'' approval over the adaptation of the novel ``Sahara.''
13847	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Anschutz alleges that Cussler acted unreasonably in exercising those approvals and committed fraud by flagrantly inflating sales of his Dirk Pitt novels to extract a $20 million fee for rights to ``Sahara'' and one other book.
13848	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Anschutz has lost about $105 million on the adventure film, which starred Matthew McConaughey and Penelope Cruz.
13849	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Closing arguments continue Tuesday, and the case is expected to go to the jury Wednesday.
13850	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Lawyers who practice in Los Angeles Superior Court said it is highly unusual for judges to close trial proceedings unless there are compelling reasons such as the need to protect national security interests or trade secrets.
13851	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Yet one morning last week Shook, a court reporter and several lawyers shuffled in and out of the judge's chambers five times in the span of an hour to discuss rebuttal testimony.
13852	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	The participants offered conflicting explanations for why they convened in private at least 59 times during the 58-day trial.
13853	LTW_ENG_20070501.0152.LDC2009T13	Marvin Putnam, Anschutz's lead counsel, said the hearings were closed at the request of Fields.
