14110	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	Army, Iraqi Government Disagree on Sunni Guards
14111	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	TAJI, Iraq
14112	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	When U.S. soldiers moved into an abandoned wool factory near here two months ago, they were pounded with bombs, mortar and gunfire.
14113	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``We were not really well received,'' Capt. David Fulton said with deliberate understatement.
14114	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	The fighting around this town north of Baghdad went on for a month, until local Sunni Muslim tribesmen decided they had had enough of the insurgents in their midst and started working with the Americans.
14115	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	About 220 of those tribesmen now staff checkpoints and have started cooperating with Shiite counterparts who once were their enemies, said Fulton, a U.S. Army company commander.
14116	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	Experiences like these have persuaded the U.S. military command to step up efforts to recruit armed residents as local protection forces, authorizing its officers to use emergency cash and other funds at their disposal to strike contracts with tribal leaders.
14117	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	On Saturday, the top U.S. commander in Iraq, Gen. David H. Petraeus, credited the strategy with beginning to turn around an insurgent haven as he toured the region of dusty villages, citrus plantations, fish farms and palm groves near Taji, about 12 miles north of the capital.
14118	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	But the Shiite-led government, which has been under intense U.S. pressure to dismantle Shiite militias, complains that the policy legitimizes what they regard as the Sunni equivalent.
14119	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``They solve one problem by creating another,'' said Sami al- Askari, an aide to Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki and member of his Islamic Dawa Party.
14120	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``This is a seed for civil war.''
14121	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	Al-Maliki wants to screen the volunteers before they are allowed to carry weapons, and he wants them incorporated into security forces under the government's control, al-Askari said.
14122	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	The strategy has been the subject of heated discussion between al-Maliki and Petraeus and U.S. Ambassador Ryan Crocker, both sides acknowledged Saturday.
14123	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	But Petraeus dismissed as ``ludicrous'' a report that al-Maliki felt he could no longer work with the general.
14124	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``This is really, really hard stuff, and occasionally people agree to disagree,'' he said.
14125	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	With the country's largest Sunni bloc suspending participation in his Cabinet, al-Maliki needs the support of Shiite conservatives in his governing coalition, who are angry about U.S. raids targeting Shiite militants in areas such as Baghdad's Sadr City and the southern city of Karbala.
14126	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``Petraeus is not answerable before the Iraqi people.
14127	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	Maliki is,'' said Haider Abadi, another one of the prime minister's aides.
14128	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``There is mounting pressure on Maliki because of these casualties.''
14129	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	Petraeus acknowledged the government's concerns about working with Sunni tribes.
14130	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``Obviously there is a concern, particularly in the areas where al-Qaida had sanctuaries, that some of them may have had ties with them before,'' he said.
14131	LTW_ENG_20070729.0028.LDC2009T13	``But at the end of the day, situations like this historically have been resolved by the local citizens helping with local security.''
