14264	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	HIMOWITZ ON COMPUTERS: About as Good as Digital Photo Prints Get
14265	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	It's no secret that many printers are sold as loss leaders.
14266	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	A manufacturer can give away great hardware if he can sell the ink at $35 a cartridge and paper for 25 cents a snapshot.
14267	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	That's where the profit is.
14268	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Given that business model, I've always been suspicious of printers equipped to print photos directly from a camera's memory card without going through a computer.
14269	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	For me, editing photos is the whole point of digital photography.
14270	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	A perfect shot is rare.
14271	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	With a computer you get a chance to adjust the exposure, crop the image, lighten the shadows, eliminate red-eye and smooth out the occasional wrinkle.
14272	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	All this happens before you commit to paper.
14273	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	So printing straight from a memory card always has seemed to be an invitation to waste money on bad shots.
14274	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	But I've changed my mind after spending a week with the new Epson PictureMate Dash.
14275	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	The latest in Epson's line of small-format printers turns out spectacular 4- by 6-inch photos in 45 seconds -- with or without a computer.
14276	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	A caveat: This compact machine is strictly for snapshot-sized prints.
14277	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	But at $99.99, it's small and inexpensive enough to keep next to your regular printer, especially if you're the family photographer and expect to churn out a lot of prints.
14278	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	At 26 cents for paper and ink combined, PictureMate shots are slightly more expensive than online photofinishers, but relatively cheap for at-home printing.
14279	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	For many photographers, instant gratification is well worth the extra pennies.
14280	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	With a 6- by 8-inch footprint, the PictureMate Dash doesn't claim much desktop real estate.
14281	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	And s etup was a snap: I inserted a print cartridge, flipped up the lid, pulled up the hinged LCD display window and loaded 4 x 6 photo paper from the top.
14282	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	A handful of buttons on the top control the printer with the aid of on-screen menus
14283	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	front-panel slots accommodate all popular memory cards.
14284	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	There are two USB ports, one for a PC and another for cameras that support direct printing.
14285	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	A wireless Bluetooth adapter is available for the cable-challenged, and a $50 battery pack will print 140 photos between charges if you're on the road.
14286	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Brushing skepticism aside, I began work without hooking the PictureMate to a PC.
14287	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	I popped a Secure Digital memory card loaded with vacation pictures into the slot, and a few seconds later I was viewing the images on the surprisingly bright, 3.6-inch LCD screen.
14288	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	The buttons and menus made navigation easy -- I could view one shot at time or peruse a lineup of thumbnail images (actually, in that small window, they're really "pinkynail" images, but still viewable).
14289	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	One irritant of digital photography is that cameras record images with a 4-to-3 aspect ratio -- the same proportion as standard TV screens and PC monitors.
14290	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Unfortunately, most commercial photo paper and picture frames are designed to accommodate 4- by 6-inch prints, with their elongated aspect ratio.
14291	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	That means you have to crop most images slightly to make them fit properly.
14292	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	The PictureMate made this cropping chore surprisingly easy from the control panel.
14293	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Same for adjusting basic exposure and color settings.
14294	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	What amazed me was how little adjustment most decent exposures needed.
14295	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	With automatic enhancement turned on, the PictureMate churned out one gorgeous, well-balanced glossy photo after another.
14296	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Each one took about 45 seconds, which is more than twice as fast as my general-purpose printer, an aging but reliable HP Photosmart 1100.
14297	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Also, to my surprise, the PictureMate accurately removed red-eye from several flash pictures and did its best to adjust for some badly exposed shots -- although it couldn't perform miracles.
14298	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Among other bells and whistles, the PictureMate prints in black- and-white or sepia, and it offers multiple photo layouts.
14299	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	They include thumbnail images of all the photos on a card, dual wallet-size or four mini-wallet-size prints, double passport-size photos, 3- or 4-inch square images, and other entertaining if less-than-useful options.
14300	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	When I finally got around to hooking up the PictureMate to my PC, the drivers installed without a problem under Windows XP.
14301	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	For real editing, Epson bundles a version of ArcSoft PhotoImpression, a quirky but reasonably competent entry-level program.
14302	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	It produced excellent prints, as did Adobe PhotoShop Elements and Microsoft's Digital Imaging, the two photo-editing programs I normally use.
14303	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	For prints with a long life, I usually recommend photofinishing services, which use real photographic paper and chemistry, instead of ink.
14304	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	But Epson now claims its inks will last 96 years under glass and 200 years in a closed album -- a lot longer than I'll ever last.
14305	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Can you believe those claims?
14306	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Who knows, since tests can only simulate the effects of time.
14307	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	But there's no doubt that today's inks are more permanent than early formulas, which were prone to smudging and fading.
14308	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Unlike most competitors, Epson bundles its ink cartridge and paper in PrintPaks, which cost $40 for 150 glossy photos (26 cents a shot) or $35 for 100 matte prints (35 cents each).
14309	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	That makes Epson consumable supplies hard to compare directly with Hewlett-Packard, Canon and other vendors who sell ink and paper separately.
14310	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	But my take is that the per-print price is on the low end, considering the quality.
14311	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	For those with bigger budgets and more ambition, Epson makes a $200 version of this printer called the PictureMate Zoom with a built-in CD burner.
14312	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	This accessory allows users to make photo CDs for friends and family, but it sounds pretty expensive for marginal additional utility.
14313	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	Bottom line: Given its reasonable upfront cost, superb images and economy of operation, it's hard to find much fault with the basic PictureMate Dash.
14314	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	If you're getting started with digital photography and don't want to use a computer as middleman, the PictureMate Dash does a great job with images straight out of the camera.
14315	LTW_ENG_20070921.0072.LDC2009T13	If you're an experienced digital photographer and want a gadget that can spit out a stream of high-quality snapshots in short order, it's a nifty gadget.
