14489	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	A gallon of self-serve regular was averaging $3.297 in the Los Angeles-Long Beach area.
14490	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	That's 13.7 cents higher than a week before, 31 cents above the month-earlier level and nearly $1 more than a year ago.
14491	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	"Crude oil prices have been breaking records since September, and that increase has hit gas pump prices in a big way this week in Southern California and throughout the U.S.," said Jeffrey Spring, an auto club spokesman.
14492	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	With that in mind, I stopped by a Hummer dealership to get a sense of how things looked from the perspective of one of the biggest, fattest, gas-guzzlingest vehicles on the road.
14493	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	I had the lot to myself as I wandered among the shiny, tanklike behemoths.
14494	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	A black Hummer H2 was selling for $65,955.
14495	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	As if it were silly to even ask, the sticker said mileage info was "not applicable to this vehicle."
14496	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	In fact, most reviews place the GM-made H2's fuel efficiency at around 10 miles per gallon in the city.
14497	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	I approached a salesman and asked how business had been.
14498	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	When he learned I was from the newspaper, he clammed up and said he couldn't answer any questions.
14499	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	I asked about who buys Hummers these days.
14500	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	The salesman called his boss over.
14501	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	He, too, declined to answer any questions and made it clear that my presence at the dealership wasn't welcome.
14502	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	So I went back to the Toyota showroom, where rock music was playing and a smattering of customers were browsing among the vehicles.
14503	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	William Stackhouse, 85, was having some maintenance done on his 2007 Prius.
14504	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	I asked how he felt about buying American.
14505	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	"That's a nice idea," Stackhouse replied.
14506	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	"I just wish Detroit made cars as good as the Japanese cars."
14507	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	So does Detroit.
14508	LTW_ENG_20071111.0021.LDC2009T13	Lazarus can be reached at david.lazarus@latimes.com.
14509	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Oaxaca After the Riots
14510	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The last time I was in Oaxaca, I was frantically trying to improvise a gas mask.
14511	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The city was a war zone: anti-government protesters packing spray paint, rocks and Molotov cocktails
14512	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	police in riot gear tossing canisters of black tear gas into the crowd.
14513	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	My eyes stinging, I raced past the burned-out shell of a bus.
14514	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Thick smoke filled the air, but there was just enough of a clearing to allow me a glimpse of El Catedral restaurant.
14515	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	It looked so enticing: a serene courtyard, white tablecloths and glass wine goblets with the distinctive Mexican blue rim.
14516	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But the door was locked.
14517	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	I kept running.
14518	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Fast-forward one year and I'm finally inside El Catedral, and in a city that feels much different.
14519	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Seated under the stars on an ancient stone patio, a fountain burbling beside me, I savor sauteed mushrooms in garlic wine sauce.
14520	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The setting is almost exactly as I envisioned it would be: a place of architectural jewels, one-of-a-kind textiles and culinary surprises.
14521	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Except I am alone.
14522	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The two-story bar, all polished wood and chrome, is dark.
14523	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The dining room to the right of the courtyard is as empty as the one to the left.
14524	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	I have returned to Oaxaca on assignment: Find out if, one year after deadly riots crippled the city, it is again an attractive destination for visitors seeking language schools, colonial history, craft markets and art galleries.
14525	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	I'm eager -- and a bit apprehensive -- to check in on friends I'd made here and find out whether Oaxaca still belongs on Mexico's A-list.
14526	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	It didn't take long to realize that the answer is more complicated than I'd thought.
14527	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Oaxaca (wa-HA-ka) is no longer the filthy, smoldering wreck of 2006.
14528	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Nor, however, is it the bustling cultural center of years past.
14529	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	It appears safe and clean.
14530	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But unresolved political tensions have prompted the U.S. State Department to keep it on a watch list.
14531	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"We're not discouraging tourism," says U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Judith Bryan.
14532	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"But we want informed and appropriately cautious tourism."
14533	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	My friend Harry Smith, a Bostonian living in Oaxaca with his wife and three daughters, is keenly aware of the economic and political injustices in the city.
14534	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But he also wants Americans to appreciate its warmth and beauty.
14535	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"I would advise people to come, as long as they come with their eyes open," he says.
14536	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"But this is not Disneyland."
14537	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	As in most of Oaxaca, things at El Catedral, where I've come for dinner, are "mas o menos," explains my waiter, Alberto.
14538	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Translated literally, the phrase means "more or less."
14539	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But Alberto's diplomatic shorthand, which I will hear often during a three-day visit, hints at the conflicted, contradictory state of an emotionally scarred city.
14540	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	For adventurous travelers, "mas o menos" can also translate to opportunity.
14541	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The decline in foreign visitors -- from 264,000 in 2005 to 190,000 this year through October -- means there are bargains to be had and no hordes to fight.
14542	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Smith, for instance, negotiated half-price rates at the nearby beaches of Puerto Escondido.
14543	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	As I finish an affordable glass of Spanish tempranillo, two groups arrive at El Catedral, adding a bit of life to the courtyard.
14544	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"It's certainly not like it was three years ago," declares Virginia O'Brien, a San Diegan who has returned to the city every year since her first Spanish language class in 1984.
14545	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"This place would be packed
14546	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	we'd be lucky to get a table."
14547	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Now in her 70s, with cropped red hair and kitschy-cool Mexican- silver skeletons dangling from her ears, O'Brien loves Oaxaca so much she even came during the riots.
14548	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	She and a travel agent friend "were going to bring a tour last year, but we canceled it, thank God," she says.
14549	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	This year's group backed out.
14550	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"People are taking their kids back to school
14551	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	they're walking in the Zocalo (town square) again," says her dining companion, Javier Garcia Vigil, who is the director of the Symphony of Oaxaca.
14552	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	O'Brien, who loves to scout for bargain-price hand-woven rugs, remains bullish on Oaxaca.
14553	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But she is sad: "It hasn't staged a real comeback yet."
14554	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The New Normal
14555	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Oaxaca -- it's the name of both the capital city and the state -- is an hour's flight south of Mexico City.
14556	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The city (population before the riots: 258,000) was laid out by Spaniards in the mid- 1500s, and its streets are lined by mossy relics of that era.
14557	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The surrounding region boasts phenomenal ruins, such as the sprawling hilltop Zapotec village of Monte Alban, and what is believed to be one of the largest and best-preserved indigenous cultures in the Mesoamerican world.
14558	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Protest is as much a part of Oaxaca's tradition as its black clay pottery and hand-woven tapestries.
14559	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	So when the city's teachers announced their perennial strike in May 2006, it barely caused a stir.
14560	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But unlike in previous years, the dispute escalated into a broader conflict over social justice.
14561	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Anti-government demonstrators stormed local radio stations and occupied Oaxaca's famed Zocalo.
14562	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The city once known for picturesque cathedrals, graceful laurel trees and colorful marketplaces was coated in graffiti and strewn with the charred remains of vehicles.
14563	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Some 4,000 federal police descended, erecting barricades and military-style encampments.
14564	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Masked protesters countered with guerrilla tactics, hurling burning tires and rocks collected from the cobblestone streets.
14565	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Before order was restored in December, the riots claimed the lives of at least nine and as many as 20 people, including American activist/journalist Brad Will.
14566	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Today, mariachi music fills the Zocalo and fresh whitewash covers the walls.
14567	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But marches in opposition to state Gov. Ulises Ruiz -- who sent riot police to battle demonstrators -- occur often, and residents say the underlying economic and political tensions remain.
14568	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Officially, Oaxaca is back to normal.
14569	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	And as if to prove it, the government has taken a more active role in some of the city's most beloved festivals, which once had been ad-hoc community affairs.
14570	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But a more nuanced truth comes out when you share a coffee or a shot of mezcal with Oaxacans or with those, like my friend John Rexer, who have adopted the city.
14571	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"It feels antiseptic," he remarks as we walk through the Zocalo and the adjacent square known as the Alameda.
14572	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Rexer, an expat American, runs the Cafe No Se bar in Antigua, Guatemala.
14573	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But he spends much of his time in Oaxaca overseeing his latest business venture, a new brand of mezcal named Ilegal.
14574	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"It feels as though it's been prettied up and staged for the tourists."
14575	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Yes, it's nice not to be dodging flying rocks, he acknowledges.
14576	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But in its effort to remove the ugly barricades and trash, the government also swept away a bit of Oaxaca's soul.
14577	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Problems and Opportunities
14578	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	We walk the few blocks to El Naranjo restaurant, where a decade ago, Oaxaca native Iliana de la Vega won international acclaim -- and sneers from local culinary purists -- with her lard-free mole and organic ingredients.
14579	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	An English-speaking man in chef's whites directs us to a table next to an ancient orange tree.
14580	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	He is friendly, helpful and definitely not de la Vega.
14581	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	She fled Oaxaca last year, and after drifting from New Mexico to Austin, Texas, hopes to soon join the staff of the Culinary Institute of America in San Antonio.
14582	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"We just couldn't make it," she tells me later in a telephone interview.
14583	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"We had trouble getting downtown
14584	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	we couldn't get deliveries
14585	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	we couldn't pay the rent.
14586	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	We'd cook all that food and then no customers would come."
14587	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Andrew Peterson, the new owner, proudly announces that he has changed every recipe on the menu save one: de la Vega's gazpacho.
14588	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	In the interest of science, I order that and the mole, which had been El Naranjo's specialty.
14589	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Neither dish stands out, and Rexer grumbles that he has trouble detecting any chilies in his allegedly spicy shrimp.
14590	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Though pleasant, El Naranjo falls short: sadly gringoized, when what we crave is authenticity.
14591	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	We amble out for a late-night stroll, pleasantly surprised to find others on the streets, a far cry from the days of curfews.
14592	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	As we turn the corner onto Macedonio Alcala, we can't resist the lure of Caribbean music pulling us into Cafe del Borgo.
14593	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Behind the bar, owner Eduardo Evans looks relieved at the sight of a relatively packed house.
14594	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"The last four months were the worst," says Evans, better known by his nickname, Lalo.
14595	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	With occupancy at many hotels below 10 percent, he considered leaving but couldn't: "All my money is invested here."
14596	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Evans predicts that the holiday season -- with Oaxaca's parades, religious ceremonies and famous radish carvings -- will be better.
14597	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	There is one difference nowadays that is both attractive to those who complained Oaxaca had been inundated with gringos and unfortunate for the business owners who survived on U.S. dollars.
14598	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	The majority of visitors -- including the two men seated beside me -- are Mexicans.
14599	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Artists in Crisis
14600	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Before the riots, Oaxaca had a thriving art scene, from museums with artifacts of pre-Hispanic cultures to galleries with the colorful paintings of 20th-century native Rufino Tamayo.
14601	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	As its reputation grew, the area attracted not only painters but also sculptors, writers, musicians and filmmakers, says local artist Rowena Galavitz.
14602	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	But last year, several galleries folded, and art students stopped coming to the city for lectures, which meant the artists, too, began abandoning Oaxaca.
14603	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	"Anybody who was able to get out, did," she says.
14604	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Others, including Galavitz, began exhibiting in other cities.
14605	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Now, "I don't really have a market here in Oaxaca anymore."
14606	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Though she is aware that the political disputes could flare up again, Galavitz says the recent calm is helping to slowly revive the art world.
14607	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	As we talk, a team of artists is hanging photos and paintings for an exhibit of pieces about the protests opening that night.
14608	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	It will be called "Fallen Angels."
14609	LTW_ENG_20071128.0003.LDC2009T13	Ceci Connolly, a Washington Post reporter currently on leave, last wrote for Travel about Panama City.
14610	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Troop Reduction to Focus on Ouylying Areas of Iraq
14611	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The change represents the military's first attempt to confront its big challenge in 2008: how to reduce the number of troops without sacrificing security.
14612	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The shift in deployment strategy, described by senior U.S. military officials in Iraq and Washington, D.C., is based on concerns that despite recent improvements, the capital could erupt again into widespread violence without an imposing American military presence.
14613	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	A year ago, when U.S. patrols in Baghdad were sparse and sectarian killings were spiraling out of control, the troop buildup was proposed in part to establish order in the capital.
14614	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Over the last four months, violence in the capital has begun to abate.
14615	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	But the most significant improvements have been in outlying areas, where the first surge troops arrived at the start of the year, followed by gradual improvements in Baghdad.
14616	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Planners at first thought it would be the other way around.
14617	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"There was a sense we would focus very significantly on Baghdad and change would come from Baghdad-out," said a senior military official in Washington, who like others spoke on condition of anonymity when discussing troop strategy.
14618	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"What we are seeing is just the opposite, it is probably outside-in, toward Baghdad."
14619	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The withdrawals are occurring over the next eight months as the troop surge that President Bush ordered last January gradually comes to an end.
14620	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Plans call for reducing troops that reached a peak of about 170,000 to pre-buildup levels of about 135,000.
14621	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The new planning is not without risk and controversy.
14622	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The change in U.S. deployment strategy probably will shift the balance of political power in the country by putting much greater authority over provincial affairs in the hands of local and regional officials.
14623	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	That will increase the influence of the local and provincial governments and offset the authority of the Shiite- dominated central government.
14624	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	In addition, some of the early troop reductions will take place in areas such as Anbar province, the site of raging insurgency in the recent past.
14625	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Nonetheless, the international military pullback from outlying areas is under way.
14626	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	On Sunday, the British will hand over authority for Basra and the south to the Iraqi government.
14627	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Next, U.S. officers expect to hand over western provinces to Iraqi control, including Anbar, followed by still-precarious provinces north of Baghdad, say military leaders in Washington and Iraq.
14628	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The new U.S. military view worries officials in the Shiite- dominated central government who fear their power will be diminished.
14629	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	The Shiite officials have expressed concern over U.S. plans to hand over security responsibilities to recently recruited police forces, particularly in Sunni strongholds such as Anbar where the new police forces are mostly Sunni.
14630	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	But the day-to-day commander in Iraq, Army Lt. Gen. Raymond T. Odierno, and his staff believe the increasing competence of provincial security and political leaders will put pressure on the government in Baghdad that "will breed a better central government," said his chief of staff, Brig. Gen. Joseph Anderson.
14631	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"There are different schools of thought here," Anderson said in an interview in his office at the U.S. military headquarters at Camp Victory.
14632	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"Our school of thought is provincial capacity will ultimately lead to enhanced central government capacity.
14633	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	That's our view."
14634	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Months ago, Bush administration officials and senior military leaders largely gave up hope of meaningful political reconciliation through Iraq's central government.
14635	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Instead, officials have pinned their hopes on incremental progress at the provincial level.
14636	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	As a consequence, Odierno's plan enjoys broad support.
14637	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"The grass-roots level will force change at the top because if they do not act on it, they will get overrun," said another senior military officer responsible for Iraq war planning.
14638	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	So far, military officials have sought to design the troop reduction in a way that avoids creation of security gaps.But by the spring, when the number of U.S. brigades in Iraq is reduced from the current 19 to 17, significant turnovers of security responsibility in outlying provinces are inevitable, Odierno said in an interview.
14639	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Those turnovers should accelerate the shift away from a pure counterinsurgency strategy.
14640	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Military leaders in Washington have been pressing generals in Baghdad to move toward what they call "tactical overwatch."
14641	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Under that strategy, Iraqi troops would take the lead in most operations, and U.S. troops would be called in only when problems occur.
14642	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	A faster move toward an "overwatch" strategy has gained adherents as U.S. officials try to draw lessons from the experience of the British in Basra, the largest city in the south, which will become the first sector of the country outside the semi- autonomous Kurdistan enclave in the north to be handed over to the Iraqi government and security forces.
14643	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"You cannot set zero violence as your standard in Iraq.
14644	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	It is just not attainable," the senior military official in Washington, D.C., said.
14645	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"The standard rather is a level of violence that is containable by the Iraqi security forces.
14646	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	And that is largely what we have seen in Basra."
14647	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	For the Americans, the first real test of how well security can hold up as the drawdown intensifies this spring probably will take place in the north.
14648	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Significant violence still plagues Diyala province and its provincial capital, Baqubah.
14649	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Military planners are grappling with a solution to deal with the instability in the region.
14650	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Some senior commanders believe violence in the northern provinces are the result of a spillover of Sunni radicals linked to al- Qaida in Iraq who have fled their former stronghold of Anbar, where a U.S.-Iraqi alliance has all but shut down their operations.
14651	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Under such an analysis, additional combat operations might be needed.
14652	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	But at least one aide to Odierno, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the violence appears more likely to be tied to ongoing sectarian disputes in the region over the eventual boundaries of the Kurdistan region.
14653	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Such disputes need to be resolved through sectarian reconciliation and not military action, the aide said.
14654	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	U.S. military officials insisted the focus on Baghdad is not indicative of a lack of success in the capital.
14655	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Violence is down significantly, they note, and services are being restored.
14656	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	But American generals also acknowledged that sectarian tensions still plague the capital.
14657	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	For example, public services provided by the central government are aimed largely at Shiite neighborhoods at the expense of Sunni areas.
14658	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	In addition, the multiethnic makeup of the capital makes it the most difficult part of the country to achieve reconciliation between once- warring factions.
14659	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Army Brig. Gen. Vincent Brooks, assistant commander for the military headquarters responsible for Baghdad, said the Iraqi central government is less willing to take a risk in the capital, worried that a dramatic reduction in the U.S. forces could quickly reignite security problems.
14660	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	"Baghdad will be last," Brooks said, "because it's the capital and because it's the most complex."
14661	LTW_ENG_20071216.0044.LDC2009T13	Spiegel reported from Iraq and Barnes from Washington.
