14676	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Cookies from the Fridge: Recipe 1
14677	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	PEANUT AND BITTERSWEET CHOCOLATE COOKIES
14678	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 1/4 cups flour
14679	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 teaspoon baking powder
14680	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	3/4 teaspoon baking soda
14681	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/4 teaspoon salt
14682	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 cup (1 stick) cold butter
14683	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 cup chunky peanut butter
14684	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 cup sugar
14685	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 cup brown sugar
14686	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 egg
14687	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1/2 teaspoon vanilla
14688	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 cup finely chopped peanuts
14689	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 cup finely chopped bittersweet chocolate
14690	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	In a medium bowl, stir together the flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt in a medium bowl and set aside.
14691	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Beat the butter until creamy in a stand mixer or in a medium bowl using a hand mixer.
14692	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Beat in the peanut butter until blended.
14693	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Beat in the sugar and brown sugar until light and fluffy.
14694	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Beat the egg and vanilla into the sugar mixture until blended.
14695	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Add flour mixture and beat until thoroughly mixed.
14696	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Then stir in the chopped peanuts and chocolate until evenly incorporated.
14697	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Divide the dough in half.
14698	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Shape it into two logs about 9 inches long and wrap each log in plastic wrap, waxed paper or aluminum foil.
14699	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Twist ends to seal.
14700	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Chill in the refrigerator overnight.
14701	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Heat the oven to 350 degrees.
14702	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Unwrap the logs and cut into one- quarter-inch-thick slices.
14703	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Place the slices on silicone-lined baking sheets, and bake 10 to 13 minutes until lightly browned around the edges.
14704	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Remove the cookies to a wire rack to cool.
14705	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Store the cookies in an airtight container.
14706	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Servings: Makes 5 1/2 dozen cookies
14707	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Each cookie: 66 calories
14708	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 gram protein
14709	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	7 grams carbohydrates
14710	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	1 gram fiber
14711	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	5 grams fat
14712	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	2 grams saturated fat
14713	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	7 milligrams cholesterol
14714	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	38 milligrams sodium.
14715	LTW_ENG_20080108.0047.LDC2009T13	Total time: 1 hour, plus overnight chilling time
14716	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Gulf Threat May Not Have Come from Iranians, Pentagon Says
14717	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The Pentagon said Thursday that the radio threat to bomb U.S. warships in the Persian Gulf last weekend may not have come from the five Iranian Revolutionary Guard speedboats that approached them -- and may not even have been intended against U.S. targets.
14718	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The communication Sunday was made on radio channel 16, a common marine frequency used by ships and others in the region.
14719	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"It could have been a threat aimed at some other nation or a myriad of other things," said Rear Adm. Frank Thorp IV, a spokesman for the Navy.
14720	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	In the radio message recorded by the Navy, a heavily accented voice said, "I am coming to you.
14721	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	You will explode after a few minutes."
14722	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	But Farsi speakers and Iranians told The Washington Post that the accent did not sound Iranian.
14723	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	In part because of the threatening language, the United States has elevated the encounter into an international incident.
14724	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Twice this week, President Bush criticized Iran's behavior as provocative and warned of "serious consequences" if it happens again.
14725	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	He is due to head Friday to the Gulf, where containing Iran is expected to be a major theme of his talks in five oil- rich sheikdoms.
14726	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Pentagon officials insist that they never claimed Iran made the threat.
14727	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"No one in the military has said that the transmission emanated from those boats.
14728	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	But when they hear it simultaneously to the behavior of those boats, it only adds to the tension," said Pentagon spokesman Geoff Morrell.
14729	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"If this verbal threat emanated from something or someone unrelated to the five boats, it would not lessen the threat from those boats."
14730	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The warning was picked up on a bridge-to-bridge communication received by many ships in the region some seven minutes after the five Iranian patrol boats first appeared on the horizon, Thorp said.
14731	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The main threat, Pentagon officials said, was the way the five patrol boats swarmed erratically around the USS Port Royal, an Aegis cruiser, and an accompanying frigate and destroyer, and then dropped small white box-like items in the water.
14732	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"When you get a bridge-to-bridge call you have no way of knowing where it came from," Thorp said.
14733	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"Nobody ever with any certainty knew it was from them.
14734	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	But it did escalate it up a notch as it was happening at the same time" that the patrol boats manned by Revolutionary Guards engaged in menacing behavior, Thorp said.
14735	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Yet the Pentagon has consistently given the impression that the threat was linked to the Iranian boats.
14736	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"This is more serious because of the aggregate of the actions, the coordinated movement of the ships, the boats, the aggressive maneuvering, the more or less simultaneous radio communication, the dropping of objects ... So yes, it's more serious than we have seen," Vice Admiral Kevin Cosgriff, commander of U.S. Naval Forces Central Command, said at a new briefing Monday.
14737	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The Pentagon's audio tape of the warning was also released Tuesday with the video tape in an abridged four-minute package of the incident, which U.S. officials said lasted between 20 and 30 minutes.
14738	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The U.S. ships were within seconds of opening fire on the five Iranian speedboats when they turned and headed toward Iran, Pentagon officials said.
14739	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The radio threat was merely a "sideshow" to the physical threat, a senior U.S. official familiar with the incident said.
14740	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"What was the command and control mechanism here?
14741	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Was Tehran aware of what they were doing?
14742	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	They made these provocative moves.
14743	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The radio was a sideshow to the event," he said.
14744	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	To further challenge the U.S. version, Iran Thursday released what it claimed was an abridged video of the same incident, which shows a calm exchange.
14745	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"Slowly get a little closer ... can't make out the ship number," says a Revolutionary Guardsman on a small Iranian patrol boat, speaking in Farsi.
14746	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"I hear something being announced from its loudspeakers, what is it saying?
14747	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	I think they're talking to us."
14748	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"Which channel?"
14749	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	says a second Iranian.
14750	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"Coalition warship 73," he says, speaking in English through his radio mike.
14751	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"This Iranian navy patrol boat.
14752	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	Request side number ... operating in the area this time."
14753	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	An American ship radios back.
14754	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	"This is coalition warship 73.
14755	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	I read you loud and clear."
14756	LTW_ENG_20080111.0123.LDC2009T13	The five-minute video, released Thursday by Iranian television, offers no indication of the tensions that supposedly sparked the weekend encounter between U.S. and Iranian vessels in the Strait of Hormuz -- and no intention of an attack.
