14795	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Junior Trader Cost French Bank $7 Billion
14796	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The alleged fraud by Jerome Kerviel, 31, staggered Societe Generale, France's second-largest bank.
14797	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Its disclosure delivered a new blow to a European banking industry already reeling from losses on American subprime mortgage securities -- including a $3 billion writedown announced Thursday by Societe Generale itself.
14798	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	"With everybody already quite scared about financial stocks, this creates even more of a threat to this sector," said Olivier de la Ferriere, a financial analyst at Richelieu Finance in Paris.
14799	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	"There is a real confidence crisis anyway ... this does not help."
14800	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	And it raised the possibility that the bank, in its haste to unwind Kerviel's bad bets, may have exacerbated a European stock- market plunge earlier this week.
14801	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	That decline, in turn, was at least partially responsible for the Federal Reserve's extraordinary 3/4-point rate cut on Tuesday.
14802	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Societe Generale's chairman, Daniel Bouton, said in a letter to shareholders that immediately after discovering the scale of the fraud on Jan. 19, he decided to liquidate Kerviel's futures positions "in all urgency to avoid even worse consequences, given (their) size."
14803	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	During a conference call Thursday in Paris, bank officials said that they completed unwinding all the transactions from Monday through Wednesday before publicly disclosing the fraud.
14804	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	They said the bank suffered an "enormous loss" because of unfavorable market conditions.
14805	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The actual timing and nature of Societe Generale's sales were unclear, however, as was its impact on European exchanges.
14806	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Those markets plummeted by more than 5 percent on Monday on the heels of a steep sell off in Asian markets.
14807	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The Fed announced its rate cut early the following morning.
14808	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	A Fed official said the central bank was unaware of the Societe Generale situation when it implemented the rate cut, according to Reuters and, in any event, the Fed maintained Tuesday that it took the step in response to "a weakening of the economic outlook" and to deteriorating financial markets.
14809	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Societe Generale's loss swamps the previous high-water mark for activity by a rogue trader -- that set by Nicholas Leeson, who lost $1.3 billion in Asian futures and other derivatives at Barings Bank in 1995.
14810	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	That loss bankrupted the 233-year-old British bank, which subsequently was taken over by the Dutch financial firm ING.
14811	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Bank officials and securities analysts said it was unlikely that the new scandal would have the same impact on Societe General, which was founded in 1864 and currently has 120,000 employees in 77 countries.
14812	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	It is the owner of Los Angeles-based TCW Group, the parent of Trust Company of the West, which manages $153 billion for clients.
14813	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	A TCW spokesman said the trust company was "in no way directly or indirectly related to any of the losses announced today by Societe Generale."
14814	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	"This is a very big bank," said Ruth Lea, economic adviser and director at Arbuthnot Banking Group in London.
14815	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	"It's not as if it's unenviable.
14816	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	I'd be very surprised if it didn't see its way through this."
14817	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	French politicians took pains to paint the case as one without implications beyond the management and regulation of Societe Generale.
14818	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	French Prime Minister Francois Fillon called the fraud "a serious matter," but said "it has nothing to do with the current situation on the global financial markets."
14819	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Bouton announced Thursday that the bank would show a profit of $875 million to $1.1 billion for 2007, a sharp decline from $7.6-billion profit in 2006.
14820	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	He said he had offered to resign after the disclosure of the trading fraud, but the bank's board had rejected the overture.
14821	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Still, the bank said that it would raise $3 billion in capital through an emergency stock sale that was already underwritten by a consortium of banks.
14822	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The capital increase was made necessary by the trading loss as well as by the writedowns from its exposure to U.S. credit securities, Bouton said.
14823	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Although Lea and other analysts speculated that the loss might make Societe Generale more vulnerable to a takeover, Bouton turned away questions about that possibility.
14824	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	In trading Thursday on the Paris Bourse, Societe Generale lost 4.4 percent of its value while the CAC 40 index of Paris stocks gained 6.1 percent.
14825	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Kerviel -- whom Societe Generale executives did not name but who was identified in news reports from Europe -- began working at the bank's back office in 2000, when he was assigned to help fashion the internal programs that placed transaction limits on individual traders.
14826	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	In 2005, he was moved to a trading desk, where bank officials said he was given only limited authority to hedge the bank's trading positions in European stocks with stock index futures.
14827	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	This involves making countervailing bets on the future performance of stocks as an insurance policy against adverse moves in the bank's stock portfolio.
14828	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	His salary was pegged at 100,000 euros, or about $146,000 a year, including bonus
14829	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	the bank said his trades were expected to generate a modest $20 million in revenue a year.
14830	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Instead, Kerviel regularly exceeded his trading limits without detection, starting as early as 2006.
14831	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Using the knowledge he had gained in the back office, he concealed his actions by fabricating balancing trades -- using "extremely sophisticated and varied techniques," as Bouton said in his letter to shareholders.
14832	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	At least for a portion of 2007 his trading was profitable
14833	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	just before the start of the new year, however, he undertook a huge bet that European stock markets would rise in January.
14834	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Instead, they fell sharply, losing nearly 10 percent through last Friday.
14835	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The following day, Societe Generale officials confronted Kerviel with evidence of his unauthorized trading.
14836	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	He immediately confessed and was fired, but spent the weekend helping superiors create a liquidation strategy.
14837	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	The bank said it had filed legal charges against Kerviel and that "four or five" officers responsible for financial surveillance had also lost their jobs.
14838	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	But executives said they believed they had discovered the full extent of the unauthorized trading.
14839	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	Bank executives said that they could not explain the trader's motivation, beyond the possibility that he was trying to show that the bank's financial control procedures could be defeated.
14840	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	There was no evidence that he personally profited from his scheme.
14841	LTW_ENG_20080125.0140.LDC2009T13	They had not yet determined whether Kerviel had accomplices inside or outside the bank.
