15035	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Why the cost has risen so much since the contract was signed with a team led by Lockheed Martin remains in dispute.
15036	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The company declined to comment but has complained to supporters that the Navy added 1,900 more requirements to the helicopters.
15037	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The Navy denies that, saying no extra requirements were added after the contract.
15038	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"It's not the truth," said Stephanie Vendrasco, a spokeswoman for the Navy program.
15039	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"And we can't figure out where that number comes from.
15040	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	It's a myth, and it's becoming a legend."
15041	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	But she and other officials said no one completely grasped the demands for the helicopter at first.
15042	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"The Navy and industry team did not clearly realize the full implications of the White House requirements," John Young Jr., the undersecretary of defense for acquisition, said in a written response to questions.
15043	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	To meet those requirements and retrofit a commercial aircraft to Navy standards, he said, "the Navy and industry teams are having to complete substantial redesign" of the helicopter.
15044	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	He added that "this redesign work is driving significant cost growth into the program."
15045	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Vendrasco attributed the problems partly to an attempt to speed up the normal development process by three years.
15046	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"There was just a slow start out of the gate," she said.
15047	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"And schedule is money."
15048	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The White House has insisted the project go forward.
15049	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"We took a look at what is the best thing to do for future presidents but also looking at it from a cost-benefit analysis," said White House spokesman Gordon Johndroe.
15050	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"The consensus was future presidents need a new helicopter.
15051	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The current ones need to be replaced."
15052	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Johndroe said President Bush has no personal stake in the project because the helicopters will not be ready until after he leaves office.
15053	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Presidents have had helicopters at their service since 1957, when Dwight Eisenhower bristled at how long it took to get from a New England vacation getaway to an airport during a crisis.
15054	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Over the years, sightings of presidents boarding Marine One on the White House lawn have produced memorable moments, perhaps most famously Richard Nixon's two-armed, double-V departure after his resignation in 1974.
15055	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Many of the White House helicopters have been in service since that era.
15056	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The current fleet includes 19 aircraft -- 11 Sikorsky VH-3D Sea Kings and eight VH-60N Black Hawks -- and the oldest have flown presidents for 33 years.
15057	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The squadron also serves the vice president, defense secretary, Navy secretary, visiting heads of state and other officials.
15058	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	So many helicopters are needed because the president typically travels with two or more when he flies, with the extras ferrying staff and Secret Service, serving as backups and playing decoy.
15059	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	When a president makes multiple stops, additional sets of helicopters must be airlifted to his next destinations.
15060	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	On Friday, for instance, Bush went to New York for an economic speech.
15061	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	He climbed into Marine One on the South Lawn, and two other helicopters accompanied him on the 10-minute flight to Andrews Air Force Base, where he boarded Air Force One for the trip north.
15062	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	At John F. Kennedy International Airport, another pair of helicopters waited to fly him into Manhattan.
15063	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Although the Marines maintain the craft with painstaking care, they occasionally break down.
15064	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	In 2006, for example, Bush accepted the resignation of his press secretary, Scott McClellan, during an emotional moment on the South Lawn, and the two then strode to Marine One to fly off together.
15065	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	But the helicopter would not work, and they had to get off and take a car.
15066	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Then-White House Chief of Staff Andrew Card Jr. grew aggravated with the aging fleet's problems in 2002, and he launched the effort to develop a new model with a post-Sept.
15067	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	11 upgrade.
15068	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Although Lockheed Martin does not make helicopters, the Navy chose it over longtime contractor Sikorsky Aircraft because the company's European partner had a three-engine model that seemed a logical off-the-shelf base for a new presidential helicopter.
15069	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	But modifying the EH-101 has proven so complicated that the company is essentially building a new helicopter.
15070	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The first five helicopters are due in 2010, a year behind schedule, though the White House made compromises on the requirements to cut costs and speed delivery.
15071	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Twenty-three more- sophisticated versions are to follow, at which point the current fleet and the first five craft would be retired.
15072	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	But the most recent target date of 2015 for these additional choppers has slipped to an unknown date.
15073	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The problems with the second batch have prompted the Pentagon to issue a stop-work order until it determines what to do and Congress provides more money.
15074	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	The Pentagon conducted a review of the project and considered 35 alternatives, but "none of these options meet the full set of White House requirements," Young said.
15075	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Britain last year bought six standard EH-101 helicopters for about $57 million each -- roughly one-seventh of what it will cost the United States to buy the same aircraft and retrofit it for the president.
15076	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Critics say that sort of mission creep has become too common.
15077	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	"If it was going to cost $11 billion in the first place, somebody should have said so," said Tom Schatz, president of Citizens Against Government Waste.
15078	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., whose district includes Sikorsky's headquarters, said the drastic changes in the helicopter make it a whole new aircraft, so it should be rebid.
15079	LTW_ENG_20080318.0026.LDC2009T13	After all the twists of this project, she said, "We ought to start over."
15080	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Putting a Special `Shine' on the Stones
15081	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Mick Jagger would have, that's who.
15082	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	When asked by Dick Cavett in 1972 whether "you can picture yourself at age 60 doing what you do now," Jagger grinned and responded, "Easily, yeah."
15083	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Period, close quote, end of story.
15084	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	What "Shine a Light," Martin Scorsese's concert documentary, does beautifully is illuminate the way things are now with the self- described world's greatest rock 'n' roll band.
15085	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	We see that benefit show and a Clinton birthday concert, filmed over two nights in 2006 at New York's Beacon Theatre, and by the time it's over, we are thoroughly entertained.
15086	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	But getting to that point turns out to have been a tougher slog than might be expected.
15087	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	What makes it tough, frankly, is all those accumulated years.
15088	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	It's not that the group has any difficulty performing up to its standards, it's that youth and anarchy (not always Bill Clinton's areas) are part of rock's DNA, and seeing the Stones as up close and personal as a concert film demands presents us with the unnerving spectacle of their battle-hardened, not to say sepulchral, faces.
15089	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	This is especially the case with Jagger.
15090	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Yes, he can still run and jump with the best of them, but on camera, that movement plays like a practiced performance untouched by genuine emotion.
15091	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Rather than feeling the music, we are wondering who does his hair and what kind of an exercise and stretching routine he maintains.
15092	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	On the other hand, though, "Sympathy for the Devil" makes us wonder if Jagger really is Mr. Scratch.
15093	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	This is especially true after the band's rendition of "As Tears Go By," originally recorded by Marianne Faithfull, reminds us of how differently age has treated these former lovers.
15094	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Paradoxically, age is hardly a problem with Keith Richards.
15095	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	With his exceptional ability to lose himself in the music -- "I don't think on stage, I feel," he says at one point -- the Stones' guitarist looks like a wraith from another dimension, a being beyond both space and time.
15096	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	If the overall age of the group is a problem, "Shine a Light" has the resources to combat and overcome it, key among them being the amount of filmmaking craft and skill director Scorsese and his team bring to the proceedings.
15097	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	A meticulous planner and music aficionado who worked on "Woodstock" and whose credits include "The Last Waltz" and two excellent PBS music documentary series, Scorsese is also a film preservationist who seems to relish the task of conserving the almost retro nature of these concerts, shooting not in 3-D in massive soccer stadiums the way U2 did but in 35 millimeter in a relatively intimate Broadway theater.
15098	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	And although "Shine a Light" is largely a concert documentary, Scorsese has shrewdly included a smattering of other material, including the Cavett chat.
15099	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	There's some behind-the-scenes footage emphasizing the comic opera aspects of preparation -- "We cannot burn Mick Jagger," the director says sternly when a lighting issue makes immolation a possibility -- as well as a selection of mostly inane interviews the group has endured over the years.
15100	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	The heart of "Shine a Light," though, is the marvelous performance footage the 18 camera operators, led by director of photography Robert Richardson and including such major talents as Robert Elswit, John Toll, Albert Maysles, Stuart Dryburgh, Andrew Lesnie, Emmanuel Lubezki, Declan Quinn and Ellen Kuras, have managed to capture.
15101	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	As put together in a heroic nine-month job of editing by David Tedeschi, this remarkable footage casually captures wonderful moments of musicianship and style, from Buddy Guy's intense guitar work on "Champagne and Reefer" to Ronnie Wood's hypnotic pedal steel solo on "Far Away Eyes" as well as Richards coolly spitting a cigarette out of his mouth just because he wants to.
15102	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	Finally, it is the scorching intensity of the blues- and R&amp
15103	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	B-inflected songs the Stones play, not any on-stage antics, that keeps the group involved in performing and the audience keyed into the film.
15104	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	With expert backup singers and veteran musicians such as Bobby Keys on tenor sax and Darryl Jones on bass providing a solid grounding, the music's insistent richness builds and builds, its sound becoming so deep and persuasive that qualms about age fade and the rhythms carry us away.
15105	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	The Stones have been in any number of memorable films, including 1970's "Gimme Shelter" and Robert Frank's documentary with the unprintable name, but this outing is special, because of where it arrives and the obstacles it faced along the way.
15106	LTW_ENG_20080404.0110.LDC2009T13	"Shine a Light" might not be the last Rolling Stones movie, but it's likely to be the last one with a touch of the poet about it.
15107	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Bhutan: `A Society on the Threshold of Change'
15108	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The children pounced on Nordon Gurung's lap, tugging on her long hair, spilling apple juice on her traditional skirt and singing songs in her ear, as if she were their grandmother.
15109	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	But Gurung is not a granny, or even a relative.
15110	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	She is a day-care provider, a once-unknown profession in this traditional and secluded Himalayan nation where grandparents have long been in charge of watching over children.
15111	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"To most elder Bhutanese, leaving your child here while you work is utterly mind-altering," said Gurung, as she lined up the children for their morning exercises under blossoming peach trees.
15112	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"But for our young, working parents, this is a wonderful lifeline."
15113	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The growing number of day-care centers in Bhutan is just one of the ways in which this ancient civilization is modernizing, often at rapid speeds.
15114	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	More Bhutanese are moving to cities and away from their extended families, traditionally a vital part of the social structure here.
15115	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	In the capital, Thimphu, young Bhutanese are wearing Western-style jeans and tuning in to satellite TV for the first time, watching programs such as "Desperate Housewives."
15116	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Now, many fear Bhutan's unique culture will be diluted, or even overtaken, by the powerful forces of globalization.
15117	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"Bhutan is a society on the threshold of change," said Namgay Zam, 22, a disc jockey at "Kazoo FM: The Voice of the Youth."
15118	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"We're struggling to find the right balance.
15119	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It's one of the most challenging questions for the next generation: How do you modernize, but also remain Bhutanese?"
15120	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Sandwiched between China and India, the world's most populous nations, rugged, forested Bhutan is landlocked and has just 2.2 million people.
15121	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It has long feared for its survival.
15122	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Bhutanese watched nervously as Tibet was occupied by China in 1950 and the tiny Himalayan kingdom of Sikkim was swallowed up by India in 1975.
15123	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Bhutan has remained peaceful.
15124	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Buddhist prayer wheels sit like kings in village squares, and centuries-old fortresses poke up through blue pine forests.
15125	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The country's revered king, Jigme Singye Wangchuck, abdicated in favor of his son in 2006, but he transformed Bhutanese life in ways that remain evident.
15126	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	He made national dress compulsory at offices and temples -- men wear a kilt-like gho, with black knee- high socks
15127	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	women sport colorful, floor-length skirts -- and he introduced a philosophy he called gross national happiness.
15128	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It's a measure of happiness built around the idea of retaining Bhutan's culture and protecting its pristine streams and forests.
15129	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Fresh from elections last month that ended more than a century of royal rule, Bhutan is now a constitutional monarchy.
15130	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It's struggling to do what many other countries have struggled to do: open up to the world while retaining its way of life.
15131	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	One Bhutanese leader has remarked that Bhutan may well be the last country on earth to allow a McDonald's to raise its arches, which here would sit among monasteries and pagodas.
15132	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Bhutan's royal government didn't legalize satellite television until 1999.
15133	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It was the last country in the world to introduce broadcast television.
15134	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It did, however, later ban MTV and the World Wrestling Entertainment channel.
15135	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"Apparently it was making the youth too violent, since they were wrestling each other all day.
15136	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The government felt this violence was not Buddhist and goes against our gross national happiness philosophy," Zam, the DJ, said with a laugh.
15137	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	She said she opposed the ban, but also saw the reason for it.
15138	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"Maybe it was a good thing to be able to understand our Bhutanese identity first, and then open up to the world," she said.
15139	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Bhutan likes doing things its own way.
15140	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	It is the only country in the world to ban the sale of tobacco.
15141	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Thimphu is the only capital in the world without a traffic light
15142	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	instead, a white-gloved traffic officer directs cars, pedestrians and yak herds.
15143	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The city had a zoo, but freed the animals, saying it wasn't in the Buddhist spirit to cage the national mammal, the takin, which has the head of a goat and the body of a moose.
15144	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	While Bhutan's ways are quirky, the culture, at least in urban areas, is morphing into something new.
15145	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Thimphu's central square is filled with teen-agers strumming guitars and wearing buttons with the names of rock bands such as Metallica.
15146	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	A transvestite recently went out in public to a disco -- a sign, the DJs at Kazoo said, that youth culture is open to previously shunned ideas.
15147	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Many younger Bhutanese have started to fuse their culture with the tastes of the West.
15148	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The Zone Cafe in Thimphu, for instance, serves yak burgers and pizza with yak meat.
15149	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	A Bhutanese fashion designer, Sangay Choden, put Velcro around the waist of her traditional kiras to make them easier to wear.
15150	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"I wanted to be creative and voice what our youth feel today.
15151	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	But I also wanted to keep being Bhutanese," Choden said.
15152	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"It can be done."
15153	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	That's what parents at Gurung's day-care center are hoping for.
15154	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Because the government is wary of permitting too much change too quickly, it has placed restrictions on day-care centers, licensing only those that watch children over the age of 3.
15155	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	The decision has effectively pushed grandparents to stay at home for the first years of a child's life or working parents to hire a nanny.
15156	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Now, parents at Gurung's center are lobbying the government to allow day care for younger children.
15157	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	They say the rules could require them to be at the center during work breaks and lunches.
15158	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"Day-care centers will keep evolving," said Gado Tshering, secretary of health.
15159	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	"But we don't always want to completely copy the West.
15160	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Imagine if we opened those, how do you say ... old-age homes?
15161	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	Imagine if Bhutanese people actually started to kick out their grandparents?
15162	LTW_ENG_20080405.0047.LDC2009T13	We just couldn't allow such a thing."
