15287	LTW_ENG_20080724.0012.LDC2009T13	But, on balance, it is in the United States' interest, and Congress should find the time to say yes -- in a lame-duck session after the November election, if necessary.
15288	LTW_ENG_20080724.0012.LDC2009T13	U.S. nuclear cooperation with India ceased when India, which had refused to sign the 1968 Non-Proliferation Treaty, exploded a nuclear "device" in 1974.
15289	LTW_ENG_20080724.0012.LDC2009T13	The sanctions were intended to show India, and the world, that there was a price to be paid for flouting the treaty.
15290	LTW_ENG_20080724.0012.LDC2009T13	Times change, though, and the Bush administration's logic is that the benefits of a "strategic partnership" with India outweigh the risks of waiving the old rules.
15291	LTW_ENG_20080724.0012.LDC2009T13	If booming India uses more nuclear energy, it will emit less in greenhouse gases.
