15370	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	"On the contrary, they undermine the very basis of cooperation and may fuel the fire of hatred and violence that we are trying to extinguish."
15371	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	U.S. military officials in Afghanistan, at the Central Command in Tampa and at the Pentagon maintained a wall of silence, saying they had no comment on the Pakistani reports.
15372	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Lou Fintor, a U.S. Embassy spokesman in Islamabad, also declined to comment.
15373	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Pakistani sources gave varying accounts, including on the number of troops and helicopters involved, and on whether U.S. troops were among those who left the helicopters and conducted a ground operation in the village.
15374	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	There were also differing versions of how far inside Pakistan the helicopters flew, because the border's location is disputed.
15375	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	By one count, the target village lay about 20 miles from the border.
15376	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	According to Pakistani military sources, the raid began about 3 a.m. Wednesday when two or possibly three U.S. Army helicopters carrying American and Afghan troops landed in Musa Nika village in the Pakistani tribal area of South Waziristan.
15377	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The raid was apparently in response to a rocket that fighters fired at a convoy inside Afghanistan, according to one senior Pakistani official.
15378	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	"By the time they got there," the official said, "the guy with the rocket had moved."
15379	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	According to another Pakistani official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity because he is not authorized to give out information, several of the troops left the helicopters and launched an assault on three houses.
15380	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	One of the homes belonged to local tribesman Pao Jan Ahmedzai Wazir, according to Anwar Shah, a resident of a neighboring village.
15381	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Several women and children who were inside Wazir's house and two other homes nearby were killed when U.S. and Afghan troops fired on the buildings, he said.
15382	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	"The situation there is very terrible.
15383	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	People are trying to take out the dead bodies," Shah said.
15384	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The reported attack comes at a time of debate over the rules of military operation along the 1,500 mile border between Afghanistan and Pakistan.
15385	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The Pakistani military appears to have acceded to U.S. pressure to step up attacks on extremists in its border areas.
15386	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	In the past two months, it has launched major offensives on Taliban and al- Qaida strongholds in two of the country's Federally Administered Tribal Areas.
15387	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Analysts in Islamabad say that the incursion into South Waziristan could augur a tactical turn aimed at cutting off an insurgency that threatens to engulf large swaths of Pakistan and reverse gains made by U.S. and NATO forces in Afghanistan.
15388	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The Pentagon has never acknowledged a case of hot pursuit into Pakistan.
15389	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Wednesday's incident "doesn't fit that bill," the senior Pakistani official said.
15390	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	There was no indication U.S. forces had begun a ground pursuit inside Afghanistan that led them into Pakistani territory.
15391	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	A Pakistani military liaison unit at the main U.S. military base in Afghanistan, Bagram, is under military procedures to be informed of any incursion.
15392	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Pakistani officials insist there was no such notification.
15393	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Last week, Adm. Michael Mullen, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, held a meeting with the Pakistani army chief, Gen. Ashfaq Kiyani, aboard a U.S. aircraft carrier in the Indian Ocean after several serious setbacks for Western and Afghan forces in Afghanistan.
15394	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	U.S. and Pakistani officials have released few details about the meeting, which was also attended by Gen. David McKiernan, NATO's top commander in Afghanistan.
15395	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	But a senior Pakistani military official with knowledge of the meeting said that Mullen and Kiyani focused in large part on the threat to international forces in Afghanistan emanating from insurgents operating inside Pakistan's borders.
15396	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The Pakistani military official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the meeting touched on a possible agreement to allow U.S. Special Forces to begin ground operations in Pakistan's tribal areas.
15397	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	Maj. Gen. Athar Abbas, chief spokesman for the Pakistani military, denied that there was any agreement for U.S. troops to operate on Pakistani territory.
15398	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	A NATO spokesman in Afghanistan said foreign forces are generally prohibited from mounting cross-border attacks into Pakistan.
15399	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	The spokesman, who gave his name only as Sgt. Yates, said NATO forces occasionally use artillery or missiles to target insurgents who attack foreign troops from Pakistani territory, but the rules of engagement are very precise.
15400	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	"Our area of operations stops at the border.
15401	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	We don't go over the border, period," Yates said.
15402	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	In Afghanistan, NATO and U.S. military operations have recently come under scrutiny because of an airstrike that Afghan and U.N. officials said killed up to 90 civilians two weeks ago.
15403	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	On Wednesday, McKiernan said that he concurred with a U.S. military investigation that found that five civilians died in the incident.
15404	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	McKiernan expressed sorrow at the loss of civilian lives in the strike, which began late on Aug. 21 in the village of Azizabad and continued into the early morning hours of Aug. 22.
15405	LTW_ENG_20080904.0127.LDC2009T13	He said NATO would work to better coordinate with the Afghan government and the U.N. mission in Afghanistan to respond to incidents involving civilian casualties.
