15409	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Pension of Disbelief
15410	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	The following editorial appeared in Monday's Washington Post:
15411	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	As you might expect, the subject of a recent American Academy of Actuaries forum was rather technical: the standards that state and local pension plans use to determine how much to invest to keep their retirement promises to government workers.
15412	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	While eye- glazing, this topic is critically important to state and local taxpayers because some of them may get stuck with an unexpected pension bill unless the actuaries, and the Governmental Accounting Standards Board (GASB), which will receive their recommendations, take a stand for accuracy and full disclosure.
15413	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	As The Washington Post reported this month, state and local government pension plans, unlike many private-sector plans, are allowed to calculate the adequacy of their funding based on relatively rosy projections about their earnings.
15414	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Instead of assuming a rate of return pegged to the lowest-risk investment, a 30-year Treasury bond (currently about 4 percent), they typically use a benchmark of 8 percent, which implies that they will do very well for very long periods in the riskier stock and bond markets.
15415	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	How likely is that?
15416	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	As Berkshire Hathaway Chairman Warren E. Buffett (a member of The Washington Post Co.'s board) noted in a recent letter to his shareholders, the Dow Jones industrial average, currently hovering around 11,000, would have to hit about 2,000,000 by the end of this century just to match the 5.3 percent annual rate of return stocks yielded in the last one.
15417	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Now, we have nothing against optimism, but in this case, it permits state and local officials to make sweet promises -- high benefits, low retirement ages -- to civil servants without having to raise the funds that might actually be necessary to keep them.
15418	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	This may not be good policy, but it's good politics since officials who make unrealistic commitments usually aren't around when they come due.
15419	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	To be sure, most pension funds are financially sound: 58 percent, according to a recent study by the Government Accountability Office.
15420	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Even those that are underfunded are still meeting current obligations.
15421	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Unlike private firms, governments probably should not accumulate surpluses in their pension funds because that creates political pressure to raid the excess for spending.
15422	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	And, unlike private firms, governments generally do not go bankrupt.
15423	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	Still, it's not impossible.
15424	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	The city of Vallejo, Calif., declared bankruptcy in May, partly because it had granted police and firefighters six-figure pensions that kicked in at age 50.
15425	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	The U.S. population is aging, and long-term inflation is a fact of life.
15426	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	The actuaries and the GASB should urge state and local governments to play by more cautious -- and more transparent -- rules.
15427	LTW_ENG_20080916.0003.LDC2009T13	For taxpayers trying to understand their governments' true pension liabilities, the best surprise is no surprise.
15428	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	Lawsuit Says Auto Club Imposes Battery Sales Quotas (Los Angeles)
15429	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	LOS ANGELES
15430	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	Members of the Automobile Club of Southern California who call for roadside help when they have a dead battery often are sold new batteries when only a jump start is needed, a lawsuit filed Tuesday alleges.
15431	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The lawsuit, filed in Los Angeles County Superior Court, alleges that the Auto Club imposes a quota system regarding battery sales on the tow truck operators who answer roadside assistance calls placed by club members.
15432	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	Auto Club tow-truck drivers who fail to meet their quota risk losing "valuable future customers," the suit contends, and operators who exceed their quotas are paid unspecified incentives.
15433	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The suit, which seeks class-action status, was filed on behalf of L.A.-area resident Paul Martin Davis-Miller.
15434	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	According to the suit, Miller called the Auto Club earlier this year when his car wouldn't start.
15435	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The tow truck operator who answered the call sold him a new battery that cost him about $125.
15436	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	"However, subsequent tests of the purportedly `dead' battery have established that the replaced battery was fully functional and able to hold a full charge," according to the suit.
15437	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	A spokesman for the Auto Club, which has more than 6 million members, said he hadn't seen the suit and couldn't comment on the allegations.
15438	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	In 2001, the Auto Club launched a new program in which tow truck operators could replace batteries at the scene of a breakdown rather than simply tow the vehicle to a repair facility.
15439	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The service has been popular with members, said David Lang, the Auto Club's vice president of automotive services.
15440	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The Auto Club gets about 4 million calls a year for roadside assistance, including dead batteries, lockouts and motorists who run out of gas.
15441	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	San Francisco attorney William Audet, who filed the lawsuit, said the number of victims could run into the thousands.
15442	LTW_ENG_20080924.0132.LDC2009T13	The suit seeks repayment of money allegedly paid for fraudulently replaced batteries as well as unspecified punitive damages.
