15569	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Great Educators: John Comer
15570	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	James P. Comer, the child psychiatrist who pioneered research on raising student achievement among poor minorities via collaborating with parents and community services.
15571	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	To educate the lowest achieving students (who are most often poor, in rural isolation, or from marginalized minorities), it will be necessary to turn traditional schooling on its conceptual head.
15572	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	The current, mechanical, input-output model that pervades our schooling system and focuses immediately on curriculum, instruction, and assessment must be changed to a model that focuses primarily on relationships, creating a positive culture, and student development.
15573	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	What reads like a slight difference is a huge and profound change in practice.
15574	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Development and learning are inextricably linked and take place through a critical dynamic: From birth caretakers interact with the young in ways that make emotional attachment and bonding possible.
15575	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Through this arrangement, as the young act on their environment to build their own survival and expressive capacities, they can imitate, identify with, and internalize the attitudes, values and life management styles of their meaningful caretakers.
15576	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Also, through this arrangement, caretakers can mediate the physical (including brain construction), psycho-emotional, moral- ethical, linguistic, cognitive-academic learning growth and development of children and students.
15577	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Most students from mainstream backgrounds -- regardless of their socioeconomic, racial or regional backgrounds -- experience this dynamic.
15578	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Children who do not come from mainstream backgrounds, or who have a non-mainstream experience, are more likely to be underdeveloped, or differently developed, and are less likely to be successful in school and in life.
15579	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Such children often lack the competencies, confidence and sense of belonging needed to perform well in school.
15580	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	They often withhold or withdraw, or act in inappropriate ways as they sense failure in the school setting.
15581	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Nonetheless, many of these students are from vibrant and meaningful subcultures.
15582	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Their emotional attachment to kin, friends and the cultural organizations to which they feel they belong is very powerful.
15583	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Many of these students, even when making academic progress in school, may eventually be highly conflicted about or reject the mainstream school and life culture if there are no positive sanctions and there is no collaboration between home, school, and community.
15584	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Most teachers and administrators -- through no fault of their own -- are not prepared to create school cultures that create a sense of belonging, support student development, and positively sanction activities and behaviors that make success possible in school and in the mainstream of the society.
15585	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	Student underdevelopment and staff under-preparation is the major reason that capable students are performing badly.
15586	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	The way to change this is simple to state, but difficult to bring about.
15587	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	The entire 3 to 4 million-person education workforce needs to create the kind of school culture that supports development, teaching, academic success and life preparation.
15588	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	There is evidence that this can be done.
15589	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	But leadership within each element of the education enterprise -- parents, teachers, school administrators, policymakers at every level and school staff preparatory programs -- must work collaboratively and synchronously to make it possible.
15590	LTW_ENG_20081018.0067.LDC2009T13	With a focus on the underlying problem, commitment to and an appropriate framework for change, it will be possible to educate all children well.
15591	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Iraq's Parliament Approves Governing Quotas
15592	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Also Monday, three bombs in Baghdad killed at least seven people, most of them at a busy square targeted by twin blasts that exploded seconds apart during morning rush hour.
15593	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Another bomb north of the capital killed one person and contributed to a day of violence that underscored the ongoing tensions in Iraq even as it enjoys a period of relative tranquillity.No date has been set for the provincial vote, but it is due to take place by Jan. 31 and has been heralded as key to undoing lopsided power structures blamed for fueling sectarian violence.
15594	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The minority quota formula approved by lawmakers would guarantee a total of six seats spread across three provincial councils to Christians and three smaller minority groups: Yazidis, Sabians and Shabaks.
15595	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Of the 150 lawmakers present, 106 voted for the plan.
15596	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	It sets aside one seat for Christian parties on the provincial councils of Baghdad, Ninevah, and Basra.
15597	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Sabians, a pacifist religious sect, will also receive one seat in Baghdad.
15598	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Yazidis, from another religious sect, and Shabaks, an ethnic minority, will each have one seat on the Ninevah council.
15599	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Like Christians, the other groups have claimed persecution under the Shiite Muslim-led Iraqi government and demanded special protection when parliament in September passed the law setting the stage for provincial elections.
15600	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	That law failed to include special considerations for parties representing minorities, prompting protests by Christian lawmakers and weeks of wrangling to come up with a solution acceptable to small groups and to the Shiite, Kurdish and Sunni Arab parties vying for dominance.
15601	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The approved quotas were less generous than those in two other proposals which would have granted a total of either eight or 12 seats to minority parties, and the choice illustrated the fears and distrust among lawmakers in heavily contested, ethnically mixed areas.
15602	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Ninevah, in northern Iraq, is particularly sensitive because of its mixed population largely composed of Sunni Arabs, Kurds, Christians and Yazidis.
15603	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Sunnis Arabs had resisted setting aside large minority quotas on the 37-seat provincial council, fearful that minority groups might lean toward the Kurds and bolster Kurdish hopes of expanding their influence in the north.
15604	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The 12-seat option rejected Monday would have set aside seven minority seats on the council.
15605	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Hassan Alaf, a Sunni Arab lawmaker, said the minorities will receive the number of seats they deserve based on their population in the region.
15606	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	"The decision . . . was very fair," said Alaf.
15607	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	"We believe granting one seat to each minority is pretty good and leaves decent room for the larger slates to compete fairly."
15608	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Alaf noted that Christian, Yazidi or other minority politicians could increase their voices in Ninevah by running for office under the banner of large political blocs.
15609	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	That would guarantee them their guaranteed one-seat quota, plus more seats if they had enough public support, he said.
15610	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	"This does not limit their participation or prevent them from nominating themselves in any slate," he said.
15611	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	"This way, they can get more seats if they have a good number of votes."
15612	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	But Christian lawmaker Younadem Kana denounced the vote as an "insult" and said it showed the "fanaticism and racism" of Arabs fearful of Kurdish influence.
15613	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	He said Arabs had feared Christians would ally themselves with the Kurds and sought to sabotage this possibility by blocking the larger quotas.
15614	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Kurdish lawmakers said they had opposed the bill because it did not give Christians more guaranteed seats.
15615	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	"The voting of today showed who is fighting the Christians and who is supporting them," said Arif Tayfur, a Kurdish political leader and parliamentarian.
15616	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The deal must be approved by the nation's three-member presidency council, and Kana said he would demand a veto.
15617	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Earlier this year, Kurds succeeded in putting plans for provincial elections on hold when President Jalal Talabani, a member of the presidency, vetoed an election bill that had passed parliament over Kurdish objections.
15618	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	That forced a re-negotiation of the law and led to the version passed in September and tweaked in Monday's voting.
15619	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	There was no indication the Christians could force another veto, although their bitter objections raise the specter of heightened tensions in the north, which is currently the country's most violent region.
15620	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The rest of Iraq has seen a sharp decline in bloodshed in recent months, but Monday's attacks showed the lingering instability.
15621	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	The worst blasts occurred seconds apart in front of a police building in central Baghdad.
15622	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Six people were killed, including a 14-year-old boy.
15623	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Cars, shops and a restaurant were damaged, and the wounded included several police officers.
15624	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	A roadside bomb in eastern Baghdad targeting an Iraqi police convoy killed one policeman.
15625	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	In Baqouba, the capital of Diyala province north of Baghdad, a car bomb in the parking lot of the provincial council exploded, killing one policeman and wounding 10 people.
15626	LTW_ENG_20081104.0088.LDC2009T13	Staff writer Ned Parker in Baghdad and special correspondents in Baghdad and Baqouba contributed to this report.
