15696	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Mexico's President Ernest Zedillo, in a historic-three day visit to California, has offered praise for the new relationship between his country and the state and a pledge to work with Gov. Gray Davis to create ``a North American dream.''
15697	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``We have far to go,'' Zedillo said in a speech Wednesday to Town Hall of Los Angeles.
15698	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``We now have a great friend here in California (in Davis) who has made human relations a priority and has declared Mexico the most important country for California.
15699	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``And California is important to Mexico.
15700	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	What happens in California affects Mexico.''
15701	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo and Gov. Gray Davis came from Sacramento to Los Angeles by train and were greeted at Union Station by Mayor Richard Riordan and other dignitaries.
15702	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Riordan offered praise for both Davis and Zedillo in seeking a harmonious relationship.
15703	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``(Zedillo) recognizes, as we do, that we cannot prosper as independent communities if we do not prosper in partnership,'' Riordan said.
15704	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``As we celebrate our history, we also embrace the dawn of a new century and the hope for a new generation where our people can share in the bounty of opportunity, prosperity and partnership,'' Riordan said.
15705	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Both Davis and Riordan attempted frequent words and phrases in Spanish, with the governor often referring to ``mi amigo.''
15706	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Riordan said to Zedillo at one point, ``Nuestra casa es su casa.''
15707	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Davis, who visited Zedillo on an official trip one month after taking office, said his vision is to see California and Mexico re-create the American dream as the North American dream.
15708	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``People came to America for liberty, opportunity, prosperity,'' Davis said.
15709	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``We want to see equal access to education, health care and justice.''
15710	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo credited Davis for the change in attitudes between the two countries since his election and the retirement of Republican Gov. Pete Wilson.
15711	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	It was Proposition 187 banning many benefits to illegal immigrants and Wilson's support for it that led to a chill in relations.
15712	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	The voter-approved ballot measure has been blocked by the courts from taking effect and Davis is seeking mediation on the matter, which has angered many Latino officials.
15713	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo, however, backed the governor and said relations between California and Mexico have never been better.
15714	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``Mexico is now your No.1 trading partner,'' Zedillo said.
15715	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``Just think how much better it could be.''
15716	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	On Tuesday, Davis and Zedillo agreed to create a computer hookup between universities in California and Mexico.
15717	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	On Wednesday, they announced California would create 15 trade centers to work with companies to increase trade with Mexico.
15718	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	They also announced plans by Mexico's Federal Electricity Commission and America's Sempra Energy International to construct a 23-mile gas pipeline, from the border to Rosarito to provide energy.
15719	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Davis said the project will include 500 jobs in California.
15720	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Also, the U.S. Department of Transportation has approved a $160,000 grant to study infrastructure needs along the border.
15721	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo also called for California authorities to work to protect the human rights of all people, saying there had been some problems with the treatment of immigrants.
15722	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	But most of the day was spent in saluting one another.
15723	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo took note of the number of Mexican descendants living in Los Angeles _ more than anywhere else in the world outside of Mexico.
15724	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``They work hard and proud as (U.S.) citizens, but they do not forget their heritage,'' Zedillo said.
15725	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	Zedillo also talked of political reform that he is pushing on his country, where his party will allow open primaries for the first time in its 70-year history.
15726	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``No longer will an official be elected only because he is from one party,'' Zedillo said.
15727	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	``We are moving toward more democracy.
15728	NYT_ENG_19990520.0057.LDC2007T07	We find that nearly all the time, the people are right.''
