15851	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	NYMEX ABANDONING PLANS FOR BRITISH TRADING FLOOR
15852	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	LONDON
15853	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex Holdings, parent company of the New York Mercantile Exchange and a lonely champion of open-outcry trading, is cutting its last ties to an ill-fated plan to set up a trading floor in Britain.
15854	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	The commodities market has quietly applied for "derecognition of exchange" with British regulators, traders here in London said.
15855	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Markets that trade in London are required to certify to the main regulator, the Financial Services Authority of Britain, that they are "recognized investment exchanges."
15856	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	With the request for "derecognition," Nymex's presence in London reverts to a marketing office, a far cry from the ambitious expansion plans it undertook less than two years ago.
15857	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	"We've had to adjust our business model," a Nymex spokeswoman, Anu Ahluwalia, said Tuesday, confirming the application.
15858	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	"We were very ambitious and went in and built a trading floor, and that is not the way that business is going, so we adapted very quickly."
15859	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Since Nymex went public last November, investors and analysts have wondered how the company might expand internationally and take advantage of the worldwide boom in commodities.
15860	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex's British foray could provide a good road map of the wrong way to do so.
15861	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	The movement across the Atlantic started after the International Petroleum Exchange in London went fully electronic in April 2005, following 25 years of open-outcry trading.
15862	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	That market is part of the IntercontinentalExchange, or ICE, Nymex's big rival.
15863	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	The New York exchange had already tested an open-outcry exchange in Dublin, which it opened in 2004.
15864	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	But Nymex was not able to move quickly, and it took five months to get the trading floor up and running, a result in part of regulatory snarls.
15865	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex spent millions trying to encourage traders to use its London floor, and on the first day of trading, in September 2005, 12 companies and 76 traders showed up.
15866	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex was expected to start open-pit exchanges in Dubai, Singapore and possibly Tokyo or Shanghai.
15867	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	But the British initiative proved short-lived, and appears to have discouraged plans for open pits elsewhere.
15868	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	By March 2006, Nymex in London was trading fewer than 20 contracts a day for Brent crude futures, the most common oil contract here, compared with about 200,000 on ICE Futures.
15869	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Executives at other exchanges and commodity traders said that Nymex's five-month delay in opening gave the International Petroleum Exchange time to learn how to trade electronically, or time to drift into another business.
15870	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	The IPE's electronic exchange was also faster than some critics expected.
15871	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex's foray also inspired ICE to start trading an important Nymex product, West Texas intermediate crude oil.
15872	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	By June 2006, Nymex had closed its London open-outcry floor and transferred trading of European commodity contracts onto an electronic and an over-the-counter exchange.
15873	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Open outcry in London "never took off the way that we hoped," Ahluwalia said.
15874	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	"This is by no means an end to our global growth."
15875	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Nymex Holdings also includes the Comex metals market in New York.
15876	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	It has offices in Singapore and Tokyo, and is working with the Dubai government to open a mercantile exchange there, which will be electronic.
15877	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	"We're going to expand our brand globally," Ahluwalia said, "just not through a trading floor."
15878	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Though Nymex failed in London, some open-outcry exchanges still exist here.
15879	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	The London Metal Exchange does the bulk of its trading by open outcry, and had record volume in 2006.
15880	NYT_ENG_20070123.0229.LDC2009T13	Open outcry "is still the most efficient and most popular method of trading," a spokesman for the London Metal Exchange, Adam Robinson, said.
