15923	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	U.N. OFFICIAL ADVANCES PLAN THAT COULD MAKE KOSOVO INDEPENDENT
15924	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	PARIS
15925	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The U.N. mediator Martti Ahtisaari presented his proposals for the final status of Kosovo on Friday, likely setting the tiny war-torn territory on its way toward independence.
15926	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Although that goal is still months away and subject to a vote at the United Nations, the presentation of a plan is an important and long-delayed step in resolving the still potentially explosive tensions that led to war in Europe just eight years ago.
15927	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The recommendations would leave the former Yugoslav province free to declare independence from Serbia, according to Western diplomats who discussed the plan that will be made public next week.
15928	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	But they say the plan would also impose international supervision, much like what exists in Bosnia, in what appears to be an attempt to provide protection for Kosovo's ethnic Serb minority.
15929	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	As a result, the proposals fall short of the full independence so hoped for by the territory's majority population of ethnic Albanians, according to Western diplomats.
15930	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Even with the promise of international involvement, the diplomats say, Russia, a Serbian ally whose support is key, remains cool to the plan.
15931	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The proposals foresee a strong international presence for the indefinite future, and include "a lot of measures to guarantee and promote the rights of the minority communities," Remi Dourlot, Ahtisaari's spokesman, said in Vienna, where the plan was presented.
15932	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	NATO troops, which have kept peace in Kosovo since fighting ended in 1999, would remain for the time being.
15933	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The U.N. mission governing the territory would be replaced by another international organization that would have executive powers to any annul legislation that breaches Kosovo's obligations under U.N. agreements, diplomats said.
15934	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	If the U.N. Security Council approves the plan, Kosovo is expected to quickly declare its independence and could expect swift recognition from its U.S. and European supporters, even if Serbia rejected such a move.
15935	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	But that step, diplomats caution, is probably months away.
15936	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	"I foresee this process taking some time, and we might be in a wholly different situation," said one senior Western diplomat in Vienna who asked not to be identified because he was not authorized to comment on the proposal until it is made public.
15937	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	"No one can predict the Security Council dynamic."
15938	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Ahtisaari handed his recommendations to representatives of the so-called Contact Group -- the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and Russia -- during a meeting at a secret location in the Austrian capital.
15939	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	It will be presented to the Serbian government in Belgrade and the Kosovo government in Pristina on Feb. 2.
15940	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Even then, only the broad outlines of the proposal are expected to be made public.
15941	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Serbia and Kosovo will have the opportunity to ask questions and suggest changes to the proposals.
15942	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	When Ahtisaari feels he has exhausted those negotiations, he will present a plan to the Security Council for approval.
15943	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Kosovo and Belgrade remain far apart in their positions, and experts say it is unlikely Ahtisaari can close the gap.
15944	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Already, Russia, which supports Serbia's efforts to keep Kosovo as a province, is pushing for the Security Council vote to be delayed until Belgrade has formed a government after recent elections, diplomats in Vienna say.
15945	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Serbia's nationalist Radical Party came in first with 28 percent of the vote earlier this month, but the democratic parties that came in second and third have the best chance to form a coalition.
15946	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	It took Serbian parties three months to form a government after the previous elections.
15947	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
15948	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	But four Western diplomats interviewed said they doubted that Serbia could prevail upon Russia to veto a resolution once the Security Council is presented with one.
15949	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Ahtisaari, a former Finnish president, has not said when he expects to send the proposals to the Security Council, but diplomats involved in the negotiations say they are pressing for it to happen this spring.
15950	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	(END OPTIONAL TRIM)
15951	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Within hours of the Vienna meeting, details of the document were leaking out.
15952	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	According to one diplomat familiar with the proposal, it would give Kosovo the right to enter into some international agreements and join world organizations as a sovereign state.
15953	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	NATO would train a civil defense force that could eventually become a Kosovo army, though it is not clear what would become of the controversial Kosovo Protection Corps, which includes former Kosovo Liberation Army fighters and has been accused of aiding ethnic Albanian rebels in Macedonia and other misconduct.
15954	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	In other ways, Kosovo would remain subject to international community oversight.
15955	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The European Union is already setting up a police force of more than 1,000 officers to monitor the territory's police, judges, prosecutors and even prison guards.
15956	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	The most sensitive part of the plan concerns treatment of the estimated 114,000 Serbs in Kosovo, most of whom adamantly oppose independence from Serbia.
15957	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	To reassure the minority that their rights will not be overrun, some Serbian areas would reportedly be given autonomy, and be free to receive some Serbian government help in building hospitals and schools.
15958	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Ahtisaari's plan also reportedly provides for the creation of several new municipalities where the concentration of Serbs is high.
15959	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Serbian legislators in the Kosovo parliament, meanwhile, would be able to stop at least some legislation if they believe it discriminates against the Serb minority.
15960	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	Serbian religious institutions would also be guaranteed special protection.
15961	NYT_ENG_20070126.0179.LDC2009T13	More than two dozen Serbian churches and monasteries, many dating to the 12th and 13th centuries, were destroyed during two days of unrest in March 2004.
