16205	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	FAMILY-OWNED FIRM TRIES TO PASS ON SOCIAL VALUES
16206	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	HOLLAND, Mich.
16207	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Right up there with putting an aging parent in a nursing home stands the wrenching job of handing over a family business to be run by outsiders.
16208	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	It happens to any family firm that lasts long enough, from Wal- Mart Stores on down.
16209	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	And, as the experience of the 102-year-old Louis Padnos Iron &amp
16210	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	amp
16211	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Metal Co. shows, the transition can be as quirky as the founding family.
16212	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	The Padnos' problem is an age gap.
16213	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Third-generation members who run the scrap-metal company, which employs about 400 people and has annual sales of about $300 million, are in their 50s.
16214	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	They want to work less.
16215	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	But the fourth-generation Padnoses who might someday want to run the place are still only in their teens.
16216	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	So, the company hired a local philosophy professor, a man who also spends time tutoring convicts at a nearby state prison in classic literature and other topics, to help groom six hired managers to become, well, more Padnos-like.
16217	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	What does that mean?
16218	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	For starters, as the Padnoses themselves point out, they are politically liberal, Jewish and, having grown up wealthy enough to travel widely, they are worldly.
16219	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Mitchell W. Padnos, one of four third-generation owners who run the company, worked after college at a Barcelona, Spain, steel mill.
16220	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	His cousin, Jeff Padnos, now the company president, once gave a speech to a Katmandu, Nepal, science club in the middle of a six- month around-the-world vacation before starting business school, he said.
16221	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	The managers, on the other hand, are mostly conservative, from Protestant backgrounds with working class-roots, and have spent much less time outside western Michigan.
16222	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"We just happen to be a Jewish family sitting in the middle of this," said Mitch Padnos, growing up and living in an area that has historically been heavily Dutch.
16223	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	He added that the elder Padnoses expected their children to behave in ways that reflected well on their religion.
16224	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"My dad was very sensitive," he said.
16225	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	As a result, the third-generation Padnoses view themselves as part entrepreneurs, part social workers.
16226	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	And it is the latter quality they seem most eager to pass along to the managers.
16227	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"I'm becoming more and more missionary-like," said Jeff Padnos.
16228	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"Doing business right really is like applied religion."
16229	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	He said he recently agreed to hire a man with a criminal record.
16230	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	If it works out, he said, "you remember that better than any buy- low, sell-high deal you've made."
16231	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	The company said it had never laid off workers.
16232	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	A family foundation holds about $7 million and contributes to many local organizations each year.
16233	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	The Padnos name is all over western Michigan, adorning the Amtrak station here, the engineering school at nearby Grand Valley State University and sculpture gardens in the area.
16234	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"They're wonderful benefactors," said the mayor of Holland, Al McGeehan.
16235	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Sure, the Padnoses could sell the company and probably collect considerably more than $100 million.
16236	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	But selling, said Mitch Padnos, would make him just another idle rich guy.
16237	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"I have friends who have no place to go every day," he said.
16238	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"Once you've sold your business, you're done."
16239	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Many entrepreneurial dynasties build family customs around the business itself, meaning a sale can emotionally upend the family.
16240	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"It's really a quagmire," said Ted Clark, executive director of the Northeastern University Center for Family Business.
16241	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"We hear all the time: I never want to sell."
16242	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Thus three years ago, the Padnoses began talking to the managers about taking on more responsibility and perhaps one day running the company.
16243	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	"The first thing they all said was, 'OK, when?"'
16244	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	said Shelley Padnos, Mitch's sister.
16245	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	She went to a business ethics seminar two years ago and met the speaker, Michael DeWilde.
16246	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	He teaches philosophy at Grand Valley State.
16247	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	A former carpenter and labor organizer, he became known in the Grand Rapids area for a program that brought literary classics to groups that normally do not read them, including some prisoners.
16248	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	Shelley Padnos was impressed, and invited DeWilde to meet with the managers.
16249	NYT_ENG_20070223.0174.LDC2009T13	They communicated poorly with one another, often running problems through a family member, she said.
