16500	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	SCIENTIST AT WORK: JOURNEYS TO THE DISTANT FIELDS OF PRIME
16501	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	LOS ANGELES
16502	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Four hundred people packed into an auditorium at UCLA in January to listen to a public lecture on prime numbers, one of the rare occasions that the topic has drawn a standing-room-only audience.
16503	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Another 35 people watched on a video screen in a classroom next door.
16504	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Eighty people were turned away.
16505	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The speaker, Terence Tao, a professor of mathematics at the university, promised "a whirlwind tour, the equivalent to going through Paris and just seeing the Eiffel Tower and the Arc de Triomphe."
16506	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	His words were polite, unassuming and tinged with the accent of Australia, his homeland.
16507	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Even though prime numbers have been studied for 2,000 years, "There's still a lot that needs to be done," Tao said.
16508	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"And it's still a very exciting field."
16509	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	After Tao finished his one-hour talk, which was broadcast live on the Internet, several students came down to the front and asked for autographs.
16510	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Tao has drawn attention and curiosity throughout his life for his prodigious abilities.
16511	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	By age 2, he had learned to read.
16512	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	At 9, he attended college math classes.
16513	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	At 20, he finished his Ph.D.
16514	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Now 31, he has grown from prodigy to one of the world's top mathematicians, tackling an unusually broad range of problems, including ones involving prime numbers and the compression of images.
16515	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Last summer, he won a Fields Medal, often considered the Nobel Prize of mathematics, and a MacArthur Fellowship, the "genius" award that comes with $500,000 and no strings.
16516	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"He's wonderful," said Charles Fefferman of Princeton University, himself a former child prodigy and a Fields Medalist.
16517	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"He's as good as they come.
16518	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	There are a few in a generation, and he's one of the few."
16519	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Colleagues have teasingly called Tao a rock star and the Mozart of Math.
16520	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Two museums in Australia have requested his photograph for their permanent exhibits.
16521	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	And he was a finalist for the 2007 Australian of the Year award.
16522	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"You start getting famous for being famous," Tao said.
16523	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"The Paris Hilton effect."
16524	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Not that any of that has noticeably affected him.
16525	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	His campus office is adorned with a poster of "Ranma 1/2," a Japanese comic book.
16526	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	As he walks the halls of the math building, he might be wearing an Adidas sweatshirt, blue jeans and scruffy sneakers, looking much like one of his graduate students.
16527	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He said he did not know how he would spend the MacArthur money, though he mentioned the mortgage on the house that he and his wife, Laura, an engineer at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory, bought last year.
16528	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	After a childhood in Adelaide, Australia, and graduate school at Princeton, Tao has settled into sunny Southern California.
16529	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I love it a lot," he said.
16530	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	But not necessarily for what the area offers.
16531	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"It's sort of the absence of things I like," he said.
16532	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	No snow to shovel, for instance.
16533	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	A deluge of media attention following his Fields Medal last summer has slowed to a trickle, and Tao said he was happy that his fame might be fleeting so that he could again concentrate on math.
16534	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	One area of his research -- compressed sensing -- could have real-world use.
16535	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Digital cameras use millions of sensors to record an image, and then a computer chip in the compresses the data.
16536	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"Compressed sensing is a different strategy," Tao said.
16537	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"You also compress the data, but you try to do it in a very dumb way, one that doesn't require much computer power at the sensor end."
16538	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16539	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	With Emmanuel Candes, a professor of applied and computational mathematics at the California Institute of Technology, Tao showed that even if most of the information were immediately discarded, the use of powerful algorithms could still reconstruct the original image.
16540	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	By useful coincidence, Tao's son, William, and Candes' son attended the same preschool, so dropping off their children turned into useful work time.
16541	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"We'd meet each other every morning at preschool," Tao said, "and we'd catch up on what we had done."
16542	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The military is interested in using the work for reconnaissance: blanket a battlefield with simple, cheap cameras that might each record a single pixel of data.
16543	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Each camera would transmit the data to a central computer that, using the mathematical technique developed by Tao and Candes, would construct a comprehensive view.
16544	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Engineers at Rice University have made a prototype of just such a camera.
16545	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16546	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Tao's best known mathematical work involves prime numbers -- positive whole numbers that can be divided evenly only by themselves and 1.
16547	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The first few prime numbers are 2, 3, 5, 7, 11 and 13 (1 is excluded).
16548	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	As numbers get larger, prime numbers become sparser, but the Greek mathematician Euclid proved sometime around 300 B.C. that there is nonetheless an infinite number of primes.
16549	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Many questions about prime numbers continue to elude answers.
16550	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Euclid also believed that there was an infinite number of "twin primes" -- pairs of prime numbers separated by 2, like 3 and 5 or 11 and 13 -- but he was unable to prove his conjecture.
16551	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Nor has anyone else in the succeeding 2,300 years.
16552	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	A larger unknown question is whether hidden patterns exist in the sequence of prime numbers or whether they appear randomly.
16553	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	In 2004, Tao, along with Ben Green, a mathematician now at the University of Cambridge in England, solved a problem related to the Twin Prime Conjecture by looking at prime number progressions -- series of numbers equally spaced.
16554	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(For example, 3, 7 and 11 constitute a progression of prime numbers with a spacing of 4
16555	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	the next number in the sequence, 15, is not prime.)
16556	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Tao and Green proved that it is always possible to find, somewhere in the infinity of integers, a progression of prime numbers of any spacing and any length.
16557	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"Terry has a style that very few have," Fefferman said.
16558	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"When he solves the problem, you think to yourself, 'This is so obvious and why didn't I see it?
16559	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Why didn't the 100 distinguished people who thought about this before not think of it?"'
16560	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Tao's proficiency with numbers appeared at a very young age.
16561	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I always liked numbers," he said.
16562	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	A 2-year-old Terry Tao used toy blocks to show older children how to count.
16563	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He was quick with language and used the blocks to spell words like "dog" and "cat."
16564	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"He probably was quietly learning these things from watching 'Sesame Street,"' said his father, Billy Tao, a pediatrician who immigrated to Australia from Hong Kong in 1972.
16565	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"We basically used 'Sesame Street' as a babysitter."
16566	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The blocks had been bought as toys, not learning tools.
16567	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"You expect them to throw them around," said Billy Tao.
16568	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Terry's parents placed him in a private school when he was 3 1/2.
16569	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	They pulled him out six weeks later because he was not ready to spend that much time in a classroom, and the teacher was not ready to teach someone like him.
16570	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	At age 5, he was enrolled in a public school, and his parents, administrators and teachers set up an individualized program for him.
16571	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He proceeded through each subject at his own pace, quickly accelerating through several grades in math and science while remaining closer to his age group in other subjects.
16572	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	In English classes, for instance, he became flustered when he had to write essays.
16573	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I never really got the hang of that," he said.
16574	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"These very vague, undefined questions.
16575	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	I always liked situations where there were very clear rules of what to do."
16576	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Assigned to write a story about what was going on at home, Terry went from room to room and made detailed lists of the contents.
16577	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	When he was 7 1/2, he began attending math classes at the local high school.
16578	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16579	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Billy Tao knew the trajectories of child prodigies like Jay Luo, who graduated with a mathematics degree from Boise State University in 1982 at the age of 12, but who has since vanished from the world of mathematics.
16580	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I initially thought Terry would be just like one of them, to graduate as early as possible," he said.
16581	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	But after talking to experts on education for gifted children, he changed his mind.
16582	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"To get a degree at a young age, to be a record-breaker, means nothing," he said.
16583	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I had a pyramid model of knowledge, that is, a very broad base and then the pyramid can go higher.
16584	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	If you just very quickly move up like a column, then you're more likely to wobble at the top and then collapse."
16585	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16586	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Billy Tao also arranged for math professors to mentor Terry.
16587	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	A couple of years later, Terry was taking university-level math and physics classes.
16588	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He excelled in international math competitions.
16589	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	His parents decided not to push him into college full time, so he split his time between high school and Flinders University, the local university in Adelaide.
16590	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He finally enrolled as a full-time college student at Flinders when he was 14, two years after he would have graduated had his parents pushed him only according to his academic abilities.
16591	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16592	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The Taos had different challenges in raising their other two sons, although all three excelled in math.
16593	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Trevor, two years younger than Terry, is autistic with top-level chess skills and the musical savant gift to play back on the piano a musical piece -- even one played by an entire orchestra -- after hearing it just once.
16594	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He completed a Ph.D. in mathematics and now works for the Defense Science and Technology Organization in Australia.
16595	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	The youngest, Nigel, told his father that he was "not another Terry," and his parents let him learn at a less accelerated pace.
16596	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Nigel, with degrees in economics, math and computer science, now works as a computer engineer for Google Australia.
16597	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"All along, we tend to emphasize the joy of learning," Billy Tao said.
16598	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"The fun is doing something, not winning something."
16599	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	(END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
16600	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Terry completed his undergraduate degree in two years, earned a master's degree a year after that, then moved to Princeton for his doctoral studies.
16601	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	While he said he never felt out of place in a class of much older students, Princeton was where he finally felt he fit among a group of peers.
16602	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	He was still younger, but was not necessarily the brightest student all the time.
16603	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	His attitude toward math also matured.
16604	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Until then, math had been competitions, problem sets, exams.
16605	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"That's more like a sprint," he said.
16606	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	Tao recalled that as a child, "I remember having this vague idea that what mathematicians did was that, some authority, someone gave them problems to solve and they just sort of solved them."
16607	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	In the real academic world, "Math research is more like a marathon," he said.
16608	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	As a parent and a professor, Tao now has to think about how to teach math in addition to learning it.
16609	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	An evening snack provided him an opportunity to question his son, who is 4.
16610	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	If there are 10 cookies, how many does each of the five people in the living room get?
16611	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	William asked his father to tell him.
16612	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"I don't know how many," Tao replied.
16613	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	"You tell me."
16614	NYT_ENG_20070312.0107.LDC2009T13	With a little more prodding, William divided the cookies into five stacks of two each.
