16623	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	KIDCENTRIC BUSINESSES BUSTING OUT ALL OVER
16624	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	She was a one-woman sales force, and her store was a diaper bag, from which she sold BabyLegs anywhere moms congregated: playgrounds, coffee shops, consignment stores.
16625	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	"If they like something, they'll tell all the other moms about it," Donnelly said.
16626	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	"Women are social, and that has really benefited our business."
16627	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	Before long, Donnelly had a factory supplier in China and moved from the kitchen of her two-bedroom apartment into a 3,500 -square-foot office and warehouse in South Seattle.
16628	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	Now babies and children all around the world sport BabyLegs
16629	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	Donnelly sells several thousand $12 pairs every day.
16630	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	The inspirations for "mamapreneurs" like Donnelly to start a business are many, but often they see an unmet need and fill it.
16631	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	In Seattle, newish moms are behind the hip baby-gear store, Tottini, in South Lake Union, as well as the local online resource, Red Tricycle, and the organic baby food delivery service, Sprouts.
16632	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	While many a new mom struggles to meet all of the demands in her life and feels that some days a mere shower is a luxury, another breed decides that, between feedings, changings and naps, it's time to start a business.
16633	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	So they become a mamapreneur, blending parenthood with entrepreneurship, usually by creating a baby- or child-centric business or product.
16634	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	The phenomenon is exploding all over the country, coinciding with a demand for stylish children's gear and a wave of older first-time parents who have more disposable income to spend on their kids.
16635	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	Many a mamapreneur has never owned or run a business before, but applies her former job skills while learning the rest on the job.
16636	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	They often rely on word of mouth through the mama grapevine to get exposure.
16637	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	No one knows the number of mamapreneurs out there, but one-woman businesses -- which many moms fall into -- grew at twice the rate of all other businesses between 1997 and 2004, according to the Center for Women's Business Research.
16638	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	Victoria Colligan says that about half of the 30,000 subscribers to Ladies Who Launch, an online network for entrepreneurs that she co-founded, are mothers with young children.
16639	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	"We see a lot of women realizing when they have a baby that they don't want the corporate lifestyle they had previously, yet they want to be inspired and make money and do something," said Colligan, who has two young children.
16640	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	"A lot of businesses are born during naptime."
16641	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	She said the No. 1 reason women start businesses is for flexibility and control, followed by passion and money.
16642	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	But they tend to launch differently from men, she added, starting lower-risk businesses with small amounts of capital and lighter overhead.
16643	NYT_ENG_20070322.0185.LDC2009T13	That was true for Donnelly, who incorporated in the summer of 2005 with $8,000 borrowed from her mother and relatives.
