16835	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	KING PORTRAIT PROPOSAL DIES IN COMMITTEE
16836	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	Cox News Service
16837	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	ATLANTA -- A proposal to hang a portrait of Coretta Scott King in the state Capitol died in a legislative committee Wednesday, prompting a racially charged rebuke from the measure's sponsor.
16838	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	House Special Rules Committee members said they rejected the measure because they believe King has already been sufficiently recognized and the Capitol should be reserved for Georgia lawmakers.
16839	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	Rep. Roberta Abdul-Salaam (D-Riverdale), who sponsored the resolution, lashed out at the committee, saying its action was worse than radio shock jock Don Imus calling the Rutgers University women's basketball team "nappy-headed hos."
16840	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"It is just like calling Mrs. King a nappy-headed (N-word)," Abdul-Salaam told reporters after the committee rejected House Resolution 376, killing it for this legislative session.
16841	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"There is already talk about boycotting in this country.
16842	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	We just need to really expand it to Georgia, if necessary," she said.
16843	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"It is absolutely time to realize that you cannot continue to conduct yourselves in such a manner and think that there will be no repercussions."
16844	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	Committee chairman Calvin Hill (R-Canton) said race had nothing to do with his panel's decision, calling King a "wonderful humanitarian."
16845	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"It is an emotional overreaction," Hill said of Abdul-Salaam's comments.
16846	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"She may be under the misunderstanding that this is a museum at the Capitol.
16847	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	It is not a museum."
16848	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	After Abdul-Salaam presented her proposal to the committee, Rep. Doug Holt (R-Social Circle) motioned for the panel to pass the resolution.
16849	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	But no one on the three-member committee seconded the motion, so the resolution died.
16850	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"I think that Coretta Scott King has been remembered sufficiently..." committee member Mike Keown (R-Coolidge) said in an interview after the meeting.
16851	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	"I think the King Center is going to stand forever.
16852	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	And it will always be a monument to the legacy of the Kings.
16853	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	And, respectfully, I think that more than anything, Coretta Scott King is going to be remembered as the wife of Martin Luther King Jr."
16854	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	King died last year after battling ovarian cancer and the effects of a stroke.
16855	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	Abdul-Salaam's resolution calls her a hero and cites her "tireless work on behalf of a free and equal society."
16856	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	The resolution urges the Capitol Arts Standards Commission to authorize hanging a portrait of Coretta Scott King on the second floor of the State Capitol next to a picture of her late husband, Martin Luther King Jr.
16857	NYT_ENG_20070411.0190.LDC2009T13	The Legislature created the commission last year to set standards for new artwork in the Capitol.
