16878	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	BANKER GATHERS HIS DEFENDERS, BUT THERE AREN'T MANY
16879	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	WASHINGTON
16880	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Paul D. Wolfowitz, the embattled president of the World Bank, worked behind the scenes on Friday to gain the support of finance and development ministers from around the world, but there were few endorsements of his leadership outside the Bush administration.
16881	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	"We must just allow the process to work through," said Trevor Manuel, the finance minister of South Africa, referring to the bank board's announcement on Friday that it would continue to weigh Wolfowitz's role in the transfer and pay raise of his companion after he became president of the bank in 2005.
16882	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Manuel also said the bank must avoid a rush to judgment.
16883	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	But Manuel is close to Wolfowitz, and the failure to praise him was significant.
16884	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Wolfowitz visited South Africa this year and has called Manuel one of Africa's most talented leaders.
16885	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	In Paris, a Foreign Ministry spokesman was similarly tepid and noncommittal, noting that the bank's board had a process under way.
16886	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	He said France would make its own views known when appropriate.
16887	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Throughout the day, Bush administration officials praised Wolfowitz's leadership, but at an evening news conference, Treasury Secretary Henry M. Paulson Jr. said that because the bank board was still considering the matter, he would not comment on what he thought the outcome should be.
16888	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	"This should not be read as any lessening of the United States' support for Paul Wolfowitz," he said.
16889	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Asked specifically if he would call for Wolfowitz to remain as head of the World Bank, he responded, "I said what I said."
16890	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	The disclosure on Thursday of Wolfowitz's involvement in the raise given to his companion, Shaha Ali Riza, has stirred a furor within the bank and prompted demands from its staff association that he step down.
16891	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Board members are said to be considering whether to reprimand him or encourage him to resign.
16892	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Bank officials familiar with the thinking of some of the 24 members of the board, who represent countries or groups of countries, said they were uncertain how to proceed and would be consulting this weekend with finance ministers here for meetings of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
16893	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	The bank leadership was also looking for a signal from the United States, including an indication as to whether President Bush would insist that Wolfowitz had done nothing wrong, or whether some in the administration might encourage him to resign from an institution that is in a virtual uprising against his leadership.
16894	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	"He could decide that his relationship with the staff and the board is so soured that he doesn't have the trust he needs to go forward," one administration official said, adding that he saw no evidence the White House was pushing for that.
16895	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Early Friday morning, after meeting the previous evening, the bank's board released a sheaf of documents about Wolfowitz's decision to direct the bank's vice president for human resources to reassign Riza to the State Department with a promotion, a raise and guarantees of future raises and promotions.
16896	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	The staff association has charged that several of Wolfowitz's actions violated normal bank rules.
16897	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	The board issued a statement saying that Wolfowitz did not involve the ethics and legal counsel in many of the decisions relating to the transfer, contrary to earlier suggestions by Wolfowitz.
16898	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	But it did not conclude that he had deliberately flouted the rules.
16899	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	The 7,000 employees of the World Bank in Washington have been exchanging e-mail messages and comments, many of them critical of Wolfowitz but some expressing sympathy with his situation and his dealings with Riza, who had been a bank officer for seven years when he became president in 2005.
16900	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Supporters and critics of Wolfowitz seized on the documents as evidence for the two different points of view.
16901	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	On one hand, the documents made it clear that Wolfowitz was very much involved in the decision to give Riza a raise to more than $190,000 a year, with the aim of compensating her for the disruption of the transfer, but critics said he violated his own preaching to the bank about the need for transparency and integrity.
16902	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	On the other hand, Wolfowitz's defenders noted that the documents showed he had tried to recuse himself from involvement in personnel decisions affecting Riza when he arrived at the bank, and reluctantly became involved in her transfer only after the head of ethics for the board directed him to do so.
16903	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	Wolfowitz remained out of public view on Friday, as did Riza, a British citizen who was born in Libya.
16904	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	But the board's documents provided a glimpse into the emotions of both as they struggled to reconcile their professional and personal lives.
16905	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	In his first month at the bank, Wolfowitz appeared from the documents to have been almost preoccupied by the matter.
16906	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	He had at first tried to allow Riza to stay at the bank and even to deal with her professionally there, with the promise to recuse himself if conflicts arose.
16907	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	That wish was denied by the ethics staff.
16908	NYT_ENG_20070413.0234.LDC2009T13	With some irritation, Wolfowitz wrote a note in August 2005 saying the ethics committee had "explicitly directed me to resolve the matter by providing instruction" to a vice president for human resources.
