17018	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	WEATHER
17019	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Showers and thunderstorms will erupt on the Plains once again as a slow-moving disturbance draws humid air north from the Gulf of Mexico.
17020	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Some of the storms will be severe, producing damaging winds and large hail.
17021	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Winds shifting direction and speed with altitude will also create conditions favorable for tornadoes.
17022	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	The area at highest risk for severe weather will be from north- central Texas to central and eastern Kansas.
17023	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	A sprawling zone of high pressure will promote sunshine and cool weather from the Great Lakes to New England.
17024	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Farther south, low pressure forming east of Virginia will generate chilly, wind- driven showers along parts of the Middle Atlantic Coast.
17025	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Scattered lowland showers and mountain snow will persist in the Rockies.
17026	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	California will turn much warmer, with locally gusty winds.
17027	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	FOCUS: SLOW STORMS
17028	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	Spring is the season of slow storms.
17029	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	In spring, the jet stream vacillates, retreating north as warmer air arrives from the tropics, and surging south as the last chilly air masses empty from the arctic.
17030	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	As a flooded river leaves pools of standing water after it recedes, the jet stream often leaves behind stagnant pools of cold air when it retreats north.
17031	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	These high- level cold pools favor the formation of storms.
17032	NYT_ENG_20070505.0102.LDC2009T13	This weekend a slow storm in the Central states will bring more severe storms to the Plains while a slow storm in the East causes unsettled weather near the Southeast and Middle Atlantic coasts this week.
17033	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	AVETT-BROTHERS-0507-COX
17034	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Cox News Service
17035	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	ATLANTA -- Scott Avett grew up in blue-collar North Carolina and lives there to this day, in the Piedmont, on 65 acres.
17036	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	His place is above a wood shop.
17037	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"It's NASCAR country," he says.
17038	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"It's much like 'Talladega Nights."'
17039	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Scott is 30 years old.
17040	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	His father owned a welding company.
17041	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	His mother taught reading.
17042	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He grew up listening to John Denver and Merle Haggard on eight-track tape.
17043	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Now he plays and sings in a twangy trio that bears his name - the Avett Brothers, a band that exploits the tensions between the rustic Old South and the cosmopolitan New South, between rootsy bluegrass and rowdy punk rock, between reverence and irreverence.
17044	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The Avett Brothers obviously respect country music
17045	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	when they deconstruct the form, it's as though they're sacrificing a loved one in the name of art - sort of like Jimi Hendrix igniting his guitar.
17046	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Thanks in part to their background in a rock band, the brothers attack their instruments with destructive intensity - they once broke 32 strings in a single gig.
17047	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"Sometimes," says Paul Lohr, the band's booking agent, "you have to throw caution to the wind and risk some sour notes and some out of tune strings or some completely broken strings to get those moments of brilliance."
17048	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	And yet, the Avetts can be tender.
17049	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They write smart, funny, heartbreaking country-tinged songs that tell shaggy dog stories and reveal surprisingly vulnerable feelings.
17050	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	On May 15, they will release a new album called "Emotionalism."
17051	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The band's duality is embodied in Seth Avett, Scott's younger sibling.
17052	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Seth is 26 and tall as summertime corn.
17053	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He likes to wear a pendant that he made himself, a sculpture of a human skull with music notes for teeth.
17054	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Seth plays guitar and sings, sometimes rather loudly.
17055	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He has had to explain to Mother Avett that screaming isn't necessarily a bad thing.
17056	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Some emotions just can't be explained in words.
17057	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Seth and his bandmates travel from gig to gig in a green Ford van decorated with both a Jesus fish and a sticker for the metal band Danzig, which once released an album called "6:66 Satan's Child."
17058	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"You gotta be well-rounded," Seth deadpans.
17059	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"There's some good things to get from Danzig, and some good things to get from the fish as well."
17060	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	And then there's Bob Crawford.
17061	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Bob is not an Avett brother, but he is an Avett Brother.
17062	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Bob is 35.
17063	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He plays upright bass.
17064	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He has read biographies of every president through Van Buren.
17065	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He's a Yankee.
17066	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He didn't discover bluegrass until a college buddy dragged him to a festival in Delaware.
17067	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The next day he volunteered for the 6 a.m. shift on his college radio station, playing Appalachian roots music for the good people of New Jersey.
17068	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"People come out to see live music down here," he says one recent night, backstage at Atlanta's Variety Playhouse.
17069	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"And they never did where I was from in South Jersey."
17070	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Getting to the roots
17071	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	In concert and on record, the Avett Brothers make music that simultaneously upholds and demolishes the Americana tradition.
17072	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The Avett Brothers play acoustically, harmonize sweetly and shriek savagely.
17073	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Their music also has an urban knowingness despite their rural roots.
17074	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The two collide in a primal ballad called "Murdered in the City."
17075	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"Growing up in the country," Scott says, "it's been hard to adjust to the amount of time we spend in cities."
17076	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	If the band has a leader, it's Scott.
17077	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	In concert, he stands at center stage.
17078	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	In conversation, he's thoughtfully chatty.
17079	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He's comfortable holding forth on, say, the Philadelphia painter Thomas Eakins.
17080	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	And he describes his own development with a kind of modest nonchalance.
17081	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	His last day job was doing janitorial work.
17082	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"It's the kind of stuff," he says, "where you're looking in the toilet at your reflection, wondering what it's all about."
17083	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	After spending his younger days obsessed with grunge bands like Soundgarden and Nirvana, Scott became curious about bluegrass about a decade ago.
17084	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"Before that," he says, "nobody was going to pry me away from anything that wasn't sharp as a knife."
17085	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He picked up the banjo to distinguish himself in a world full of guitarists.
17086	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	He learned standards including "Foggy Mountain Breakdown" and "Boil Them Cabbage" but says that he started crafting his own songs as soon as he could play chords.
17087	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	About five years after Scott started taking lessons, he began giving them.
17088	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	When Scott and Seth discovered that their angsty rock band, Nemo, had - as Scott puts it - "imploded upon itself," they turned to roots music and began focusing on the Avett Brothers.
17089	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Catharsis onstage
17090	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The band does not fit comfortably into any mainstream genre, or even into any established subgenre.
17091	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They're a little too hippie- ish for alternative country yet way too scruffy for mainstream country.
17092	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They exist alongside a handful of other Americana misfits, namely the shape-shifting songwriter Will Oldham and the tight string band Old Crow Medicine Show.
17093	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	In their own ways, all three of these groups are warping the traditional sound and shape of country music.
17094	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	"My favorite comparison to them," says agent Lohr, "is the Violent Femmes crossed with Bob Dylan.
17095	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Because they have that wild, unbridled stage presence.
17096	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Plus, Dylan is obviously one of the greatest songwriters of all time."
17097	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The Avett Brothers are most powerful onstage, which is where they spent about 180 nights last year.
17098	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They stand three across - Bob on the left, Seth on the right and Scott in the middle.
17099	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They dress up for shows by wearing jackets or ties, adding another layer of incongruity.
17100	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The formal clothes clash with the unhinged music.
17101	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	They can also make the band members hot.
17102	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	At a recent show in Athens' Georgia Theatre, sweat flew off Scott's head in a rainy sheet.
17103	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Avett concerts showcase the band's panoramic range.
17104	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Song forms are all over the place - ballads, rockers, folk tunes, instrumentals.
17105	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	All three members sing.
17106	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The audience sometimes joins them.
17107	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	Scott and Seth both play percussion instruments with their feet, and Bob likes to twirl his bass as though it were a dance partner.
17108	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	To see an Avett Brothers concert is to witness an emotional and physical catharsis.
17109	NYT_ENG_20070505.0116.LDC2009T13	The effects become apparent backstage.
