17355	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	RADIOLOGY WAS YOUNG, AND SO WAS I: A REMINISCENCE
17356	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Some people are born with silver spoons in their mouths.
17357	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	I grew up in a lead cocoon.
17358	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father, Dr. William S. Altman, known as Sol, was a radiologist, and his office and its X-ray machines occupied the first floor of our house in Quincy, Mass.
17359	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	To protect his staff members, his patients and our family from scatter radiation, he lined many walls, floors and doors with lead sheets.
17360	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	We learned to open and close those heavy doors carefully to avoid jamming a finger.
17361	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Whether for convenience or frugality, many doctors, even in a technically oriented field like radiology, practiced in a home office until shortly after World War II.
17362	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	As I turn 70 today, I am reminded of this piece of Americana that has largely disappeared.
17363	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Into the 1970s, X-rays helped detect many diseases, but changed the course of few.
17364	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiology has made major advances since Wilhelm K. Roentgen discovered X-rays in 1895 in Germany, providing the first opportunity to see inside a body without opening it up.
17365	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	CT scans take radiographic slices of the body in details Roentgen could not have imagined.
17366	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Interventional radiologists perform surgery guided by X-ray images to stop bleeding from the intestines, prevent some strokes and treat other problems.
17367	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Use of radium furthered development of other radioactive isotopes that produce images to detect thyroid and other glandular abnormalities.
17368	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	These and other imaging techniques not based on radiation, like ultrasound and magnetic resonance imaging, now spare many patients exploratory operations and improve the precision of surgery.
17369	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father was a man of enormous patience and a wonderful sense of humor who liked dealing with people.
17370	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	All of that contributed to an excellent bedside manner.
17371	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In the early 1930s, after a year in general medicine, he became one of the first trained radiologists in this country.
17372	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He changed fields in part because of a love of tinkering that he learned from his own father, who was an electrician.
17373	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Fully respecting the hazards of radiation, he always wore cumbersome but protective lead aprons and gloves while working, unlike some colleagues, who later succumbed to leukemia and other blood ailments.
17374	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He lived to 83
17375	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	those who died younger included general practitioners who took X-rays in their offices.
17376	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father, like many radiologists, split the day between home and hospital offices.
17377	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Occasionally he wrote scientific articles and reviews.
17378	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Twice a week he volunteered to teach at Tufts University, where he and I attended medical school, and to join colleagues who shared X-rays of their most perplexing or interesting cases.
17379	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Routine use of X-rays caught on slowly in this country.
17380	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In important ways, U.S. radiology was a specialty imported from Germany.
17381	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In bringing their expertise and equipment, German and Austrian refugee radiologists made Boston an early national leader in the field.
17382	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The name of one, Dr. Richard Schatzki, is now attached to a circular narrowing of the esophagus -- a Schatzki ring -- that causes food to stick in the gullet of many patients.
17383	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In time, American leaders emerged, and they joined the conferences when visiting Boston.
17384	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	One, Dr. Henry S. Kaplan, cured a case of Hodgkin's disease with radiation at Stanford, and I studied with him there as a visiting medical student.
17385	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiologists were said to work regular hours, but that was a myth.
17386	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Often a middle-of-the-night call from the hospital would summon my father to look at the X-rays of accident victims and patients needing emergency surgery.
17387	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He considered the trips a normal part of his job.
17388	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	While emergency X-rays were performed at the local hospital, office practices handled elective cases.
17389	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Some patients rang the office bell because they wanted an X-ray and expected it on demand, even in the middle of the night.
17390	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father explained calmly that radiologists never accepted a patient without a doctor's referral.
17391	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The office telephone also rang in our living quarters because doctors and patients called at all hours to make appointments.
17392	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My mother (Esther), my sister (Dorothy) or I would record an agreed- upon time in the appointment book and pass on to the patient instructions like not eating or drinking from midnight before the day of the requested procedure.
17393	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiologists sometimes made house calls, usually for patients bedridden with a fractured hip.
17394	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Dad's "black bag" was a portable X-ray machine the size of a large suitcase and heavy.
17395	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Use of portable X-rays was limited, because the radiation exposure time was long and the quality of the films seldom matched those taken in an office.
17396	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The first-floor waiting room was paneled in knotty pine.
17397	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Magazines were piled on stands next to the chairs.
17398	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	To preserve the quiet atmosphere, my father would not let me take up the trumpet or drums.
17399	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	(He encouraged me to take piano and clarinet lessons, but the sour notes I produced upstairs could not have sounded any better.)
17400	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Two rooms were for diagnostic X-rays, mostly of bones, lungs, kidneys and bowels.
17401	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Mammograms were rarely performed in those days.
17402	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Fluoroscopy -- the use of X-rays and a fluorescent screen to produce images of the body's internal structures, such as the stomach and intestines -- was a standard procedure, performed in the dark.
17403	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	To see better, fluoroscopists wore red goggles
17404	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	because it took time to adapt vision from light to dark, they would often wear them for about a half-hour beforehand.
17405	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	When my father went from the home office to the hospital to do fluoroscopies, my mother often drove him.
17406	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
17407	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Dad also performed special procedures.
17408	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The one he hated most was a pneumoencephalogram, in which he had to insert a needle in a patient's lower back, remove spinal fluid and inject air.
17409	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	That procedure could outline the ventricles in the brain on X-rays.
17410	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	But the patient invariably suffered an excruciating headache, and only the rare patient would agree to any additional test.
17411	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Now the accuracy of CT and MRI scans have made pneumoencephalograms a relic of the past, as they have a number of other once-routine procedures.
17412	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	A third room was for a different form of X-ray -- radiation therapy.
17413	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Sometimes it was curative.
17414	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	But mostly it provided symptomatic relief and palliation, particularly in cancer, making radiologists known as "the cancer doctors."
17415	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Before the introduction of steroid drugs, a small blast or two of radiation often was given for a few benign conditions.
17416	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	One was bursitis in the shoulder
17417	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	radiation quickly relieved the pain and, with exercises, allowed restoration of full shoulder motion.
17418	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Now radiation is rarely given for noncancerous ailments.
17419	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Dad also used radium to treat cancers, mostly those of the cervix and uterus.
17420	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He stored the radium in a lead-lined case in a safe in the cellar.
17421	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Today, we would call such treatments palliative, though they were not regarded that way in an era when most cancers were detected in their late stages.
17422	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In my youth, chemotherapy was in its infancy, and people spoke about cancer in euphemisms.
17423	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In something rarely seen today, many patients arrived with cancers that were so advanced they formed festering ulcers.
17424	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Maggots even grew in a few such cancers.
17425	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	X-ray films were developed in a darkened room with the type of chemical solutions used for camera film.
17426	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	A technician mixed fresh solutions daily, and they stank.
17427	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiologists would give a preliminary "wet reading" after looking at the X-rays before they dried.
17428	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The digital age has eliminated those steps by making X-ray film obsolete.
17429	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	One convenience of a home office was that my father could go upstairs to nap.
17430	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The bathroom doubled as a library, with stacks of the latest scientific journals.
17431	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	After dinner with the family, Dad went down to the office, stood before a viewing box, examined each patient's dry X-ray films and dictated reports far into the night.
17432	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	I do not remember how old I was when I first joined him and peered over a shoulder at the films.
17433	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	But I have vivid memories of a number of patients who had large areas in their lung X-rays that appeared white, instead of the normal black, from silicosis -- a serious disease that many workers acquired in the local granite quarries.
17434	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	In such cases, my father taught me to take a closer look because silicosis increased the risk of tuberculosis.
17435	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	To the untrained eye, X-rays were mostly uninterpretable shadows.
17436	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiologists learn to look at them in a disciplined, systematic way.
17437	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	For example, they scan the chest X-rays that were taken at various angles.
17438	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Then they look at the lungs, heart and ribs in detail.
17439	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	"The more experienced eye can take in a complex pattern of shadows and images almost at a glance and become instinctively sensitive to an abnormal contour or shadow," said Dr. Joseph T. Ferrucci Jr., the emeritus chairman of radiology at Boston University, whose radiologist father was one of my dad's colleagues.
17440	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Radiologists and other medical specialists have a different perspective on patients and their diseases.
17441	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	As one aphorism puts it: A physician sees a patient at the bedside and imagines the disease.
17442	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	A radiologist sees the disease on the film and imagines the patient.
17443	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	As X-ray technology improved, my father often replaced older machines with newer, larger and more powerful ones that produced better pictures.
17444	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Ultimately he had to expand the office to the point where only a rock garden was left between the front of the house and the street.
17445	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The equipment often broke down.
17446	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	When the X-ray repairmen came, my father joined them in spreading across the floor the diagrams needed to trace the complex circuitry and pinpoint the problem.
17447	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	His acumen was so sharp that Harvey Picker, whose company made X-ray machines, came along.
17448	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	I did not inherit those interests.
17449	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father was curious about the causes of the medical problems he saw and sought ways to prevent them.
17450	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He drew out epidemiologic information by talking with patients.
17451	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	For example, he asked victims of automobile accidents about the model and color of the cars involved.
17452	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Because so many victims said the color was dark, he bought only light-colored cars (much easier to see at night) and advised others to do likewise.
17453	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Other conversations and observations convinced him, long before the 1964 surgeon general's report, that cigarette smoking caused lung cancer.
17454	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	No one in our household smoked, though relatives who did died from ailments related to smoking.
17455	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	My father was puzzled by why so many workers at the Fore River shipyard in Quincy developed mesotheliomas and other cancers.
17456	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	He tried to persuade the owners to find out why.
17457	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Doctors later determined that many were from asbestos.
17458	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Those anecdotes and studies kindled my interest in epidemiology.
17459	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Dad and other radiologists would be irked when referring doctors failed to communicate the specific symptoms and physical findings that led them to order a patient's X-rays.
17460	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	Such details help radiologists know what to look for.
17461	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	The lack of precise information is still is a common problem between radiologists and referring doctors.
17462	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	And that is a symptom of a much larger problem: lapses in communication among medical professionals and the public.
17463	NYT_ENG_20070618.0190.LDC2009T13	It was partly to remedy such lapses, and partly to inform the public about medicine and its advances, that I chose the specialty I have pursued for four decades: medical journalism.
17464	NYT_ENG_20070619.0208.LDC2009T13	PURSUIT OF QAIDA FIGHTERS BEGINS BY BLOCKING ESCAPE
