17487	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	If the ancestral pulp of Mel Gibson's "Apocalypto" seemed too loud, too bloody, or too long, the simple magic-realism of "Ten Canoes" might be preferable.
17488	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Set among the predominantly nude Yolngu people of northern Australia, the film is about the act of storytelling, and how we expect to be gratified or entertained by it.
17489	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Played by the veteran Aborigine actor David Gulpilil, who was the star of Nicolas Roeg's "Walkabout" and Philip Noyce's "Rabbit- Proof Fence," an unseen Storyteller draws us back a thousand years to his ancestors, a group of Yolngu men stripping trees of their bark to build canoes for the swamp-bound goose-egg-hunting season.
17490	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	One of the men, a goose-egg rookie named Dayindi (Jamie Gulpilil, David's son), fancies the third and youngest of the three women married to his much older brother, Minygululu (Peter Minygululu).
17491	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	This is a no-no, which requires a tale meant to teach the kid a lesson.
17492	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	For us, it means a trip back even further to hear what happened the last time a Yolngu man coveted his brother's missus.
17493	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Things are more complicated than that.
17494	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	One man does lust after his brother's youngest wife.
17495	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	But there's also a mysterious stranger who drops in on the tribe (the men deem him a weirdo because he covers his procreative parts with a cloth), and the brother's second wife disappears, sparking a low-key manhunt and speculation that the stranger nabbed her.
17496	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Duties for telling this fable fall to our Storyteller and Minygululu, whose portion of the film has been shot in black and white.
17497	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	This strategy means the story is being told by two men with an almost jokey indifference to pacing, and so the tale of the stranger and the missing wife starts and stops and begins again, interrupted by the black-and-white scenes of the hunters building their canoes.
17498	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	This should be far more frustrating than it is, although as a filmmaking conceit it's frustrating enough.
17499	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Yet the codirectors - the Dutch-Australian veteran Rolf de Heer and Peter Djigirr, an Aborigine whose background is in traditional crafts rather than film - go at this movie with a naturalist serenity that's too playful to be completely vexing.
17500	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	It's handsome-looking, too.
17501	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	When we're not following the story (because the film has taken a break from telling it), we're following the camera as it glides through the sunny swampland and dotes on the full, contemplative faces of the actors.
17502	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	The movie also merrily insists that things were extremely formal a thousand years ago.
17503	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Who knew that silent-but-deadly was a genre of flatulence even back then?
17504	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	But maybe "Ten Canoes" plays too much.
17505	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	It's a thriller that refuses to thrill.
17506	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	It taunts us with resolution and mysteries, then slaps our hand for reaching out for a conclusion.
17507	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	That's a natural expectation that the filmmakers are happy to subvert.
17508	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	Wesley Morris can be reached at wmorris@globe.com.
17509	NYT_ENG_20070622.0083.LDC2009T13	For more on movies, go to boston.com/ae/movies/blog.
17510	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	JUST SAY NO TO RUPERT
17511	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK - I was lucky enough to find myself here Monday night at the Gerald Loeb awards, the Pulitzers of business journalism.
17512	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Too bad the Bancrofts of Boston couldn't have been here, too.
17513	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The family that has controlled The Wall Street Journal for a hundred years is on the brink of selling one of the world's great newspapers - and the most important voice in business journalism - to Rupert Murdoch.
17514	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Loebs were a timely and excellent measure of why this quiet New England family has more to lose than to gain in selling to Murdoch, a man who has grown rich and powerful by never overestimating his audience.
17515	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Journal, as usual, dominated the Loeb awards this year.
17516	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	In all the newspaper had 10 finalists
17517	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The New York Times was second with six finalists.
17518	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Journal won two Loebs, including one to the Boston-based reporters who broke the story about the wide practice of companies secretly backdating option awards to top executives.
17519	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	It was the story of the year in business, and swept awards, including the Pulitzer Prize.
17520	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Now Murdoch, at 76, wants to buy what he has not been able to build in a lifetime.
17521	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	His $5 billion bid is a rich premium for Dow Jones &amp
17522	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	amp
17523	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Co., owner of the Journal, which has made more than its share of management missteps over the years.
17524	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	But the Bancrofts need to ask themselves: Do they really want to be the generation that sells the Journal to a man whose contribution to American journalism is the New York Post and Fox News?
17525	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Because that is who they will forever be.
17526	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	And they will be poorer, not richer, for it.
17527	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Fifteen years ago the Taylor family sold this newspaper to The New York Times Co.
17528	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Frankly, I liked things the way they were.
17529	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	But if the paper had to be sold, the Taylor family understood it had a duty to find not just a buyer, but a buyer that shared its values.
17530	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Given the options, Journal editors and writers would be very happy with The New York Times or The Washington Post Co. as a buyer.
17531	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	But it is not going to happen.
17532	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Plenty of the Journal's best talent is already looking for the exits.
17533	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Bancrofts are about to make a pact with the devil.
17534	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Over the past couple of days The New York Times has spelled out in detail how Murdoch uses his media reach to promote his vast business interests, whether in Washington or in China.
17535	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Fat book contracts for congressmen.
17536	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Another one for Deng Xiaoping's daughter, and a sensitivity to the Beijing government that has made him "the Chinese leadership's favorite media baron," as the Times put it.
17537	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	When you sell your house, you have to move out.
17538	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Bancroft family and its Boston lawyer, Michael B. Elefante of Hemenway &amp
17539	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	amp
17540	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Barnes, are fashioning a sorry fig leaf of alleged editorial protection for the newspaper they are abandoning for their horse farm, or whatever.
17541	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	See the experience of Harry Evans, the editor of The Times of London, who was forced out soon after Murdoch bought that paper in 1981.
17542	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	These agreements don't work over time.
17543	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	Whether the Bancrofts or the Taylors, you forfeit your right to a say the day you take the money.
17544	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	You become just people from a rich family who used to be somebody.
17545	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	This much we know: The Journal is a great newspaper.
17546	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The chances of Murdoch improving it are much less than the chances of him compromising it.
17547	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	There were no finalists from the New York Post at the Loebs.
17548	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The builder of the Journal, Clarence Barron, got his start in Boston by reporting the financial news on State Street.
17549	NYT_ENG_20070626.0176.LDC2009T13	The Bancrofts of Boston still have time to do something really unusual, even heroic, by just telling Rupert no.
