17551	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	UTILITIES DUMP COAL PLANT
17552	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	TALLAHASSEE Under pressure from Gov. Charlie Crist, a consortium of Florida utilities pulled the plug Tuesday on another controversial coal-fired power plant because of concerns about global warming.
17553	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"It's like a new day is dawning for energy in Florida," said Susan Glickman of the Southern Alliance for Clean Energy, which opposed the plant.
17554	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Crist announced the demise of the coal plant during a news conference unveiling the agenda of his global warming summit in Miami next week, where he promised to "identify specific actions" that Florida can take to combat climate change.
17555	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"Good things are happening," Crist said.
17556	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"That pleases me, and I think it pleases our fellow Floridians."
17557	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Last month the Public Service Commission short-circuited a proposal by Florida Power &amp
17558	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	amp
17559	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Light to build a 960-megawatt coal-fired plant near Everglades National Park.
17560	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The PSC based its vote in part on concerns about the cost of cleaning up the plant's greenhouse gas emissions.
17561	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Now the four utilities involved in building the 800-megawatt Taylor Energy Center in the state's Big Bend area have dropped their plans for that coal plant as well, saying they will "assess how best to meet their customers' electricity needs in ways consistent with growing concerns about greenhouse gas emissions."
17562	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Utilities officials took that step Tuesday after repeated meetings over the past six months with one of Crist's top aides, Chris Kise, who told them about the governor's concerns regarding greenhouse gas emissions from coal-burning plants.
17563	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"It's good to encourage good behavior, and I think they've done something very positive," Crist said.
17564	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	After Crist was sworn in as governor in January, he dispatched Kise, whose title is "counsellor to the governor," to meet with FPL executives and the executive director of the consortium involved in the Taylor Energy Center.
17565	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	They talked about global warming.
17566	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"They got a sense of where the governor's leadership is on the environmental considerations," said Kise, a Miami native who served as solicitor general when Crist was attorney general.
17567	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The four utilities involved in the Taylor County plant were "very receptive to the governor's message about climate change," Kise said.
17568	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Taylor project spokesman Mark McCain said Kise didn't tell anyone what to do, but "we shared information about the project and how it compares with other options."
17569	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	As a result, he said, utilities officials realized that "climate change is becoming a major issue in Florida."
17570	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	That point was driven home by last month's decision by the PSC to reject FPL's Glades Power Park plan.
17571	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	FPL officials had announced last September that they would build the plant on about 5,000 acres of Glades County farmland owned by Tampa-based Lykes Brothers.
17572	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The location would have put the plant within 70 miles of Everglades National Park and 40 miles north of Big Cypress National Preserve.
17573	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	Crist openly questioned the plant's location, the National Park Service raised concerns about air pollution and environmental groups argued it would increase greenhouse gases at a time when the nation is trying to combat global warming.
17574	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	On June 5, PSC commissioners rejected the plant by a 4-0 vote, saying they worried that electric rates could grow much higher for the coal plant if Congress begins taxing carbon emissions as a way to reverse climate change.
17575	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The vote marked the first time global warming had ever played a role in a PSC decision, and the first time in 15 years the agency rejected a new power plant.
17576	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	So this week the four utilities Tallahassee, the Jacksonville Electric Authority, the Florida Municipal Power Agency and the Disney-based Reedy Creek Improvement District agreed to stop seeking state permits to build the Taylor Energy Center plant near Perry.
17577	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"It's more important that we work with state leaders to craft an energy plan for Florida," Taylor Energy Center project manager Mike Lawson said in a news release, noting that he looked forward to attending the governor's summit.
17578	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The announcement marked a startling turnabout for Taylor County residents who opposed the plant.
17579	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	"I'm tickled!"
17580	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	said resident Joy Towles Ezell, who frequently referred to the plant as the "Taylor Emphysema Center."
17581	NYT_ENG_20070703.0261.LDC2009T13	The Taylor plant "was a 19th century solution to a 21st century problem," said Ross Burnaman, a Tallahassee lawyer who had sued to try to stop the plant.
