18281	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	HOUSTON
18282	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	A hug on Thursday between the commanders of the space shuttle Discovery and the International Space Station marked the first time that women have served in both roles at the same time.
18283	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	Led by the shuttle commander, Pamela A. Melroy, and the station commander, Peggy A. Whitson, the crews met with shouts of greeting and hearty embraces as the two vehicles made their way around the earth at 17,000 mph, crossing over North Carolina.
18284	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	The shuttle docked with the space station at 8:40 a.m. Eastern time after it was put through a back flip to allow astronauts on the station to shoot pictures of its belly.
18285	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	Analysts on the ground study the pictures for any signs of damage from debris during liftoff.
18286	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	The back flip is a maneuver that is now part of every shuttle mission to the space station.
18287	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	It was begun after the loss of the shuttle Columbia and its crew in 2003 in an accident traced to damage by debris during the launching.
18288	NYT_ENG_20071025.0262.LDC2009T13	In an interview before the mission, Melroy, who is a retired Air Force colonel, said that performing the back flip so close to the station -- just 600 feet away -- was counterintuitive for a pilot.
