18350	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	The legislator, Yuval Steinitz, has written to all U.S. senators to encourage them to support a move begun in the House of Representatives to freeze $200 million of a projected $1.3 billion in military aid to Egypt.
18351	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Steinitz said he was asked to write the letter by senators he met as a leader, with Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., of a joint group on defense that meets twice a year.
18352	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	The House bill would freeze the $200 million until the secretary of state certified that Egypt "has taken concrete and measurable steps" to enact a law protecting the independence of the judiciary, to "curb police abuses" by providing training for police leadership and to "detect and destroy the smuggling network and smuggling tunnels that lead from Egypt to Gaza."
18353	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	The Senate version urges Egypt to do more to stop smuggling but would not halt aid.
18354	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	In his letter, Steinitz, former chairman of the Israeli Parliament's Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee and chairman of the security subcommittee, accuses Egypt of allowing Hamas to obtain 20,000 rifles, 6,000 anti-tank missiles, 100 tons of explosives, several dozen Katyusha rockets and shoulder-held anti-aircraft missiles every year.
18355	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	In the last three months, Steinitz says, Egypt has allowed "the organized departure of large groups of operatives from Gaza for military training in Iran."
18356	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	In September, he notes, 100 Gazans who had trained in Iran were allowed by Egypt to return home despite Israeli protests.
18357	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Egyptian authorities say the accusations are inaccurate and aimed at sabotaging Egyptian-U.S. relations.
18358	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	They say that they have done all they can to try to safeguard the border, but are hamstrung by the 1979 Camp David agreement, which restricts the number of soldiers they can deploy there.
18359	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"Egypt can't have a real security presence on the border," said Fouad Allam, former director of Egyptian State Security.
18360	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"Egypt tried to amend this, and Israel refused."
18361	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Steinitz's assessments track those of the Israeli military and military intelligence.
18362	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	His complaints are shared by the Israeli government.
18363	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Foreign Minister Tzipi Livni on Tuesday told her Egyptian counterpart, Ahmed Aboul Gheit, that "there is a real need for a determined effort to stop weapons smuggling into the Gaza Strip."
18364	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	But the government does not associate itself with the Steinitz letter or its call to freeze aid to Egypt, which, like Jordan, has a formal peace treaty with Israel.
18365	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	The U.S. House move was led by Reps. Gary Ackerman and Nita M. Lowey, both D-N.Y., who are strong supporters of Israel.
18366	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Ackerman is chairman of the subcommittee on the Middle East and Asia
18367	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Lowey is chairwoman of the state and foreign operations subcommittee of the Appropriations Committee.
18368	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Ackerman told the newspaper Haaretz that Egypt had been allowing between $12 million and $20 million a month in cash to flow to Hamas, and said smuggling had worsened.
18369	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"Egypt is not helping as much as it can," he said.
18370	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Egypt has sent senior officials and military officers to Washington to argue against the freeze and to describe their efforts to stop the smuggling.
18371	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	In a document given to legislators, Egypt suggested that some Israeli soldiers were helping smugglers.
18372	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	The Bush administration opposes withholding aid.
18373	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
18374	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	A Senate foreign-policy aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the delicate nature of negotiations in Congress, said the Senate seemed unlikely to back withholding aid because it does not wish to signal a weakening of support when Egypt has a crucial role in the Middle East peace effort.
18375	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	But the aide said the issue would have to be resolved in a conference committee.
18376	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	On Wednesday, Egypt said that it had uncovered another six smuggling tunnels and destroyed them
18377	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	it announced the destruction of others on the eve of U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice's last trip there.
18378	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Months ago, just after Hamas took control of Gaza, men in the border town of Rafah who had identified themselves as smugglers said that when smugglers were caught ferrying goods or weapons into Gaza, they were treated more leniently by judges who were sympathetic to the Palestinian cause.
18379	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	They also said that security guards at the border could be persuaded to look the other way for money.
18380	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Overall, Egypt's relationship with Hamas is complicated by domestic political concerns.
18381	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	On one hand, analysts said, it is not in Egypt's interest to improve relations with Hamas, an offshoot of the banned Muslim Brotherhood.
18382	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	On the other, Egypt does not want to be seen to be helping Israel over the Palestinians.
18383	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"I do not think that Egypt is re-examining its relationship with Hamas, because any legitimacy for Hamas negatively affects the legitimacy of the Egyptian regime," said Emad Gad, an analyst at the Ahram Center for Political and Strategic Studies in Cairo.
18384	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"Any success for Hamas is a success for the Muslim Brotherhood."
18385	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	When Egypt opened its border with Gaza in September to allow Hamas militants to pass through, analysts in Egypt said that it was likely part of some deal, but that politically, they had no choice.
18386	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Newspapers in Egypt reported that Hamas turned over a wanted Qaida militant in exchange for the passage, a deal the government never confirmed.
18387	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"This would be a political crisis for Egypt," Gad said.
18388	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	"People will say that Egypt is cooperating with Israel against the Palestinians.
18389	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	And Egypt can not do this."
18390	NYT_ENG_20071108.0178.LDC2009T13	Analysts added that Egypt has cultivated an unofficial relationship with Hamas partly because it is such a large force that it can not be ignored and partly in the hope of bringing greater unity between Hamas and Fatah.
18391	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	SEX WORKERS FIGHT BACK AGAINST HIV
18392	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Cox News Service
18393	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	BOCA CHICA, Dominican Republic -- Saturday is date night in this fading beach town where paunchy American men promenade down the main drag at twilight, their arms draped proudly around lithe young local girls.
18394	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	As most of these couples literally don't speak the same language, silence prevails over dinner before a night of intimacy that will cost the men about $50.
18395	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The commercial sex trade that brings these couples together throngs the streets, fills the restaurants, keeps occupancy up in beach hotels during a slow season.
18396	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	It is a buyer's market on this impoverished island where the United States sends money to fight the HIV/AIDS epidemic, but with strings to keep it from anyone who does not condemn prostitution.
18397	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	A woman who asks to be called Julia joined the girls lining the street here as a teenager.
18398	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She hoped to make her living as a waitress, Julia says, but when that didn't cover food and rent, she sold sex after her shifts ended.
18399	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"People come to the city with dreams and learn there is nothing for them here," says Martha Butler de Lister, a physician and former national AIDS director who now works in Santo Domingo with charitable organizations.
18400	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"They end up selling happiness."
18401	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Julia doesn't anymore, since she found out she has AIDS.
18402	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Vaguely worded policy
18403	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	HAINA - Now Julia is back where she came from, in a turquoise- painted shack covered with children's handprints in white paint, where both sunlight and rain pour through gaps between boards covering the roof.
18404	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She does not know what she would have done after her diagnosis, she says, if it weren't for the women of Movimiento de Mujeres Unido (Movement of United Women).
18405	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	It is an organization of sex workers and former sex workers like her.
18406	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	A woman named Jocelyn from MODEMU helps Julia get her medicine and tells her she cannot work anymore.
18407	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	That is only one way some of the people hit hardest by the virus that leads to AIDS have taken a role in fighting the epidemic here.
18408	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Organized sex workers also have taken to the front lines in a search for solutions, participating in vaccine trials and teaching condom use, with some support from drug companies, nonprofit organizations and their government.
18409	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	One source from which they don't get money, though, is the U.S. President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief, which sent $6.4 million to fight the epidemic here last year, but with stipulations that preclude anyone who does not condemn sex work from getting the money.
18410	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Critics of that policy say the pledge has caused organizations to pull away from helping women who are both at the highest risk for catching the virus and in the greatest need of support.
18411	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"It's widely misunderstood," U.S. global AIDS coordinator Ambassador Mark Dybul responded recently.
18412	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	While critics refer to the policy as an "anti-prostitution pledge," Dybul says, the policy aims to help women by taking a stand against a trade that he calls "damaging to gender equality."
18413	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	He adds that PEPFAR money supports 120 programs that provide care and support services to women who are sex workers.
18414	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"There's a disconnect," Dybul says.
18415	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	If there is, it works against vulnerable women, says Jodi Jacobson of American Jewish World Services, an organization that assists grass-roots groups and has turned down a U.S. faith-based initiative grant rather than take the pledge.
18416	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She added that the policy is vaguely worded.
18417	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"There's a requirement that people sign and adopt a policy opposing prostitution, whatever that might mean," Jacobson says.
18418	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"Also, there's a requirement that you not promote prostitution, whatever that means."
18419	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The result, she says, has been that organizations shy away from helping sex workers, fearing that it will cost them money.
18420	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"I would say Ambassador Dybul hasn't spoken to people affected directly by the pledge."
18421	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Conjugal visits at penitentiary
18422	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	SANTO DOMINGO - Beachfront hotels and flashing casino lights are the fa?ade for a deeply divided and largely impoverished country, human rights activists here have said, pointing to the bateyes, former sugar cane plantations where imported Haitian laborers toiled for several decades for little more than subsistence, until even that money ran out.
18423	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Disparities are on display closer to the tourist destinations, too, along the Malecon seafront strip and the dim streets surrounding the colonial district where scores of streetwalkers wait for customers, and in gas stations where teenagers hop into cars driven by strangers.
18424	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Sex work is essentially legal here and institutionalized to the point that a recent law requires that "cabanas" - hotels that rent rooms by the hour - have two condoms in each room.
18425	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	On the higher-priced end are bikini-clad women with dancers' bodies who line up in the blink of disco lights at takeout brothels behind pricey casino hotels.
18426	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	They will spend the night with a customer for about $85.
18427	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	On the more desperate end are women who visit the nearby penitentiary, where HIV rates are estimated to be as much as five times higher than those on the outside.
18428	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	There, Wednesdays and Sundays are conjugal visiting days, when prisoners hang sheets over their bunks and sex workers serve prisoners for about 150 pesos, less than $5.
18429	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Some try to serve enough men to leave with 1,500 pesos.
18430	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"Sometimes they say they'll pay 100 pesos and then only pay half," a childlike young woman said on a recent visiting day.
18431	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	To make money during the rest of the week, many women who visit the prison also work on the streets serving tourists, says Grace Butler de Mejia, who runs Fundacion Genesis, which works with the American nonprofit Health Through Walls to bring condoms to the prison.
18432	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"This is an international problem," de Mejia says.
18433	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	'Now there is no work'
18434	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	DUQUESA - To understand how a woman can bring herself to such a place, one must look at the alternatives, says Sonia Pierre, an activist for the rights of Dominican women of Haitian descent.
18435	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"The women who do sexual work in jail come almost exclusively from the bateyes," Pierre said recently.
18436	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"More than 12 years ago, the sugar companies began to pull out.
18437	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Because now there is no work, bateyes are places of women and children."
18438	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Ten minutes from the center of Santo Domingo, a garbage dump replaced sugar cane fields as a source of livelihood for the residents in Duquesa, a quarter-mile-long settlement off the road to the new airport.
18439	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Here a series of philanthropic efforts turned a one-room schoolhouse into two rooms.
18440	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	It still does not draw many children, though, because they can better improve their immediate existences by diving in the dump.
18441	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	There - among rotting garbage, medical waste and industrial chemicals, including battery acid and mercury - children find toys and treasures in what other people throw away: a handful of drinking straws, bits of metal, plastic and glass they can sell.
18442	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	This is one of the better bateyes, says Pierre, who grew up in one and organized her first protest about conditions there at the age of 13.
18443	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Bateyes around Haina and San Cristobal are worse, she says.
18444	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Even for rural Dominicans not of Haitian descent and outside of bateyes, life is hard, offering few opportunities for women who struggle to support their families, Pierre stressed.
18445	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	'Not for $200, not for $500!'
18446	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	HAINA - By contrast, the rooms behind the Seaman Bar, where girls have sex with sailors for prices running from $15 to $20, are a haven, with roofs and running water.
18447	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The joking, squabbling and camaraderie of a girls' dormitory prevail here, where women decorate their rooms with rosaries, pictures of the Virgin Mary and snapshots of sailors.
18448	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Con suerte - with luck - they can make $500 a month, they say.
18449	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	More often they earn less than half that.
18450	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	When only a few ships dock, some make nothing at all.
18451	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Ships from around the world dock in this town in this industrial port town, with a weekly manifest showing visits from Miami, Savannah, Houston, New Orleans, as well as ports in Europe, South America and Asia.
18452	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Some of the children of women who work here reflect this diverse range of origins, with fathers from Haiti and the Philippines.
18453	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Jocelyn, a mother of three with a beatific smile, points to her 9 -month-old son and says his father is from India.
18454	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	A sex worker who also has recently found a niche in HIV education, Jocelyn says she always uses condoms, except with the fathers of her children.
18455	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Fellow sex workers watch her children for her when she travels to nearby towns with a tote bag filled with condoms and an anatomically correct model to roll them onto, showing other sex workers how to insist on, or if necessary, cajole a thin layer of protection.
18456	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"People will offer them $100 to have sex without a condom," she says.
18457	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"I tell them, 'No!
18458	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Not for $200, not for $500!"'
18459	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The girls at the Seaman Bar can knock on her door at 1 o'clock in the morning to get condoms, she says
18460	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	she keeps big bags full of them in the cramped, crowded two rooms across the street that she shares with six other people.
18461	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She gets paid for outreach work during funded projects now but stays in touch with the women whom she visits when she is not getting paid.
18462	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	That way, she says, she won't have to start over when she is called upon to look for new women to recruit for a vaccine trial.
18463	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Jocelyn participated in one of the first trials for an anti-HIV vaccine run by "Dr. Ellen" when her friend Juliana recruited her.
18464	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The trial gave her access to health care, vitamins and information on how to avoid getting sexually transmitted diseases, including HIV, she says.
18465	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	It also gave her a chance to hit back at the epidemic that affects people she knows.
18466	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Now when she meets women who have the virus or need treatment for other sexually transmitted infections, she sends them to Dr. Ellen.
18467	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She kisses her fingers and raises them to the sky when she says, "Dr. Ellen."
18468	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	'It is their challenge'
18469	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	SANTO DOMINGO - Dr. Ellen Koenig, who runs the Instituto Dominicano de Estudios Virologicos, did not set out to be a physician.
18470	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"The HIV epidemic made me a doctor," she says.
18471	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Koenig, an American who grew up in Delaware, had a degree in microbiology when she married a Dominican, and he invited her to join him "in paradise," she says.
18472	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"Then AIDS started."
18473	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	One of her brothers, Dr. Jay Levy, was involved in the earliest work to identify a virus.
18474	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	He suggested that she look for signs of the illness on the island.
18475	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The blood samples she and a team of local university students gathered later showed the virus was present in the Dominican Republic in the early 1980s.
18476	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Koenig began to diagnose people with HIV and, frustrated she could do nothing to help them, went to medical school, completing her degree in 1991 at the age of 50.
18477	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	As new medicines to manage AIDS became available, though, only the wealthiest patients could afford them.
18478	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"We lost a lot of patients because they didn't have the money," the doctor says.
18479	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"The only way I could see out was clinical trials."
18480	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The women of MODEMU were willing to help, Koenig says.
18481	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Women recruited through the group have since participated in a series of vaccine trials.
18482	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"These are the heroines of today's epidemic.
18483	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	They realize it is their challenge," Koenig says.
18484	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Like others who have faced the epidemic since its beginnings, she believes a vaccine that either will prevent infection or keep the virus from progressing is the best hope for containing HIV.
18485	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Then, she says, the women of MODEMU, who have continued to find volunteers, will be proud.
18486	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"I keep telling them, you one day will say to your children, 'I helped to make that vaccine possible."'
18487	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Talking 'equal to equal'
18488	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	HAINA - In the meantime, stipends for recruiting and outreach work allowed Jocelyn to buy a stove top, a refrigerator, a television, a couch and two chairs for the crowded apartment where two double beds were the only furniture for seven people.
18489	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Her friends say her career as a sex worker had slowed to the point that she had not had a customer in four months.
18490	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Juliana, who through her work with MODEMU recruited some of Koenig's first trial participants, lives with her two children in a solid, tidy two-bedroom house decorated with religious regalia.
18491	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She says she is retired.
18492	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She socializes with active sex workers.
18493	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	On a recent visit to the rooms behind the Seaman Bar, she rummaged pointedly through the toiletries cluttering a friend's dresser and, with an expression of satisfaction, held up a condom she found there.
18494	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She had a beer downstairs with a friend who still works the local prison on visiting days and who fills her straw purse with condoms to give other women working there.
18495	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	She, too, gets stipends for outreach work through MODEMU.
18496	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	With money from the government AIDS office, the group operates locally now from a sparsely equipped office on a noisy corner in the middle of Haina.
18497	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The office provides vocational and literacy training, as well as outreach workers to connect HIV-infected women with services and to make sure they know that they cannot work anymore.
18498	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"We talk with the women equal to equal to get across our message.
18499	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	I say 'us' to a sex worker," Juliana says.
18500	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	Many want a better life, she says, pointing to the response she gets when she recruits for vaccine trials.
18501	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	The future she and the others worry about stretches beyond their immediate needs, she says.
18502	NYT_ENG_20071112.0090.LDC2009T13	"I have a daughter who is 15, and I'm afraid."
