18515	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Because dried cranberries are often sweetened, you may reduce the honey to taste.
18516	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Fresh Cranberry Salsa 12 servings Hands on: 15 minutes Total time: 1 hour, 15 minutes
18517	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Serve this easy dip with corn chips - blue chips are fun.
18518	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	The recipe comes from The Associated Press.
18519	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	12 ounces (3 cups) fresh or frozen cranberries, washed 4 to 5 medium scallions, roughly chopped 3 cups loosely packed cilantro leaves 2 cups loosely packed fresh mint leaves 2 to 3 tablespoons seeded and chopped jalapeno peppers 1/2 tablespoon grated orange zest 1/2 cup honey 1/4 cup orange juice 2 tablespoons lime juice 2 to 3 drops hot sauce, or to taste
18520	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Place the cranberries in a food processor and pulse until finely chopped.
18521	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Transfer the cranberries to a medium bowl.
18522	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Set aside.
18523	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	In the food processor, combine the scallions, cilantro, mint, jalapenos and orange zest and pulse until finely chopped.
18524	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Transfer to the bowl with the cranberries and toss to mix.
18525	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	In a small bowl, mix together the honey, orange and lime juices, and hot sauce.
18526	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Pour the mixture over the salsa, toss to combine, then chill for at least 1 hour before serving.
18527	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Per serving: 361 calories (percent of calories from fat, 25), 9 grams protein, 59 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams fiber, 10 grams fat (2 grams saturated), 106 milligrams cholesterol, 276 milligrams sodium.
18528	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Share the recipe for your favorite potluck, bake sale or casual gathering dish with us.
18529	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Send the recipe, a short testimonial, your name, phone number and hometown to Jeanne Besser, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Eighth Floor, 72 Marietta St. N.W., Atlanta, GA 30303.
18530	NYT_ENG_20071114.0035.LDC2009T13	Or e-mail her at jbesser AT ajc.com.
18531	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	CHRIS-HART-Q &amp
18532	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	amp
18533	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	amp
18534	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	A-STP
18535	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	At his old job, Chris Hart lured businesses to Florida.
18536	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Now he's working the other side of the fence, making sure those businesses can find decent workers once they get here.
18537	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Hart, a former state legislator with deep roots in Tampa, became president of Workforce Florida in Tallahassee this month.
18538	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	His task?
18539	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Move the state's workers like they're pieces of a jigsaw puzzle: out of struggling industries and into fields that are growing, better paid and higher skilled.
18540	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Hart, 39, joins Workforce Florida from Enterprise Florida, another public-private organization aimed at economic development.
18541	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Here are excerpts from his interview last week with the St. Petersburg Times:
18542	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Why do we need an agency
18543	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	like Workforce Florida?
18544	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	When a business is looking to come to Florida, the first question they always ask us is about the work force.
18545	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	"What does your work force look like?
18546	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Are they educated the way I need them to be educated?
18547	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Do they have the certifications I need?"
18548	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	The way the world used to work, people went where the businesses were.
18549	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Now, the businesses go where the talent is.
18550	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Do out-of-state companies worry that Florida's talent is second rate?
18551	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	I don't think we're seen as second rate at all.
18552	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	It isn't (about) trying to bring us up to par with other states and other countries, but to kind of look over the horizon (at demographic changes, emerging industries, etc.) to decipher what training is going to be needed to support the next activity.
18553	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What are those next big activities?
18554	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What industries are going to create a lot of jobs here?
18555	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	The energy industry from line workers to plant workers and everything up and down the channel.
18556	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	There are several programs that are already in motion (to train energy workers): There's an Employ Florida Banner Center for energy at Lake-Sumter Community College that got under way this past spring.
18557	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	(The Banner Centers, which Workforce Florida rolled out last year, are state-funded programs that train workers in growing industries like aerospace, biotechnology and manufacturing.)
18558	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	There's also a Banner Center at UCF for alternative energy (in the works).
18559	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What else?
18560	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	The other area that we're looking at is space.
18561	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	The space shuttle by 2010 will no longer be in existence (according to NASA's plans).
18562	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	The next generation of spacecraft will need fewer workers.
18563	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	That gives us a great opportunity, because we have some of the smartest people they really are rocket scientists who are now available.
18564	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What are you going to
18565	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	do with all those rocket
18566	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	scientists?
18567	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	We're working with Enterprise Florida and Space Florida they can help point out what businesses they (the scientists) can go to.
18568	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What about the Tampa Bay area's work force?
18569	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What's
18570	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	our future in?
18571	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Tech and financial services.
18572	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	I see the University of South Florida and Moffitt Cancer Center and the fact that you have a lot of technology entrepreneurs.
18573	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	SRI is over there now in St. Pete
18574	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	they're going to need some of the best and brightest, they're going to need lab technicians, chemists and engineers.
18575	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Do we really have that
18576	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	kind of talent here?
18577	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Jimmy Wales is moving Wikipedia from St. Petersburg (to San Francisco) because
18578	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	his words!
18579	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	'you go where the talent is.'
18580	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	I don't think he was looking hard enough!
18581	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Florida is steadily losing jobs in manufacturing.
18582	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Does that bother you, or would you say 'good riddance'?
18583	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	I'd like to see a renewed interest in the state in manufacturing, but it's a clean manufacturing, a research and development manufacturing, not an easily copied type of manufacturing.
18584	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What do you mean by 'research and development manufacturing'?
18585	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Manufacturing new products and new processes.
18586	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	So mainly, those workers who are working to develop a new drug, or a new medical device.
18587	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	They would be manufacturing that not for mass distribution, because once you get to that point you've mechanized the process and that's something that you can bid on price a lot of that is probably being done offshore.
18588	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	You keep talking about knowledge-driven jobs.
18589	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	What about all our service jobs?
18590	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Do you want to get
18591	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	rid of them?
18592	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Some people say they want those jobs to disappear, but tourism and agriculture are lifeblood in this state, and have been since the beginning of Florida's existence.
18593	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	They do provide a lot of jobs, directly and indirectly.
18594	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	That's a big part of who we are.
18595	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	Christina Rexrode can be reached at rexrodesptimes.com or (727) 893-8318.
18596	NYT_ENG_20071124.0092.LDC2009T13	.
