18961	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Strike increases game-show allure
18962	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	By Mekeisha Madden Toby
18963	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Detroit News Television Writer
18964	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Reality TV shows aren't the only thing to look forward to this winter.
18965	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Game shows are the other choice.
18966	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	One such offering is Fox's new game show "The Moment of Truth," which debuts 9 p.m. Jan. 23.
18967	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Participants will be put to the test -- the lie detector test -- to reveal whether or not they are being honest for a chance to win $500,000.
18968	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	First, contestants must answer 21 increasingly personal questions honestly, as determined by a polygraph, to which they are attached prior to the game.
18969	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	At any time, between the polygraph and the televised game, participants can change their answers or walk away from the competition and forfeit the big cash payout.
18970	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	To win, the contestant must fess up to every one of her personal revelations knowing that the truth could spark shock and disappointment in her relatives and friends and cause public embarrassment on national television.
18971	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	If the Pinocchio motif of "The Moment of Truth" doesn't pique your interest, the current nine-week Writers Guild of America strike ensures the production of two returning game shows that don't use writers to fill in the broadcast network's programming holes:
18972	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	"Power of 10" (8 p.m. Wednesdays on CBS, Channel 62): Drew Carey pulls double duty -- he also hosts "The Price Is Right" in the day -- and fronts this summer-time favorite where contestants guess at the mindset of American pollsters, "Family Feud" style, for a shot at the $10 million top prize.
18973	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	"1 vs. 100" (8 p.m. Fridays on NBC, Channel 4): Contestants face off with a mob of 100 to correctly answer a number of trivia questions.
18974	NYT_ENG_20080102.0150.LDC2009T13	Comedian Bob Saget hosts.
