18976	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	NH-PROCESS-STP
18977	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Commentary: New Hampshire melted my cold Floridian heart
18978	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	It is wicked cold here in Dover, N.H., and the residents are pale and lumpy in their New England Patriots jackets, and the roadsides are festooned with campaign signs planted in the sooty snow banks like flags in Mount Everest, and in so many ways it is so much different than the rest of America.
18979	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	If New Hampshire were applying for the job of vetting candidates for president of these United States, one might suggest that New Hampshire look elsewhere for work, like at one of the approximately 1,443,713 Dunkin' Donuts that cover the state, the way corn covers Iowa.
18980	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	As a political reporter for Florida's largest newspaper, my sense has long been that New Hampshire played an outsized role in choosing the nation's presidential candidates.
18981	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	It has only 1.3-million residents, far fewer than live in the Tampa Bay area.
18982	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	More than 95 percent of them are white.
18983	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	You can drive from one end of New Hampshire to the other and back in less time than it takes to get from St. Petersburg to Miami, and that's taking the long way.
18984	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	It is dangerously close to Canada, a foreign country full of foreigners who, if they were to sneak across the border, would be illegal immigrants.
18985	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	So what makes the Granite State so great, so prescient, that it should tell everyone else in the country who should be president?
18986	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Wondering that very same thing, the Florida Legislature last year moved the Sunshine State's Democratic and Republican primary elections to Jan. 29, figuring a large, diverse and politically important state deserved a bigger role in choosing the next presidential candidates.
18987	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	New Hampshire and the other early primary and caucus states Iowa, Nevada and South Carolina were not amused.
18988	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Vetting presidents was their job, their political leaders insisted.
18989	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Florida was too big to serve as a laboratory, and it cost too much to campaign there.
18990	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Besides, the argument went, folks in other states just didn't have the tradition and interest in choosing the best candidates.
18991	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	"It's part of the culture here," said Fergus Cullen, the chairman of the New Hampshire Republican Party.
18992	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	"This is sort of hard for outsiders to appreciate, and I recognize that.
18993	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	But because the process has evolved over the last half century, voters take their role very seriously.
18994	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	We go to forums, go to town meetings, and make very informed decisions."
18995	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	That's the myth, anyway.
18996	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	But is it true?
18997	NYT_ENG_20080112.0080.LDC2009T13	Hit the ground shivering
