19049	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	REDUCING WATER PRESSURE, LADY BUGS
19050	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	Q. I have very high water pressure that measures about 100 (pounds per square inch I think), compared to a normal of 60.
19051	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	Could I turn the main valve down by half to reduce this pressure?
19052	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	TOO MUCH OOMPH
19053	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	A. I doubt it.
19054	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	There are two aspects to water delivery: Pressure (how much weight is behind the water flow) and volume (how much water is being pushed).
19055	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	Closing the intake valve down by a half or so will reduce the volume but the pressure will stay the same.
19056	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	But you can do something: Have a plumber install a pressure reducing valve on the main line coming into the house.
19057	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	This is a good idea because the high pressure can damage the pipes, especially the connections.
19058	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	Q. Two questions: I am getting quite a few lady bugs in the fall and even in the winter.
19059	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	They often hide in the ruffles of the curtains.
19060	NYT_ENG_20080117.0097.LDC2009T13	How can I keep them out of the house?
