19170	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	UKRAINE, EAGER FOR TIES TO THE WEST, JOINS THE WTO
19171	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	MOSCOW
19172	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Ukraine joined the World Trade Organization on Tuesday after 14 years of negotiations, a milestone for the former Soviet republic that helps clear the way for a valuable free trade agreement with the European Union.
19173	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Officials in the Ukrainian capital, Kiev, suggested that the membership represented a coming of age, of sorts, for trade relations of former Soviet countries.
19174	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The deal is expected to lift living standards and increase investment in what is one of Europe's poorest countries.
19175	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Ukraine -- with a population around 46 million and a gross domestic product estimated by the World Bank at $106 billion -- became the largest former Soviet state to join the trade group to date
19176	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Russia is negotiating for membership.
19177	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	"We have difficult homework to do," President Viktor A. Yushchenko of Ukraine said at a news conference in Geneva, where the WTO is based, as quoted by Bloomberg News.
19178	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	"This starts the colossal integration work that lies ahead."
19179	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	He said membership meant "better living standards, higher wages, improved social standards and economic life."
19180	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Trade among the former Soviet republics has often seemed chaotic, marred by politics, fraud and strange barter deals, like a swap in the mid-1990s when Ukraine paid for natural gas with a vast quantity of rubber boots instead of cash.
19181	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The final hurdle for Ukraine to join the WTO was an agreement to lower existing export tariffs on cattle, animal skins and ferrous metals, and not to raise them in the foreseeable future.
19182	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The deal -- about three years after Yushchenko came to power in widespread protests that became known as the Orange Revolution, pledging to integrate Ukraine more closely with the West -- paves the way for talks on creating a trade zone with the European Union.
19183	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	While the European bloc has declined to open membership talks, it kept the door open for discussions on a trade pact if Ukraine became a member of the WTO first.
19184	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The membership can be expected to give Ukraine some leverage in settling disputes with Russia over steel, sugar and dairy products.
19185	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Though Russia is working to join the WTO, because Ukraine is now in, it will have a veto on Russian membership.
19186	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Another Russian neighbor, Georgia, has threatened to use its veto against Russian membership unless Moscow lifts a ban on imports of Georgian wine, ostensibly for health reasons though more likely a result of the souring of political relations between the countries.
19187	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Russia also bans the import of Georgian mineral water and citrus fruit.
19188	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Ukraine will take a different tack, Irina Gerashchenko, a member of parliament from Yushchenko's Our Ukraine party, explained in a telephone interview.
19189	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Yushchenko's support of Russia's membership, she said, was aimed at ushering Russia into the group as quickly as possible so that Ukraine can avail itself of the WTO's dispute-resolution mechanisms to resolve their conflicts.
19190	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	At the signing ceremony on Tuesday, Yushchenko said that he would support Russia's membership.
19191	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	For Ukraine, he said, membership in the WTO would raise the gross domestic product and bring additional billions in foreign investment.
19192	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The agreement is subject to ratification by the Ukrainian parliament, or Rada, by July 4.
19193	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	All major Ukrainian political parties except the Communists support membership, but that may not guarantee easy approval.
19194	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Earlier in the day, Yushchenko canceled a speech equivalent to the State of the Union because opposition members of parliament occupied the rostrum
19195	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	others hung posters on the walls protesting the president's support for joining NATO.
19196	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	The speaker of parliament removed the presidential speech from the day's agenda, and the president's press service said it would be rescheduled.
19197	NYT_ENG_20080205.0134.LDC2009T13	Yushchenko then flew to Geneva to sign the trade pact.
