19219	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	FOR A TRAVELING ATHLETE, PAYING TAXES IS A COMPLICATED BUSINESS
19220	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Derek Jeter, the New York Yankee shortstop, has resolved his problems with New York state tax collectors, state officials said last week.
19221	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Details of the settlement are not known, but the dispute revolved around a tax issue that is central for athletes and other itinerant workers: the official location of their permanent residence.
19222	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Jeter said he has lived for years near the New York Yankees' complex in Tampa, Fla., where there is no state income tax
19223	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	New York state officials said that from 2001 through 2003, his residence was in Manhattan, and that he was therefore responsible for New York state income tax for that period.
19224	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Athletes who play in numerous out-of-town stadiums, as Jeter does, not only need to pin down their legal residence but they must also pay attention to another ticklish problem: which state is entitled to collect tax from them on any given day.
19225	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	The results are often a tax return as thick as a phone book and as complex as a collateralized debt obligation.
19226	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	In fact, states with nonresident income taxes treat players on visiting teams like workers in those states -- every time the team visits.
19227	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Given the combinations and permutations of league and interleague play, a player might have to file returns in more than a dozen states, and in Canada, too.
19228	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Team players in other sports, like football, basketball and hockey, and even professional tennis and golf players, are treated the same way.
19229	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	So are entertainers and anyone else whose work life follows a similar pattern.
19230	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Complicating the task of figuring all this out is the concept of state tax credits.
19231	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	If a player's home state has an income tax, it will allow him to deduct roughly what he has paid to other states from the amount owed the home state.
19232	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	For example, Laurence I. Foster, a certified public accountant who is a consultant at Eisner L.L.P., said that "when the Yankees are playing in Cleveland, Cleveland taxes would apply."
19233	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	They are deducted from New York taxes due on that income.
19234	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	This makes hitting a 95-mph fastball look simple.
19235	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	David Wright, the New York Mets' third baseman, said, "I try to understand taxes, or at least the basics of everything.
19236	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	But there are things that I really can't 100 percent grasp."
19237	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	That's why, he said, "I surround myself with people who do know the laws and the rules."
19238	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Doing so is in an athlete's interest, because the amounts involved are far from chump change.
19239	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	A $20-million-a-year Boston Red Sox superstar who plays nine games at Yankee Stadium, for instance, might owe in the vicinity of $100,000 in New York state and New York City tax.
19240	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	In Jeter's case, state records show that New York state brought a tax-collection civil proceeding against him in November, contending that he was a New York resident from 2001 to 2003.
19241	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	State officials would not say why they zeroed in on only those years.
19242	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	While playing for the Yankees, and staying in town between home games, would probably not be enough to establish residency in New York, state tax officials pointed to other actions, including the presence of many of Jeter's valued personal items in his apartment in the Trump World Tower building in Manhattan, and "public statements regarding his desire to be in New York," according to documents in the proceeding.
19243	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	While a state official who had been briefed on the case said last week that it had been settled, he would not say what payment, if any, was required.
19244	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Tom Bergin, a spokesman for the State Department of Taxation and Finance, said the department had no comment on the matter.
19245	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Jeter's lawyer, Maria T. Jones, called the case "confidential" and declined to use the word "settlement."
19246	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Making clear that she was not talking specifically about the Jeter case, Jones said that multistate taxation of not only athletes and performers but even executives who travel often was "an important issue" nationwide, even when residency is not in question.
19247	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Multiple-state taxation is a "crazy hodgepodge of rules and systems," said Stephen W. Kidder, a lawyer in Boston who deals with the issue on behalf of the baseball, football and hockey players' unions.
19248	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	"Virtually every state where the players play taxes visiting players on some percentage of their time and wages earned," he said.
19249	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	If an athlete lives in a state like Florida that has no income tax, he pays each state visited the tax on the income attributable to those games, Foster said
19250	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	there are no state tax credits in such a case.
19251	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	A Florida resident playing for the Yankees, for example, would pay no tax on income earned while playing the Tampa Bay Rays, or while in spring training in Florida.
19252	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	But if that player lived in New York, he would owe money on the Florida income, because New York taxes its residents on all their income, wherever it is earned.
19253	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Because of the complexity of the issues, it can take three to five times longer to prepare an athlete's return than another one with the same level of complexity on federal tax issues, according to Steve Blatt and Robert E. Harrison, part of a team at Tanner Mainstain Blatt &amp
19254	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	amp
19255	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Glynn, an accounting firm in Los Angeles that deals with many professional athletes.
19256	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Foster said that teams usually provide their players with a breakdown of income earned in each state, but he double-checks the figures.
19257	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	Asked if calculating multiple state taxes was an automated process after those figures are verified, he said: "Nothing is that automated.
19258	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	If it were, all the ballplayers could go to H&amp
19259	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	amp
19260	NYT_ENG_20080210.0033.LDC2009T13	R Block."
19261	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	PANAMA FINDS MEDICINE POISONED 174
19262	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Panamanian investigators have concluded that at least 174 people were poisoned, 115 of them fatally, by counterfeit cold medicine linked to an unlicensed Chinese chemical plant.
19263	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The report was the government's first effort to offer a precise toll of those killed and disabled in the mass poisoning in 2006.
19264	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	But the head of the agency that prepared the report, Dr. Jose Vicente Pachar, said the number of victims was bound to be much higher because many in remote areas of the country were unlikely to report their cases to the government.
19265	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	"The figures we have are the tip of the iceberg," Pachar, director of the Institute of Legal Medicine of Panama's Public Ministry, said in an interview.
19266	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	"We will never know the full extent."
19267	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	As if to underscore that point, a government agency that dispenses aid to victims found a higher number of poisoning victims: 184 so far, including 123 deaths.
19268	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	More than 700 claims have been filed on behalf of possible poisoning victims.
19269	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pachar's agency issued its report two weeks ago after investigating victims' claims and exhuming more than 50 bodies.
19270	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Previously, the government had estimated the death toll at 100.
19271	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The mass poisoning caused a political upheaval in Panama, partly because the government itself distributed the counterfeit medicine and because of questions over how vigorously the authorities sought to identify and help the victims.
19272	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	One protest last summer turned violent when the police began clubbing families of victims who were trying to deliver a list of complaints to Panama's president.
19273	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The poisonings also brought new scrutiny to Chinese exports after The New York Times reported last May that a supposedly safe drug ingredient in the cold medicine actually contained diethylene glycol, an industrial solvent used in some antifreeze.
19274	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	What is more, it was made by a Chinese chemical company that did not have a license to sell drug ingredients.
19275	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	China's regulators initially said they had no legal grounds to take action against the manufacturer, but under rising international pressure the government closed the plant last year.
19276	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The families of some Panamanian victims have accused their government of trying to suppress the number of those harmed.
19277	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Gabriel Pascual, the leader of a group that represents victims and their families, criticized the government for ruling some cases inconclusive for poisoning without specifying their reasons.
19278	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pascual cited seven examples of people he said had medical records certifying that they ingested the poison, yet who government investigators concluded were unaffected or had inconclusive evidence.
19279	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	In 128 cases, the government said it lacked enough information to reach a definitive conclusion.
19280	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pascual also criticized the slow pace of the exhumations.
19281	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The authorities said that they exhumed 52 bodies, and that 27 of those tested positive for diethylene glycol.
19282	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Asked why more bodies were not exhumed, Pachar said the tests were expensive, adding: "The institute's budget is about $3 million for the whole year.
19283	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The government spends almost $4 million on Carnival."
19284	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pachar, whose report is being used by prosecutors in criminal cases they have filed against 16 Panamanians involved in the handling and distribution of the toxic syrup, said it was impossible to identify all the possible victims.
19285	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	"People in the countryside who live far from the modern sectors of Panama tend to think of death as a matter of God's will," he said.
19286	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	"They tend not to report deaths that we might find suspicious."
19287	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	He said his investigation was 95 percent complete.
19288	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Elida de Gonzalez, the chief social worker for the Victims' Support Office, said her agency confirmed a different number of victims than Pachar's agency because the two investigated independently.
19289	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Gonzalez speculated that her agency's number was higher because people might be more willing to report their cases to an agency that provides financial aid.
19290	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pascual, the representative of the victims' group, said he was injured during a demonstration on July 19, 2007, when the police used billy clubs to stop the group from presenting a petition listing its complaints to President Martin Torrijos.
19291	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Pascual said one person was hospitalized and seven others were treated and released.
19292	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Afterward, the government apologized.
19293	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	"It's really sad and lamentable what happened," Torrijos said in a statement to the press.
19294	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The poisonings occurred after a Chinese factory sold 46 barrels of toxic syrup to a Beijing broker, owned by China's government.
19295	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	It then sold the mislabeled syrup to another broker in Barcelona, who passed it on to a Panamanian broker, who sold the barrels to a Panamanian health service.
19296	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	It unwittingly mixed the diethylene glycol into 260,000 bottles of cold medicine.
19297	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	No one in China has been prosecuted for selling the counterfeit syrup.
19298	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	The same poison, diethylene glycol, was later detected in Chinese-made toothpaste sold in Panama, setting off a worldwide hunt for tainted toothpaste.
19299	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	Last year nearly three dozen countries, including the United States, issued health alerts or product recalls after finding diethylene glycol in Chinese toothpaste.
19300	NYT_ENG_20080213.0114.LDC2009T13	China's government responded by banning the use of diethylene glycol in toothpaste.
19301	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	HIGH-PROFILE INVESTMENTS BRING NEW SCRUTINY TO ABU DHABI FUND
19302	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Abu Dhabi has 10 percent of the world's oil and 0.02 percent of its population.
19303	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The result is a surfeit of petrodollars, much of which is funneled into a secretive, government-controlled investment fund that is helping to shift the balance of power in the financial world.
19304	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	After decades in the shadows, the fund, the Abu Dhabi Investment Authority, is turning heads on Wall Street and in Washington by making high-profile investments in the United States and elsewhere.
19305	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Known as ADIA (pronounced ah-DEE-ah), the fund recently formed a small team that is now buying big stakes in Western companies.
19306	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	This unit masterminded ADIA's $7.5 billion investment in Citigroup, the largest U.S. bank, in November.
19307	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	It has also taken a large position in Toll Brothers, one of America's biggest home builders.
19308	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"There is an idea that Abu Dhabi should not be the underdog of the map," said Frauke Heard-Bey, a historian who has written a book about the political emergence of the United Arab Emirates.
19309	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"They have the money to buy companies that are ailing, and why should they not?
19310	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Why not make a mark?"
19311	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	ADIA is the largest of the world's sovereign wealth funds, giant pools of money controlled by cash-rich governments, particularly in Asia and Middle East.
19312	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	But Abu Dhabi, the wealthiest of the seven Arab emirates, says little about its fund.
19313	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Few outsiders know for sure where ADIA invests -- or even how much money it controls.
19314	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	And secrecy breeds hyperbole
19315	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	some estimates of the fund's size surpass $1 trillion.
19316	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Before long, ADIA will certainly reach that mark.
19317	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	But for now bankers, former employees and analysts familiar with the fund peg it at $650 billion to $700 billion -- an amount that is still more than 15 times the size of the Fidelity Magellan Fund.
19318	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	In all, sovereign wealth funds in countries like the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Singapore, China and Russia together control more than $2 trillion, a figure that could approach $12 trillion by 2015, analysts say.
19319	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Such riches, coupled with the more-aggressive stance being taken by ADIA and other sovereign funds, has raised concern that these investors will wield their wealth for political as well as financial reasons.
19320	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	ADIA's secrecy is also drawing scrutiny.
19321	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The fund has no internal communications department, although it says it is in the process of setting one up.
19322	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	When sovereign fund leaders from around the world descended on Davos, Switzerland, in February for the World Economic Forum, no one from ADIA saw fit to show up.
19323	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Executives at ADIA declined to comment for this article.
19324	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Last week Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind., the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on security and international trade and finance, who has raised concerns about sovereign fund transparency, traveled to Abu Dhabi to meet with senior ADIA executives.
19325	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Also last week, a delegation led by Clay Lowery, a top Treasury official, met with ADIA executives as part of a dialogue to formalize investment guidelines for sovereign funds.
19326	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	In many ways the tension between ADIA's elephantine size -- the fund is twice as big as Norway's, the second-largest sovereign fund -- and its demure aspect is underscored by its investment in Citigroup.
19327	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Since ADIA's genesis in 1976, the fund has followed a conservative investment approach.
19328	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	It has farmed out its assets to foreign money managers and taken stakes in companies based upon their weighting in benchmark stock indexes like the Standard &amp
19329	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	amp
19330	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Poor's 500.
19331	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	ADIA is also one of the largest institutional investors in hedge funds and private-equity funds.
19332	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	This approach has served ADIA well and reflects the strongly felt notion that the fund's ultimate purpose is to serve as a financial reserve for Abu Dhabi in times when oil revenues are less robust.
19333	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Nevertheless, guided by the advice of a stream of foreign bankers who worked at ADIA in the 1970s and 1980s, the fund has allocated a large portion of its assets to equities.
19334	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	It now has about 65 percent of assets, or about $450 billion, invested in stocks, according to bankers.
19335	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Currently, the fund averages a yearly return of 10 to 20 percent, say people who have been briefed on the fund's investment strategy.
19336	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	With oil about $100 a barrel, bankers and analysts estimate Abu Dhabi produces a surplus of at least $50 billion a year.
19337	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Given the emirate's small population, 80 percent of which is foreign born, even the most expansive investment and welfare policies make it hard to put a dent in such a sum.
19338	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The United States is not a big buyer of Abu Dhabi's oil, most of which goes to Asia, but the surplus is a vivid reminder of the U.S. economy's own fiscal imbalance, to say nothing of its diminishing global stature, a theme that underpins much of the political worry surrounding sovereign fund investments.
19339	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"In the short run, that they are investing here is good," Bayh said.
19340	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"But in the long run it is unsustainable.
19341	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Our power and authority is eroding because of the amounts we are sending abroad for energy and consumer goods."
19342	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	In the past, much of Abu Dhabi's cash surplus has gone to ADIA, although the formation two years ago of a smaller sister fund, the Abu Dhabi Investment Council, has resulted in a lesser amount flowing to ADIA, analysts say.
19343	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	But ADIA's new strategic investment group represents the clearest sign that the fund is taking steps to leverage its size and influence.
19344	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The division was set up in the summer of 2006 and is overseen by Saeed Mubarek Rashid al-Hajiri, a young, Western- educated portfolio manager who also heads the fund's considerable investments in emerging-market economies.
19345	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	In addition to Citigroup and Toll Brothers, in which AIDA took a 4.5 percent position last summer, other companies in the group's portfolio include EFG Hermes, one of the leading investment banks in the Arab world, and Banque de Tunisie et des Emirats, a Tunisian bank.
19346	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Instead of passively tracking indexes, this unit actively picks investments in hopes of generating market-beating returns.
19347	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	It is a method of stock picking practiced by most hedge funds and asset management companies, and the Citigroup investment, with its size and attendant risk, is a good example of this approach.
19348	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Compared with the overall fund, the assets within this group are small at about $30 billion, according to people who have been briefed on ADIA's strategy.
19349	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	As with all its investments, ADIA adopts a long-term, passive approach and does not seek board seats.
19350	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	These people say that outsiders still manage 80 percent of ADIA's assets, proof that the fund's commitment to making direct investments is only in its early stages.
19351	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	This hesitation partly reflects the lack of a strong individual within the organization who has the combination of investment experience, trust of the royal family and a bit of international swagger to assume a larger public presence.
19352	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Sheik Khalifa bin Zayed al-Nahyan, the president of the United Arab Emirates and the ruler of Abu Dhabi, while chairman of the fund, has a cautious and reserved disposition and does not take an active role in ADIA.
19353	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	When Citigroup's chairman, Robert E. Rubin, traveled to Abu Dhabi last November, his courtesy call was made to Sheik Mohammed bin Zayed al-Nahyan, the crown prince of Abu Dhabi and the point person for the United States-Abu Dhabi relationship.
19354	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The fund's managing director is Sheik Ahmed bin Zayed al-Nahyan, a half-brother of Sheik Khalifa who maintains a full-floor office in ADIA's sleek 40-story headquarters.
19355	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	People familiar with ADIA management, however, say the sheik, who has worked at ADIA for 10 years, delegates significant authority to Jean-Paul Villain, a publicity-shy French money manager who directs investment strategy and asset allocation.
19356	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Villain, the most senior foreign-born executive at the fund, first joined ADIA in the early 1980s from the French bank Paribas.
19357	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	While other expatriates have come and gone, Villain has stayed, except for a brief period in the mid-1980s.
19358	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	More so than the other foreigners, Villain, whose wife is Syrian-born, has gained the royal family's trust.
19359	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	One view is that ADIA's penchant for secrecy stems from its experience during the scandal at the Bank of Credit &amp
19360	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	amp
19361	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Commerce International of the early 1990s, during which ADIA is said to have lost hundreds of millions of dollars.
19362	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	The al-Nahyan family became embroiled in regulatory investigations, although no charges were ever brought against them.
19363	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	But people who worked at ADIA from its earliest days in the late 1970s and 1980s say that the fund's reticence dates to its formation.
19364	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	Some see this as a reflection of Abu Dhabi's small size, insular culture and geographical vulnerability, a sense that the less that is known about the specifics of ADIA's hoard, the better.
19365	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"ADIA does not answer to a wide public at home," said David L. Mack, a former United States ambassador to the United Arab Emirates.
19366	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	"They are a small country in an area with some nasty countries like Iran that can make trouble for them.
19367	NYT_ENG_20080227.0187.LDC2009T13	They don't like to advertise."
