19461	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	STRIVING FOR NORMALITY, IRAQ TO CRACK DOWN ON SEAT BELT SCOFFLAWS STEPHEN FARRELL CONTRIBUTED REPORTING.
19462	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	BAGHDAD
19463	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Iraqis often complain about the problems in their country and the government's lack of obvious progress in solving them.
19464	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	But as drivers in traffic-clogged Baghdad learned this week, Iraqi officials are taking action in one area: strict enforcement of a seat belt law.
19465	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Later this month, traffic police officers all over Iraq will start issuing tickets to any scofflaw who drives without buckling up.
19466	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Violators will be fined 15,000 dinars -- about $12.50.
19467	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"It is part of the healing process of this country and of Baghdad to enforce the law, law by law," said Brig. Gen. Zuhair Abada Mraweh, traffic commander for the capital's Rusafah district.
19468	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"The citizens are learning the laws step by step," said Mraweh, sitting in his office in the Karada neighborhood.
19469	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"We have applied all the laws concerning traffic, so it's time for the seat belt law to be practiced."
19470	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Some might say that that there are more pressing issues, like the car bombs that can turn a morning commute into a nightmare of blood and body parts, the daily killings and kidnappings, the political and sectarian infighting.
19471	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Or that enforcing the seat belt law might not be an adequate solution in a city where traffic rarely moves above a crawl, checkpoints are ubiquitous, roads are often blocked and it is not uncommon to see a vehicle charging down a street in the wrong direction or abruptly swerving across lanes.
19472	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Still, brigades of traffic officers trying valiantly to do their jobs have been a constant in an ever-changing landscape of war and chaos over the last five years.
19473	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	And as traffic police officers warned Baghdad drivers earlier this week that seat belt enforcement was about to begin, many drivers said it was probably a good thing.
19474	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"It is a symbol of civilization," said a taxi driver, Ahmed Wahayid, whose 1993 Honda Elantra was stuck in a long line of cars waiting to clear a checkpoint.
19475	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"Western people in Europe and America have it, so we are like them."
19476	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Wahayid said he could not find words to describe the traffic in Baghdad.
19477	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"It's a very, very bad feeling, and if I didn't need to drive in order to eat and live I wouldn't," he said.
19478	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Hussain Fathil, 35, trying to guide his 1991 Opel through the logjam, put it more briefly: "It pulls your heart apart," he said.
19479	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	But he doubted whether enforcing the seat belt law would help.
19480	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"Do you want to know my opinion?'
19481	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	he said.
19482	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"This law cannot be applied in such a city."
19483	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	But he had his seat belt on and said that he would keep wearing it.
19484	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	"It's the law," he said.
19485	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Mraweh said that the seat belt legislation -- which applies only to drivers, not passengers -- was in effect during the government of Saddam Hussein.
19486	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	After the Americans invaded in 2003, a high import tax on automobiles was lifted, flooding Iraq with enthusiastic new drivers.
19487	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	He said there were no dependable statistics on traffic accidents, but that enforcing the law would reduce them by 70 percent.
19488	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	Mraweh is passionate about traffic control.
19489	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	He is particularly irked by the driving behavior by the employees of security companies like Blackwater, who sometimes throw water bottles at people walking down the street or shoot their guns in the air to clear the road, he said.
19490	NYT_ENG_20080416.0147.LDC2009T13	But primarily, Mraweh sees his job as a way to piece together his shattered country.
