19696	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	EVACUATION ORDERED AS CHILEAN VOLCANO BEGINS TO SPEW ASH
19697	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	SANTIAGO, Chile
19698	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	The Chaiten volcano in southern Chile blasted ash and what appeared to be lava a dozen miles into the air on Tuesday, leading the government to order the immediate and complete evacuation of everyone living within a 30-mile radius of it.
19699	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	Preceded by dozens of tremors, the volcano -- until now considered inactive -- began erupting last Friday.
19700	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	It covered about 60 square miles with more than 15 inches of ash, rendering the air unbreathable, contaminating water sources, killing livestock and destroying all small- and medium-scale agriculture in this rural and mostly impoverished area 800 miles south of the capital, Santiago.
19701	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	An enormous gray mushroom cloud of ash that could be seen from 100 miles away has since loomed over this sliver of land next to Argentina, where continental Chile breaks up into archipelagos.
19702	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	East winds have spread ash toward Argentina.
19703	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	The thick layer of volcanic ash, coupled with rain, has made access to the sparsely populated border zone difficult.
19704	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	President Michelle Bachelet visited the area on Monday, announcing subsidies and other aid for affected families.
19705	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	On Tuesday, she convened an emergency committee of government ministers, emergency agency representatives, the director of the police force and regional officials.
19706	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	The committee resolved to order the total evacuation of Chaiten, to authorize the release of emergency funds and to appoint Defense Minister Jose Goni to coordinate the response to the natural disaster.
19707	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	"The situation is rather complicated," said Interior Minister Edmundo Perez.
19708	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	"The volcano continues erupting, and we don't know how long this will last.
19709	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	It could be a day, a week or more."
19710	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	About 8,000 residents of nearby towns have been evacuated since the weekend.
19711	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	There have been no deaths or injuries reported, although a 92-year-old woman died of a heart attack as she was evacuated from Chaiten on Sunday.
19712	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	After flying over the area on Tuesday morning, specialists from the National Geology and Mining Service said that they had found no evidence of lava flowing from the volcano, although they were able to see lava at the base of the large crater.
19713	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	This is the first time the Chaiten volcano has erupted in at least 2,000 years, according to service officials.
19714	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	Since the weekend, the military, navy and police have helped ship out several thousand residents from Chaiten, situated only six miles away from the base of the volcano and near the Chaiten Bay.
19715	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	About 20 families are still refusing to leave their homes, animals and belongings in spite of the presidential order, which makes no exceptions for military, police or journalists.
19716	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	On Tuesday, hundreds of residents in Futaleufu, just miles from the border, were being evacuated voluntarily by bus, crossing over to Argentina for part of the journey.
19717	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	About 25,000 head of cattle and sheep are at imminent risk of dying, eating plants and drinking water contaminated by volcanic ash.
19718	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	The navy has shipped feed, and some animals have also been evacuated to uncontaminated areas.
19719	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	Some civil engineers said they believed that the soil and plant life in the area may not recover for several decades, if at all.
19720	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	"The soil in the area covered by this volume of ash deposits will be practically lost," said Wilfredo Vera, engineer from the University of Chile.
19721	NYT_ENG_20080506.0226.LDC2009T13	He told a Chilean radio station that "agricultural production will be virtually nil."
