19723	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	NEW YORK
19724	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Without horses, where would we be?
19725	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Trousers might never have become fashionable.
19726	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The violin might never have come into existence.
19727	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The Aztecs might have thrived another few centuries.
19728	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The Industrial Revolution might have sputtered out before its time.
19729	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	No one would have to get off his high horse, and no political race would have a dark horse candidate.
19730	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	And the American Museum of Natural History would have had to find another subject for its sprawling, charming and illuminating exhibition that is opening Saturday: "The Horse."
19731	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The opening festivities will include demonstrations of horseshoeing and horse grooming
19732	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	an appearance by Thumbelina, a creature billed as the world's smallest horse (171/2 inches tall)
19733	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	and a visit by a vintage horse-drawn ambulance.
19734	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	But the exhibition itself relies far less on country fair spectacle and far more on a provocative history of the ways in which humans and horses became, as the show says, "powerfully linked."
19735	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Those links may be as slight as fashions in clothing (trousers, we are told, developed specifically for the riding of horses) and as important as the fate of empires ("Next to God," Cortes is supposed to have said about the conquest of Mexico, "we owed our victory to the horses").
19736	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The exhibition is suggestive about the evolution of the arts.
19737	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	(The 13th- and 14th-century Mongols, who held their immense empire together with the aid of the horse, also used hair from its tail to create the ancestor of the modern violin bow.)
19738	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	And it invites speculation about the course of technology.
19739	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	(The Industrial Revolution ultimately displaced horse power with horsepower, but not before horses shared the burden with machines: on display is a horse-drawn, steam-powered firetruck from 19th-century Pennsylvania.)
19740	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Created by Ross MacPhee, the curator of mammalogy in the Division of Vertebrate Zoology at the museum, and Sandra Olsen, the curator of anthropology at the Carnegie Museum of Natural History in Pittsburgh, this show makes it clear just how crucial a role the horse has played.
19741	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	With the aid of dioramas, interviews, marvelous computer graphics, varied skeletons, archaeological finds, reproductions of cave paintings and objects, including a World War I gas mask for a horse and Triple Crown trophies, the history of the horse becomes humanized.
19742	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The ancient Greeks, the show points out, might have been so surprised by their first sight of warriors on horseback that they imagined that they were centaurs.
19743	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The exhibition almost seems to suggest that this mythology touches on a deeper truth: The connection is so strong, we are all of us centaurs.
19744	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	At one time the relationship could hardly have been ignored.
19745	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Horses, the show reminds us, "have cleared forests, plowed land, herded cattle and driven machines."
19746	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	From the moment they were first used to pull chariots into battle (perhaps 1500 B.C.) until their valedictory cavalry campaigns in the World War II, horses were bound up in human warfare.
19747	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Similarly, with human welfare: in 1900 130,000 horses were working in Manhattan alone (and their presence must have been palpable: each horse, the show says, produced up to 45 pounds of manure and 2 gallons of urine every day).
19748	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Now we are mainly aware of horses through the remnants of horse- inspired vocabulary, by the persistence of sports like polo, and, as a video shows, from ceremonies from around the world that use the horse to display power and grace.
19749	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	But the show reminds us just how recent a phenomenon this diminution of importance is, and how difficult it is to think of any human activity untouched by the powers of the horse.
19750	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	But the horse, of course, is equally unthinkable without the human, which the exhibition also points out, but humans don't enter the story for a while.
19751	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The opening diorama shows ancient horses of North America, some 50 million years ago: a three-toed Hypohippus feeds on forest shrubs as a large, modern-looking Dinohippus grazes in the grasses.
19752	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	A large number of horse species were "forest browsers" with three toes.
19753	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	But with the changes in climate about 35 million years ago, the predecessor of the modern horse became dominant, his two outer toes yielding to the single hoof, suited to the harder grasslands.
19754	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	In outlining the evolution of the horse, the exhibition also traces the animals' mass migrations, which are almost the inverse of human pathways.
19755	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Instead of beginning in Africa and migrating to Europe, Asia and finally to the Americas, like mankind's ancestors, horses took just the opposite path: the majority of horse species began in the Americas.
19756	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Some 20 million years ago, three-toed horses crossed into Asia and then into Europe and Africa.
19757	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	About 10,000 years ago, horses became extinct in the Americas -- perhaps because of environmental change and overhunting -- which is one reason they had such a forceful impact when the Spanish took them back to the Americas, in conquest.
19758	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	That expansive family tree was pruned over time and not, it seems, by human forces.
19759	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The show argues that all contemporary horses -- perhaps even the Asiatic wild horse, the Przewalski -- are part of a single species, Equus caballus.
19760	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Even the genus Equus is small, containing only seven living species, including donkeys and zebras.
19761	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The impact of the horse, though, is apparent in the earliest surviving human evidence.
19762	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The show reproduces some of the extraordinary cave paintings of Southern Europe, which are perhaps 16,000 years old.
19763	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	One, in Lascaux Cave, shows a horse looking exactly like the Przewalski wild horse of Central Asia, with its pale stomach and dark mane.
19764	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Recent archaeological research in northern Kazakhstan, displayed in a diorama, suggests that the Botai people of Central Asia were among the first to domesticate horses.
19765	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Digs have yielded evidence of ancient fences, along with soil components suggesting a high concentration of manure.
19766	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	In domestication, horses were remade into human companions and human tools, but physiologically they didn't change much-- something that, as the exhibition notes, cannot be said of the boar when it was transformed into a domesticated pig, or the wolf into a domesticated dog.
19767	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Horses were also "good partners": herd animals that could also show intense loyalties.
19768	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	They were easily trained and relatively free from the territorial viciousness of related species, like zebras.
19769	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Human planning split this single species into numerous branches and more than 200 breeds.
19770	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	One ambition was to increase the animal's size, so it could become a more imposing war-beast, strong enough to bear its own 50 pounds of armor along with the hundreds of pounds of a mounted warrior.
19771	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	So important was the size of warrior horses that in the 16th century, King Henry VIII, coveting the larger animals on the continent, decreed that all landowners must keep at least two large mares.
19772	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Among the gentry of Europe, the domestication of the horse, and the formal display of ownership and mastery, also came to reflect personal cultivation and accomplishment.
19773	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The French, Spanish and English words for gentleman, the show points out -- chevalier, caballero and cavalier -- also mean horseman.
19774	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Some parts of this show are too brief -- the transformation of the American West could have been more imaginatively presented -- and some parts are less than revelatory: the presence of horses in sports is familiar.
19775	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The show might also have provided more extensive glimpses of the horse in the arts: in Remington's famous 19th-century images, in plays like "Equus," in Hollywood westerns or even in vintage television comedies like "Mister Ed."
19776	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Horses have generally been imagined not as alien beings, but as reflections of ourselves.
19777	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	They are almost never demonic
19778	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	they seem to represent the best of humanity's animal nature.
19779	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Despite weaknesses, though, the show's impact is strong.
19780	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	And could interaction between humans and any other animal bear this sort of examination?
19781	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Dogs may inspire more intense and complex friendships, but horses were almost more than companions
19782	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	they were partners in agriculture, war, industry and commerce.
19783	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	The final gallery contains a remarkable life-size sculpture of a horse, "Isbelle," by Deborah Butterfield.
19784	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	It seems constructed out of scraps of driftwood, but is actually cast bronze, its weathered skeleton looking worn and ancient.
19785	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	It seems old, haphazardly shaped with its random relics and remnants, but the creature is so tautly formed, its skeletal innards seem charged with dynamism and power.
19786	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	It's not a bad image for this presentation of the horse's history: it might seem a collection of ancient and random facts, but when brought together as smartly as it is, it almost comes to life, reminding us of the centaurs we all once were.
19787	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	GIDDYUP!
19788	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	A 'Horse' Trot
19789	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Free outdoor activities are planned Saturday from noon to 4 p.m., weather permitting, for the opening of "The Horse" at the American Museum of Natural History.
19790	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	On 81st Street, between Central Park West and Columbus Avenue, members of the Equus and Equestrian Sport Foundation and others will demonstrate how to care for horses, from hoof to mane.
19791	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Storytellers will share horse tales.
19792	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Children can try on equestrian clothing, and two equine ambulances -- one vintage and one contemporary -- will be on view.
19793	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	Thumbelina, considered to be the world's smallest horse, at a shade more than 17 inches high, will make a personal appearance, as will members of the New York City Parks Enforcement Patrol Mounted Auxiliary Unit.
19794	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	If it rains, all will be canceled except Thumbelina's appearance, which will move indoors.
19795	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	"The Horse" will be on view through Jan. 4 and requires timed tickets ($22
19796	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	$16.50 for students and 60+
19797	NYT_ENG_20080515.0125.LDC2009T13	$13 for 12 and younger).
