19901	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	Clem McSpadden, known as the voice of professional rodeo, his Oklahoma intonations a familiar presence through six decades as the sport grew from a rural pastime to a spectacle showcased in Las Vegas, died July 7 in Houston.
19902	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden, also a former U.S. congressman and an Oklahoma state legislator, was 82.
19903	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	His death, at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, was announced by the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association.
19904	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden, who lived in Chelsea, Okla., was a past president of the association.
19905	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden was a grand-nephew of the humorist Will Rogers and grew up on a ranch in Oologah, Okla., that was owned by Rogers and managed by McSpadden's father, Herb.
19906	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden displayed a dry wit in his own right when comparing his dual callings of rodeo and politics.
19907	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	Last January, when the post office in Chelsea, Okla., was renamed in his honor, McSpadden was quoted by The Tulsa World as observing how "there's an amazing correlation between the two arenas in that there's bull in each profession."
19908	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden was competing as a professional rodeo performer while a student at Oklahoma A&amp
19909	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	amp
19910	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	M (now Oklahoma State) when he filled in as an announcer at an Iowa rodeo in 1947.
19911	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He earned $100 for four nights of announcing and $286 for winning the calf roping.
19912	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He went on to become general manager of the National Finals Rodeo in Oklahoma City for almost two decades before it left for Las Vegas in the mid-1980s.
19913	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He announced rodeos in 41 states and was the first American to be the voice of Canada's prominent Calgary Stampede.
19914	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He was a rodeo announcer for A "Wide World of Sports" in the 1960s.
19915	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	"There are very few people who you can say really made rodeo, and he is one of them," Shawn Davis, general manager of the National Finals Rodeo, told the cowboys association.
19916	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	Early in his announcing career, McSpadden turned to politics.
19917	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	A Democrat, he was an Oklahoma state senator from 1955 to 1972, served one term in Congress, then gave up his seat to seek his party's gubernatorial nomination in 1974.
19918	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He was beaten in a runoff primary by David Boren, who won the general election.
19919	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	McSpadden operated a ranch near Chelsea, and he owned a lobbying firm in Oklahoma City.
19920	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	He is survived by his wife, Donna
19921	NYT_ENG_20080714.0027.LDC2009T13	his sons Bart and Paul
