20127	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	BP COMPROMISES ON RUSSIAN OIL VENTURE
20128	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	PARIS
20129	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	BP, the British energy company, agreed Thursday to replace the head of its Russian joint venture and surrender some control on the board to resolve a dispute with its billionaire Russian partners and hold on to its most important source of new oil reserves.
20130	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	Under the deal, the chief executive of the joint venture, Robert Dudley, an American, will step down by the end of the year, to be succeeded by "a Russian-speaking candidate with extensive Russian business experience" who will be nominated by BP.
20131	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	The new chief executive will be charged with improving "transparency, financial returns and the market value of the company's share."
20132	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	The deal, which is to be finalized over the next few months, calls for a reorganization of the TNK-BP board through the appointment of three new independent directors.
20133	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	That could help to end a deadlock in which the partners, each of which has five directors, were unable to agree on strategy.
20134	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	The companies also said they had agreed to an option for TNK-BP to sell up to 20 percent of its shares through an initial public offering, "subject to the consent of the Russian authorities."
20135	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	BP had been locked in a struggle with its four Russian partners, all billionaires, over control of the venture, in which BP and the billionaires' consortium each holds 50 percent.
20136	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	The Russian investors' side of the venture is called AAR, and consists of Viktor Vekselberg, Mikhail Fridman, German Khan and Leonid Blavatnik.
20137	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	Fridman, chairman of the TNK-BP Ltd. board, said in a statement released by AAR that the deal marked "an exciting new chapter in the development of a great company," adding: "As long-term investors, we are ambitious to see our joint venture with BP achieve great success."
20138	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	The BP chairman, Peter Sutherland, said in a separate statement that the deal would ease management conflicts by aligning shareholders' interests.
20139	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	"It will create a stable base from which to grow the joint venture to the benefit of everyone involved," Sutherland said, "including the Russian state for which strong capital investment and continued technical innovation to boost declining oil output are so important."
20140	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	Dudley, whose tenure at the top of the company had become increasingly tenuous, was denied a Russian work visa in July.
20141	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	He has continued to operate as chief executive from abroad.
20142	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	Robert Wine, a BP spokesman in London, said the deal in no way reflected badly on Dudley.
20143	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	"He's an exceptional CEO who's delivered everything that was expected of him and more," Wine said.
20144	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	Uncertainty over the venture has weighed on BP's stock for months, as it has accounted for nearly all of the growth in BP's oil reserves in recent years.
20145	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	On Thursday, BP shares rose 4.3 percent in early London trading.
20146	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	"We are pleased that this situation has been resolved and the shareholders have come to an agreement without the involvement of third parties, including the state," Igor Sechin, deputy prime minister of the Russian Federation, said in the AAR statement.
20147	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	"This is a positive signal for the Russian market.
20148	NYT_ENG_20080904.0049.LDC2009T13	We support the development of TNK-BP and believe that this company has excellent long-term prospects."
20149	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	MCCAIN FOCUSES ON BONUS PAY AND TUTORS
20150	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	In comparison with Sen. Barack Obama's education plan, Sen. John McCain's is terse.
20151	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Among his short list of initiatives, McCain, the Republican presidential nominee, includes bonus pay for teachers who raise student achievement or who take jobs in hard-to-staff schools, an expansion of after-school tutoring, and new federal support for online schools and for the voucher program in Washington, D.C.
20152	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	The brevity of McCain's plan reflects his view that the federal government should play a limited role in public education, and his commitment to holding the line on education spending, said Lisa Graham Keegan, a McCain adviser and former Arizona education commissioner.
20153	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	"Education is obviously not the issue Sen. McCain spends the most time on," Keegan said, adding that his plan's limited scope should not be interpreted as a lack of commitment to education and school reform.
20154	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	"He's been a quiet and consistent supporter of parents and educators who he thinks are making a difference."
20155	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	McCain would make it easier for students in failing schools to get taxpayer-financed after-school tutoring by private companies.
20156	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Under President Bush's No Child Left Behind law, students at schools that have repeatedly missed testing goals are eligible, but few parents nationwide have taken advantage of those services.
20157	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	That is because, in McCain's view, local school districts often set up a cumbersome process for certifying the tutors and do a poor job of getting the word out to parents.
20158	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Under McCain's plan, the federal government would certify tutoring companies, letting them market directly to parents.
20159	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Both the McCain and Obama plans acknowledge that the No Child Left Behind law has helped the nation focus on closing the achievement gap between minorities and whites, but they also promise changes to the law without offering many specifics.
20160	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	And both are silent on the law's deadline requiring that all students be proficient in reading and math by 2014.
20161	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Both plans also propose performance pay initiatives.
20162	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	McCain would reallocate 60 percent of the $3 billion in current federal spending on teacher quality programs to finance direct payments to "high-performing teachers" who take jobs in high-needs schools and to those who improve achievement.
20163	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Obama's plan would offer federal financing to districts that negotiate performance pay programs with teachers unions.
20164	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	It would allow bonuses for veteran teachers who help novice colleagues as well as those who teach in hard-to-staff schools or demonstrate high levels of performance.
20165	NYT_ENG_20080909.0108.LDC2009T13	Both national teachers' unions have endorsed Obama.
