20182	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	WASHINGTON
20183	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., the leader of Democratic Party efforts to gain Senate seats in the Nov. 4 elections, said Wednesday that polls show Democratic candidates leading in five states with incumbent Republican senators.
20184	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Schumer said polls indicate that his party's candidates are ahead in Virginia, New Mexico, Colorado, New Hampshire and Alaska, states now held by Republican senators.
20185	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Democratic candidates are also doing well in their Senate races in North Carolina and Oregon, Schumer said, and are close in Mississippi, Minnesota, Georgia and Kentucky.
20186	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	"We're doing extremely well in places we didn't expect to do well," Schumer, chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, told reporters on Wednesday, though he declined to predict how many seats he expects the party to win in November.
20187	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Schumer also maintained that it was "too early" to predict whether his party would end up with the 60 seats needed to block filibusters in the chamber.
20188	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	"The wind is more strongly at our back than ever," Schumer said.
20189	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	"We're doing better.
20190	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Where it ends up, I don't know."
20191	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	The DSCC raises and distributes campaign funds and recruits and advises candidates.
20192	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Schumer criticized the Chamber of Commerce, which he termed "a wing" of the Republican Senate campaign committee.
20193	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	The business group has donated money almost exclusively to Senate candidates, rather than House races or the presidential contest, Schumer said.
20194	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Schumer said the chamber has given over $16 million to Republican candidates this year but only $329,000 to their Democratic counterparts.
20195	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	In a statement responding to Schumer, R. Bruce Josten, the chamber's executive vice president of government affairs, said the organization is "pro-growth and pro-jobs" and supports candidates who work toward these aims.
20196	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	"It's a shame that Sen. Schumer would try to turn our pro-jobs, pro-growth agenda into a partisan issue for his campaign purposes -- especially at a time when our nation needs leadership and unity in Washington," Josten said.
20197	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	"The U.S. Chamber is focused on eliminating barriers to economic growth.
20198	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	To that end, we support candidates and policies that will reduce government waste, reduce taxes, and eliminate lawsuit abuse."
20199	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Democrats currently maintain a 51-49 advantage in the Senate -- a count that includes two independents: Sen. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt., and Sen. Joe Lieberman, I-Conn., who caucus with the Democrats and thus provide the margin of control of the Senate.
20200	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	Twenty-three of the 35 contested Senate seats on Nov. 4 are held by Republicans.
20201	NYT_ENG_20081008.0089.LDC2009T13	The last time a party gained the 60 seats required to block a filibuster was during the 95th Congress of 1977-1978, when the Democratic Party controlled 61 seats.
