20245	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	SHIPS ORDERED TO SLOW DOWN TO SAVE WHALES FOR SUNDAY, OCT. 26.
20246	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Cox News Service
20247	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	MELBOURNE, Fla. - The giant, lumbering right whales that winter along Florida's coastline will soon be protected by a new federally imposed speed limit on large ships, a victory for environmentalists in a long-running struggle.
20248	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	But the controversy over protecting the whales is far from over.
20249	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Some shipping industry representatives doubt the scientific studies underpinning the rule, which will lapse in five years if it is not renewed by federal regulators.
20250	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	The measure, which takes effect in December, calls for ships over 65 feet in length to slow to 10 knots in areas out to 20 miles offshore along the Eastern Seaboard where the whales congregate.
20251	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Environmental groups had asked the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration for a 30-mile slow-speed zone, but nevertheless hailed the new regulation.
20252	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"It's a huge step for the right whale," said Amy Knowlton, a research scientist at the New England Aquarium, which has studied the whales for decades.
20253	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"We're disappointed about some aspects of the rule, but it hasn't been so watered down that it won't be effective."
20254	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Don O'Hare, a spokesman for the World Shipping Council, a trade group that has been critical of the rule, said shippers will cooperate, even as they push for more studies and new technologies they hope will protect the whales without impeding shipping.
20255	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"While we have differences of opinion with NOAA on what the science says should be done to protect the right whales, the shipping industry respects their efforts and intentions with these new regulations," O'Hare said in an e-mailed response to the new agency rule.
20256	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Right whales, prized for their oil-rich blubber, were hunted nearly to extinction in the 1800s.
20257	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	The behemoths, which grow as large as 60 feet in length, were easy targets because of their slow movements, their preference for near-shore waters and the fact that their bodies floated after they were killed.
20258	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	They spend their summers off the New England coast, but females come south in winter to give birth off the coasts of Georgia and Florida.
20259	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Along Florida's coast from Jacksonville to Palm Beach, beach- goers are sometimes delighted to spot the whales during winter months just a few dozen yards off the shoreline.
20260	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	But many do more than simply watch
20261	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	a network of some 800 volunteers have been trained to call in whale sightings, with the information relayed to the Coast Guard, which passes the word to ships.
20262	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"When they see a whale they call us and once we get photographers to confirm it, we report it," said Julie Albert, coordinator of the right whale project for the Florida Marine Resources Council, a non-profit group based in Brevard County.
20263	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"The new speed limits will definitely be good for the whales.
20264	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	It's scary that there are so few of them left."
20265	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Protected by federal regulations for decades, the whales have still struggled to survive.
20266	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Between 1991 and 2002, 14 whales were confirmed victims of ship strikes, while 8 more died that way between 2002 and 2007.
20267	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Scientists say more whales may be killed by ships but their bodies never recovered.
20268	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	They also say entanglement in fishing lines is another menace threatening the species.
20269	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Researchers estimate there are about 300 to 400 right whales remaining.
20270	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Shippers say the new speed limits may cost them time and money while not being that effective.
20271	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Federal estimates say the limits should cost less than 1 percent of the $300 billion trade value of U.S. East Coast shipping, and should add only about an hour to the trip into port for most ships.
20272	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Edwin Fendig III, a harbor pilot in Brunswick, Ga., said ship captains do all they can to avoid the whales and want to see them survive, but worry that the speed limits will increase the danger of accidents.
20273	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"It's very unsafe for us to drive a ship at 10 knots," he said, noting that the Brunswick shipping channel is only 500 feet wide and holding a giant vessel on course in those confines in stormy weather is a challenge.
20274	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"We're extremely environmentally sensitive to the whales, but if cargo isn't brought into port in a safe and timely fashion, what will that cost the U.S.?"
20275	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	The federal rule allows an exception for ship captains to exceed the 10-knot limit if they deem it necessary for the safety of the vessel.
20276	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Researchers have developed high-tech buoys that aid in spotting the whales.
20277	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Teams from Cornell University and Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution have developed the devices, which listen for whale sounds with underwater hydro-phones and then relay the information by satellite, with the locations eventually passed on to ships.
20278	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	A network of the buoys is already deployed off parts of the New England coast, where the whales congregate in summer.
20279	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Two of the buoys were set off the Georgia coast near Brunswick last winter, and two will be placed this winter near the entrance to the Jacksonville port.
20280	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"The goal is to make all the information immediately available to shippers," said Chris Clark of Cornell's Bioacoustics Research Program.
20281	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Environmentalists, however, point out that the buoys are only effective if the whales are making sounds.
20282	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"It doesn't substitute for aerial surveys," the method used for decades to locate the whales, said Vicki Cornish of the Ocean Conservancy, an environmental group which pushed for the speed limits.
20283	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"And funding for the aerial surveys has been cut.
20284	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	We really think it's important these ships slow down.
20285	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	It's only for 20 miles."
20286	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	Cindy Dolaway, a retired teacher from New York who now lives in Brevard County and volunteers for the whale-spotting network, said many people don't know the whales spend part of their lives off the Florida coastline.
20287	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"It's really exciting to see them," she said.
20288	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	"I tell people they are the length of two school buses.
20289	NYT_ENG_20081021.0051.LDC2009T13	I've seen them right on the other side of the break off the beach."
