20564	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	MADOFF ' S METHOD
20565	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	How did he fool all those people?
20566	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	That question comes up every time a new investment con, especially any Ponzi-style scam, is exposed to the light of day.
20567	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	The Bernard Madoff case raises it one more time, along with a special sense of amazement.
20568	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	For one thing, the numbers (something between $24 billion and $50 billion from a long list of clients) are unprecedented.
20569	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	But the particular people and institutions who lost all that money by investing with Madoff are even more intriguing.
20570	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	The people at the head of the list are uniformly wealthy and sophisticated when it comes to money.
20571	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	The institutions - investment vehicles and private banks around the world - exist to protect their rich clients from hidden financial risk.
20572	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	These are the last people and organizations anyone would expect to get taken by an investment scam.
20573	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	It turns out they were attracted by one reliable element of most long-term investment scams.
20574	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Reports of consistently good but never spectacular gains can lull all kinds of investors into a false sense of security over time.
20575	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Though some Madoff investors are extremely wealthy, many others, like George Rautenberg of Lexington, are merely well-off.
20576	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Rautenberg, now 85, first invested with Madoff in 1992 and earned very steady returns over the next 16 years.
20577	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	He kept a close eye on the details of his account and believed Madoff's strategy would in fact produce the kinds of gains recorded.
20578	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	"They weren't outrageous compared with what Harvard was telling you they were doing and what all those other smart guys were doing," says Rautenberg, who invested after he and his brother sold their Boston manufacturing company.
20579	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	"He wasn't winning big at all in the good years.
20580	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	He stayed fairly stable."
20581	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	How stable?
20582	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Here are the annual returns Rautenberg's account earned over the past decade: 11.5 percent in 2007, 13.36 percent in 2006, 10 percent in 2005, 10.52 percent in 2004, 10.37 percent in 2003, 13.9 percent in 2002, and 14 percent in 2001.
20583	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Numbers like that have an obvious appeal, and they are a staple of modern Ponzi schemes.
20584	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Clients buy into the idea they are acting conservatively, choosing a manager who never swings for the fences, but still makes plenty of money for them.
20585	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	They believe they have chosen the responsible path and put their money in relatively safe hands.
20586	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Be honest: Wouldn't you?
20587	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Of course, there's more to it than that.
20588	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Big investment cons commonly penetrate tight social circles, and friends reinforce each other's faith in the person holding their money.
20589	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Hustler investment managers keep moving money, robbing Peter to pay Paul, until someone wants too much cash back and the whole con falls on its face.
20590	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	The lure of solid, low-risk returns appeal to rich and middle- class investors alike.
20591	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Clients who are savvy about money and those without much financial experience can feel the attraction.
20592	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	While FBI agents were arresting Madoff in New York Thursday, another financial con man was making his own court appearance in Boston.
20593	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Brad Bleidt was testifying in US District Court via teleconference from his current home, the Federal Correctional Institution in Fort Dix, N.J.
20594	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Bleidt is serving 11 years in prison for swindling more than 100 clients who lost $27 million in what passed for a notorious case at the time.
20595	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	He testified last week in a lawsuit brought by investors trying to squeeze money out of his old firm's bank, alleging it should have caught on to the scam.
20596	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	The money in the Bleidt case pales in comparison with the billions lost by people who invested with Madoff.
20597	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Most clients who gave Bleidt their money, sometimes their life savings, weren't rich and never claimed to be financial experts.
20598	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	But they heard a familiar story.
20599	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Bleidt kept clients happy with promises of the same kind of reliable, moderate returns.
20600	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	He told them not to expect to shoot the lights out.
20601	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	They were sold.
20602	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	No regulator or other outsider was paying very much attention to Brad Bleidt.
20603	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Lots of people looked closely at Bernie Madoff's business and some were skeptical, but no one stopped him.
20604	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Both were exposed the way all financial cons eventually end.
20605	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Sooner or later, too many people want their money back and it just isn't there.
20606	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	Steven Syre is a Globe columnist.
20607	NYT_ENG_20081216.0069.LDC2009T13	He can be reached at syre@globe.com.
