20851	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	FDA approves drug to prevent hepatitis B reinfection in liver transplant patients
20852	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua)
20853	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) on Friday announced the approval of HepaGam B for the prevention of hepatitis B reinfection in certain liver transplant patients.
20854	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	HepaGam B is the first product of its kind (an immune globulin product) approved for this purpose.
20855	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	Hepatitis B is a serious disease caused by a virus that attacks the liver and can cause lifelong infection, liver cancer, liver failure and death.
20856	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	Liver transplant patients who have already been exposed to the hepatitis B virus (HBV) are at an increased risk of reinfection because they have weakened immune systems.
20857	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	"This approval provides a new treatment option for the reduction of hepatitis B recurrence in liver transplant patients with a prior history of this serious disease," said Jesse Goodman, director of FDA's Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research. "
20858	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	It is the first immune globulin product -- one of several classes of proteins derived from human plasma -- approved for this use."
20859	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	HepaGam B works by providing an immediate immune response to the virus.
20860	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	This immunity protects patients previously exposed to HBV.
20861	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	Patients must receive injections at the time of their liver transplant and throughout their lives.
20862	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	This product is manufactured from human plasma collected at U.S. licensed plasma centers from healthy donors.
20863	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	FDA based its approval on the company's clinical data in a study of HBV-infected persons undergoing full liver transplants, which showed a reduction in the virus recurrence rate from 86 percent to about 13 percent.
20864	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	Adverse reactions were similar to other immune globulin products for other indications and included headache and hypertension.
20865	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	In January 2006, FDA licensed HepaGam B to prevent infection with HBV for the following other purposes: after acute exposure to blood or certain body fluids containing HBV
20866	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	perinatal exposure of infants to mothers previously exposed to HBV
20867	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	sexual exposure to persons previously exposed to HBV
20868	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	and household exposure to persons with acute HBV infection.
20869	XIN_ENG_20070406.0236.LDC2009T13	HepaGam B is manufactured by Cangene Corp. of Winnipeg, Canada.
