21143	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Roundup: EU seeks to clinch deal on institutional reform
21144	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	LISBON, Oct. 17 (Xinhua)
21145	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	European Union (EU) leaders meet in Lisbon on Thursday and Friday to try to agree on the text of a draft treaty after years of debate over institutional reform of the 27-nation bloc.
21146	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	At the informal summit, hosted annually by the incumbent EU president in autumn, national leaders will look at the Reform Treaty prepared by the intergovernmental conference (IGC) according to the guidelines set out by the leaders after a marathon meeting in June.
21147	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	The treaty will replace the controversial Constitutional Treaty, which was signed by EU states in 2004 but was permanently frozen after French and Dutch voters gave it a thumbs-down in 2005.
21148	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	The new treaty, hammered out by EU legal experts earlier this month, is expected to make the EU's decision-making mechanism more efficient yet more democratic, and to accelerate integration in Europe.
21149	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	The EU's successive enlargements in recent years have made the body increasingly difficult to run smoothly.
21150	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	TIME TO MOVE ON
21151	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	"We need the EU to speak with the single strong voice to deliver global leadership.
21152	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	We need more efficient and democratic decision-making to deliver policy results that benefit our citizens," Jose Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, the executive arm of the EU, said Wednesday.
21153	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	"We need to put this institutional debate behind us.
21154	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	We have spent six years discussing the institutional architecture.
21155	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	It is time to move on," he said.
21156	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	After two years of reviewing the fate of the EU constitution, and months of intense negotiations among member states since the beginning of this year, Barroso believes the current draft treaty "is the best deal that is on offer."
21157	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	"There are no reasons, no excuses not to solve this issue this week," he said.
21158	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	TREATY REVISED
21159	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Unlike the constitution, which was meant to replace all earlier EU treaties and start afresh, the Reform Treaty is designed to amend the Treaty on the European Union (the Maastricht Treaty) and the Treaty Establishing the European Community (the Rome Treaty).
21160	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	It also scraps all reference to EU symbols - the flag, the anthem and the motto, and shies away from any phrase which smacks of "a European Superstate."
21161	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Hence the title "constitution," which is loathed by many skeptical EU citizens, is dropped.
21162	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	However, the new treaty retains many of the changes the constitution attempted to introduce.
21163	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	They include:
21164	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- a president of the European council who would serve a two-and-a half-year term.
21165	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	This would replace the current system of a rolling six-month presidency
21166	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- an EU higher representative for foreign and security policy.
21167	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	This would combine the jobs of foreign affairs chief Javier Solana and External Affairs Commissioner Benita Ferrero-Waldner
21168	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- reducing the size of the European Commission, from 27 commissioners to 18, from 2014
21169	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- introducing double majority rule for Council decisions in 2014: proposed EU legislation requiring a qualified majority needs to muster the support of 55 percent of member states and of 65 percent of the EU's population.
21170	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	But, in a concession to Poland, member states will be able to invoke the old system until 2017
21171	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- a redistribution of voting weights between the member states, phased in between 2014 and 2017
21172	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- new powers for the European commission, European parliament and European court of justice, in areas such as justice and home affairs
21173	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	- the removal of the national veto in a number of policy areas.
21174	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Put simply, the new treaty is widely seen as having preserved the main substance of the constitution.
21175	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	STICKING POINTS
21176	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Squabbling over the new treaty never seems to end.
21177	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Poland, Britain, Italy and Austria are among those member states which have their own issues.
21178	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Poland, which holds elections on Oct. 21, wants a future EU voting mechanism that would allow EU decisions to be frozen temporarily when a minority of member nations disagree.
21179	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Poland, which claims that the new treaty would give bigger member states more leverage than before, said the decision-blocking mechanism, or the Ioannina clause, should be written into the treaty.
21180	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Until now it is written in a declaration which has no legal standing.
21181	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	London negotiated complex opt-outs on police and judicial cooperation and from the Charter of Fundamental Rights.
21182	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Poland also chose not to be bound by the Charter of Fundamental Rights.
21183	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Italy disputes a decision on how EU parliamentary seats should be distributed.
21184	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	According to the new rules, Rome's seats should be cut from 78 to 72 in 2009, the biggest drop among member states.
21185	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Austria, which complains about a big influx of German students in its medical schools, demands certain limits on the number of foreign students who could be enrolled in its universities.
21186	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	FATE OF TREATY UNKNOWN
21187	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Although there are still points to settle, some EU officials are optimistic about the prospect of a successful summit.
21188	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	French Foreign Minister Bernard Kouchner said Monday that all the differences among member states are minor and EU leaders will conclude the meeting within 30 minutes.
21189	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	But others are more cautious.
21190	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	They say that it is not uncommon for member states to raise new demands in the eleventh hour and capsize the boat.
21191	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Even if the draft is approved at this meeting, the Reform Treaty will not be signed right away, said Portugal, which holds the EU presidency.
21192	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	The informal meeting is just an opportunity for heads of state to see the results of legal work carried out on the treaty over the autumn.
21193	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	Hopefully, it will be signed by member states at the formal summit in Brussels in December.
21194	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	After that, the treaty need to be ratified by each of the 27 member states before it becomes a legally binding document.
21195	XIN_ENG_20071017.0453.LDC2009T13	EU leaders want the treaty in place ahead of next European Parliament elections scheduled for 2009.
