21839	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	and a new title -- Olympic champion.
21840	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	"I love winning.
21841	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	It is good feeling to me," he beamed after bagging the Olympic champion, showing a pair of lovely canine teeth.
21842	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	SHOOTING NOVICE
21843	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	Hancock started shooting at the age of eight, when his shooter father Craig asked, "Do you want to try shooting'?
21844	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	"Why not?"
21845	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	he said.
21846	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	A diligent shooter, every day he shot around four or five 25-shell boxes of ammunition on the skeet field created by his dad.
21847	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	After that he did other routines that helped keep his mind sharp and his body in good form, including push-ups, pull-ups, sit-ups and dips, as well as relaxation and visualization exercises on his living room floor.
21848	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	Three years later, the boy began appearing in competitions.
21849	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	In 2005, he debuted in international arena, grabbing the gold medal in Changwon World Cup with a surprising 149 hits, when everybody was wondering who the kid was.
21850	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	However, Hancock considered that competition hardest in his life.
21851	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	"I focused on nothing but the targets," he said.
21852	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	He started seven times that year in international tournament, taking a medal each time as the first shooter ever to do so, and was hence awarded as shooter of the year.
21853	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	IMPORTANT YEAR
21854	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	In 2006 the boy did two things.
21855	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	One was quitting competitions to join the armed force, where he was supposed to "train soldiers how to shoot".
21856	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	Founded in 1956, the shooting squad of the U.S. armed force has produced many ace shooters.
21857	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	To date, its members have achieved 21 Olympic medals.
21858	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	The team members trained five days a week and five to six hours a day.
21859	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	Like real soldiers, they received psychological drill as well as physical, while psychology is important in shooting competitions.
21860	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	"I learned a lot from the army, like determination, perseverance and discipline," he said, adding that this was helpful in his shooting career.
21861	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	As his coach Lloyd Woodhouse saw it, joining the army could put many ace shooters together for them to compare with each other and improve.
21862	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	"When you train alone, you can work really hard, but you don't know where your problems are," he said.
21863	XIN_ENG_20080816.0437.LDC2009T13	The other thing Hancock did was meeting Rebekah who was from a nurse school.
